>the DJ table thingie, but i dunno if he played any live tracks... ummm..

>Dope... got it on the raga @ 1st, went hard, then played breakcore, & he
>cut off his hair!!!  Oh my gosh.. no more dreads!!!  I think there was
>some1 else b4 him.. i 4got...

>next, busted out like kinda more rougher kinda like ummm... more funky...

> > >> > I was pretty hyped up about the love parade, and unlike most thing=

> > >> > that I get hyped up about, I wasn't let down. It truly blew my
> mind.
> > >> >
> > >> > I danced for over 10 hours, walked more then 10 miles, saw
> > >> > people having sex
> > >> > people doing drugs directly in front of cops
> > >> > pregnant women dancing
> > >> > naked people
> > >> > fire yellow glow sticks flying up over the crowds
> > >> > Asian girls in Japanese school girl outfits
> > >> > people on stilts
> > >> >
> > >> > but most importantly
> > >> >
> > >> > I saw the sun set and the sun rise in city.
> > >> >
> > >> > Here is the story in a stream of consciousness type of way:
> > >> >
> > >> > thursday: bought an 8oz bottle of Robitussin Max strength and dran=
k
> > >> > half of it. Called up all my friends to see who wanted to go with
> me
> > >> > ---> no go, everyone was busy. So alone I was going to be. But no
> > >> > problem, I figured I have friends that will be there so I was just
> > >> > gonna try to find them there.
> > >> >
> > >> > Friday: Emptied the rest of the tussin and drilled a hole in the
> cap
> > >> > where I threaded it on a lanyard (those VIP looking things that go
> > >> > around your neck). I couldn't drink it because I wanted to not be
> > >> > fucked up for Saturday, especially if there was any chance that I
> > >> > could score something better.
> > >> >
> > >> > Saturday: Hopped on Bart in Fremont at around 1:00pm. Arrived in
> San
> > >> > Francisco around 2, but got off on the wrong exit on Market becaus=
e
> I
> > >> > couldn't remember where the parade ended, only where it started
> (2nd
> > >> > and Market). So I walked all the way down, past the anti-war
> protest,
> > >> > with my tussin bottle around my neck made my way in front of the
> Civic
> > >> > center. First float I hung out at was
> > >> >
> > >> > the Tantra psytrance/goa float.
> > >> >
> > >> > It was packed and lovely. Lots of interesting people here, but I
> was
> > >> > far too sober to be listening to it so I moved on.
> > >> >
> > >> > the Breaks float
> > >> >
> > >> > where there were people break dancing on linoleum. It was awesome.
> One
> > >> > guy had fairy boots on with a bike visor and he was break dancing
> in
> > >> > them. Really good I might add. I hung out there for a good hour or
> so
> > >> > then went over to
> > >> >
> > >> > The Pure Future float
> > >> >
> > >> > To try to meet up with some friends from the progressive world,
> > >> > xtcradio.com <http://xtcradio.com>, and watch James Lauer spin. Th=
e
> crowd was pretty small,
> > >> > but they were deeply into the music. He spun a near perfect
> > >> > progressive set and there was some very old lady (75+ yo) there
> > >> > completely loving it. Next I made my way to the
> > >> >
> > >> > Bay Area DnB float
> > >> >
> > >> > hoping to find some friends, and I did. Osby and Adrianna were
> there.
> > >> > So I finally wasn't a loner. We made our way back to
> > >> >
> > >> > the Breaks float
> > >> >
> > >> > where I got handed a free mini keg and by that point I was fairly
> > >> > drunk. We danced for awhile and walked around some and then
> Adrianna
> > >> > had to go and Osby had his work to do, so I was off by myself
> again.
> > >> > Hoping to meet up with some tranceaddict.com<http://tranceaddict.c=
om>friends I headed over to
> > >> >
> > >> > the Spundae float
> > >> >
> > >> > and made it just in time for Carl Cox'es set. He really got that
> crowd
> > >> > worked up into a frenzy. I found myself the perfect spot to spend
> the
> > >> > rest of the Love Parade. Ferry Corsten came on and proved himself
> to
> > >> > be the best DJ of the day. As the sun set behind the capital
> building
> > >> > in the clear blue sky Ferry pounded out some of the best tracks an=
d
> > >> > the crowd seemed to be linked with a common bond to the music. The
> > >> > lights turned on, and everyone had their hands in the air. No need
> for
> > >> > air condioning with the cool, sweet ocean air, the melodic
> breakdowns
> > >> > of the trance had everyone with their arms in the air and chills
> down
> > >> > their spine. I was practically moved to tears in the beauty of the
> > >> > event. So perfect, and I wasn't even drunk anymore at that point.
> > >> > Notable track: 808State - cubik remix. Light turned to dark, the
> civic
> > >> > center was lit up with Red and Blue lights underneath the half mas=
t
> > >> > American Flags. It was almost 9pm and I was hoping to find Osby so
> I
> > >> > could see where he was going next, but searched and searched to no
> > >> > avail.
> > >> >
> > >> > The parade had ended and I found myself in a littered street
> sitting
> > >> > on a dirty curb with cops amassed on bicycles. No way was I going
> to
> > >> > pay $60 to get into the Spundae afterparty at the Civic center and
> I
> > >> > was suppose to meet a friend at the BADnB party at Studio Z at
> 10ish
> > >> > so I got directions and took a walk.
> > >> >
> > >> > Bay Area Drum and Bass Afterparty
> > >> >
> > >> > Studio Z was empty when I got there. No DJ was even playing yet, s=
o
> I
> > >> > stood outside for about an hour once it got somewhat going. I sat
> by
> > >> > the door, but my friend that said she was going to show up never
> came.
> > >> > So I went to plan B ( which always seems to work). I hit the bar
> and
> > >> > ordered a Grand mariner shot and a red bull and vodka. Quickly
> downed
> > >> > it, another red bull and vodka later I was starting to quite enjoy
> > >> > myself. Grabbed a few beers and started talking to two guys who
> were
> > >> > rolling. Had some great conversations until they decided that they
> > >> > couldn't sit still and needed to dance, neather could I. The drum
> and
> > >> > bass was going off. I'm not sure who was the DJ, but it was
> intense. I
> > >> > started getting tired around 1am and I wanted to catch Paul Van
> Dyk.
> > >> > Knowing that Bart doesn't have service from 12am to 8am I also kne=
w
> I
> > >> > needed a place to spend the night. So I walked to
> > >> >
> > >> > 1015.
> > >> >
> > >> > And made it just in time to be in the main room for Paul Van dyk's
> > >> > entire set. It was packed, but I didn't care, I was drunk as fuck
> and
> > >> > the music was spot on. I'm not sure what dj followed PVD, it was
> about
> > >> > 4am, so I ended up sleeping in a remote corner of the club until
> about
> > >> > 6am telling each and every security gaurd that I'm fine, and that
> I'm
> > >> > not K-holing or anything. At this time I went to the front room an=
d
> > >> > the dj was playing some really dark evil trance that I've never
> heard
> > >> > before. It was actually freaking me out. After his set was over I
> > >> > left, walked outside, saw the sun come up, walked to the bart
> station
> > >> > and hung out with bums until it opened up.
> > >> >
> > >> > Thanks! for the great time! Seriously, this was an event to
> remember.

Subject: [sfraves] a rose for emily.   october 2005 on sfraves

'a rose for emily'
squashed from formal publication
available only on SFRaves, during the witching season of Halloween week. 

“In his deepest madness since 1996, Boomerang exhumes the corpse of Faulkner, and the smell of
decay is sickening.  You will never again see the DJ with innocent eyes.”                    
   --  Portland Underground Review, August 2005
...............................
   
The world decayed, and the underground decayed with it. Saturday night after Saturday night.  
Corpses were found in bathrooms, in bedrooms, and in the sleeping arms of rave businessmen whose
pockets were fat with green.   

Some of our bodies waited days for discovery, until the stench became unbearable.

Postmodernism lost its irony.

Shit said howdy to the fan, and no pardons were granted.

> > >> > I was pretty hyped up about the love parade, and unlike most things

> mind.
> > >> >
> > >> > I danced for over 10 hours, walked more then 10 miles, saw
> > >> > people having sex
> > >> > people doing drugs directly in front of cops
> > >> > pregnant women dancing
> > >> > naked people
> > >> > fire yellow glow sticks flying up over the crowds
> > >> > Asian girls in Japanese school girl outfits
> > >> > people on stilts
> > >> >
> > >> > but most importantly
> > >> >
> > >> > I saw the sun set and the sun rise in city.
> > >> >
> > >> > Here is the story in a stream of consciousness type of way:
> > >> >
> > >> > thursday: bought an 8oz bottle of Robitussin Max strength and drank
> > >> > half of it. Called up all my friends to see who wanted to go with
> me
> > >> > ---> no go, everyone was busy. So alone I was going to be. But no
> > >> > problem, I figured I have friends that will be there so I was just
> > >> > gonna try to find them there.
> > >> >
> > >> > Friday: Emptied the rest of the tussin and drilled a hole in the
> cap
> > >> > where I threaded it on a lanyard (those VIP looking things that go
> > >> > around your neck). I couldn't drink it because I wanted to not be
> > >> > fucked up for Saturday, especially if there was any chance that I
> > >> > could score something better.
> > >> >
> > >> > Saturday: Hopped on Bart in Fremont at around 1:00pm. Arrived in
> San
> > >> > Francisco around 2, but got off on the wrong exit on Market because
> I
> > >> > couldn't remember where the parade ended, only where it started
> (2nd
> > >> > and Market). So I walked all the way down, past the anti-war
> protest,
> > >> > with my tussin bottle around my neck made my way in front of the
> Civic
> > >> > center. First float I hung out at was
> > >> >
> > >> > the Tantra psytrance/goa float.
> > >> >
> > >> > It was packed and lovely. Lots of interesting people here, but I
> was
> > >> > far too sober to be listening to it so I moved on.
> > >> >
> > >> > the Breaks float
> > >> >
> > >> > where there were people break dancing on linoleum. It was awesome.
> One
> > >> > guy had fairy boots on with a bike visor and he was break dancing
> in
> > >> > them. Really good I might add. I hung out there for a good hour or
> so
> > >> > then went over to
> > >> >
> > >> > The Pure Future float
> > >> >
> > >> > To try to meet up with some friends from the progressive world,
> > >> > xtcradio.com , and watch James Lauer spin. The
> crowd was pretty small,
> > >> > but they were deeply into the music. He spun a near perfect
> > >> > progressive set and there was some very old lady (75+ yo) there
> > >> > completely loving it. Next I made my way to the
> > >> >
> > >> > Bay Area DnB float
> > >> >
> > >> > hoping to find some friends, and I did. Osby and Adrianna were
> there.
> > >> > So I finally wasn't a loner. We made our way back to
> > >> >
> > >> > the Breaks float
> > >> >
> > >> > where I got handed a free mini keg and by that point I was fairly
> > >> > drunk. We danced for awhile and walked around some and then
> Adrianna
> > >> > had to go and Osby had his work to do, so I was off by myself
> again.
> > >> > Hoping to meet up with some tranceaddict.comfriends I headed over to
> > >> >
> > >> > the Spundae float
> > >> >
> > >> > and made it just in time for Carl Cox'es set. He really got that
> crowd
> > >> > worked up into a frenzy. I found myself the perfect spot to spend
> the
> > >> > rest of the Love Parade. Ferry Corsten came on and proved himself
> to
> > >> > be the best DJ of the day. As the sun set behind the capital
> building
> > >> > in the clear blue sky Ferry pounded out some of the best tracks and
> > >> > the crowd seemed to be linked with a common bond to the music. The
> > >> > lights turned on, and everyone had their hands in the air. No need
> for
> > >> > air condioning with the cool, sweet ocean air, the melodic
> breakdowns
> > >> > of the trance had everyone with their arms in the air and chills
> down
> > >> > their spine. I was practically moved to tears in the beauty of the
> > >> > event. So perfect, and I wasn't even drunk anymore at that point.
> > >> > Notable track: 808State - cubik remix. Light turned to dark, the
> civic
> > >> > center was lit up with Red and Blue lights underneath the half mast
> > >> > American Flags. It was almost 9pm and I was hoping to find Osby so
> I
> > >> > could see where he was going next, but searched and searched to no
> > >> > avail.
> > >> >
> > >> > The parade had ended and I found myself in a littered street
> sitting
> > >> > on a dirty curb with cops amassed on bicycles. No way was I going
> to
> > >> > pay $60 to get into the Spundae afterparty at the Civic center and
> I
> > >> > was suppose to meet a friend at the BADnB party at Studio Z at
> 10ish
> > >> > so I got directions and took a walk.
> > >> >
> > >> > Bay Area Drum and Bass Afterparty
> > >> >
> > >> > Studio Z was empty when I got there. No DJ was even playing yet, so
> I
> > >> > stood outside for about an hour once it got somewhat going. I sat
> by
> > >> > the door, but my friend that said she was going to show up never
> came.
> > >> > So I went to plan B ( which always seems to work). I hit the bar
> and
> > >> > ordered a Grand mariner shot and a red bull and vodka. Quickly
> downed
> > >> > it, another red bull and vodka later I was starting to quite enjoy
> > >> > myself. Grabbed a few beers and started talking to two guys who
> were
> > >> > rolling. Had some great conversations until they decided that they
> > >> > couldn't sit still and needed to dance, neather could I. The drum
> and
> > >> > bass was going off. I'm not sure who was the DJ, but it was
> intense. I
> > >> > started getting tired around 1am and I wanted to catch Paul Van
> Dyk.
> > >> > Knowing that Bart doesn't have service from 12am to 8am I also knew
> I
> > >> > needed a place to spend the night. So I walked to
> > >> >
> > >> > 1015.
> > >> >
> > >> > And made it just in time to be in the main room for Paul Van dyk's
> > >> > entire set. It was packed, but I didn't care, I was drunk as fuck
> and
> > >> > the music was spot on. I'm not sure what dj followed PVD, it was
> about
> > >> > 4am, so I ended up sleeping in a remote corner of the club until
> about
> > >> > 6am telling each and every security gaurd that I'm fine, and that
> I'm
> > >> > not K-holing or anything. At this time I went to the front room and
> > >> > the dj was playing some really dark evil trance that I've never
> heard
> > >> > before. It was actually freaking me out. After his set was over I
> > >> > left, walked outside, saw the sun come up, walked to the bart
> station
> > >> > and hung out with bums until it opened up.
> > >> >
> > >> > Thanks! for the great time! Seriously, this was an event to
> remember.

On Oct 4, 2005, at 10:56 AM, D D wrote:

> What are the differant ways you people out there refer to placing  
> pills into the anus?

"rectsasy", "booty bumpin", "the chocolate express", and "OH GOD IT  
BURNS".


> Pluggin Pills is pretty good, I've always refered to it as Booty  
> Bumpin'
> What are some other ways to describe this crazy act, and who all  
> has tried
> it? I know of a couple of people who did. One girl who actually  
> preferred
> that method and a guy friend who tried it and said his ass burned  
> all night.


i've done it 3 times.  it's always happened on those occasions where  
things have gotten so depraved that it doesn't seem like such a big  
deal (that, and nobody really remembers doing it).  i've convinced  
many people to try it though. that's always fun.

the trick to keeping the burning to a minimum is to make sure it gets  
way up there.  most people don't have fingers that long though, so  
getting help from someone else is key.

i can hear you all going "ewwwwww" right now. :-)

pxd

Some of you may have read this article or similar ones like it. The
mainstream media has shrugged aside LOADS of credible evidence that suggest
the 2004 presidential voting results are quite fishy, and most democrats in
office have put their tails between their legs in fear of shattering the
confidence that americans have in their so called "democracy." For those of
you who wonder why the exit polls (which are the gold standard to detect
fraud when the US/UN monitors other nations' elections like Yugoslavia,
Ukraine etc) didn't match up with the 2004 presidential results, along with
many other open seats on capital hill, the only plausible thing the polling
organizations could come up with was that kerry voters were more likely to
speak with the pollsters?! How's that for hard evidence. Below is a very
LONG, and in-depth article that uncovers the many irregularities surroundin=
g
the 2004 elections, you may surprised ;)
<http://www.projectcensored.org/newsflash/voter_fraud.html>

Oh yah, I don't have a problem with anybody disagreeing with this, but if
you plan to, you may want to read the entirety of this article first!


Here is the link to the article:
It won't let me send the entire thing on here :(

http://www.projectcensored.org/newsflash/voter_fraud.html



No Paper Trail Left Behind:
The Theft of the 2004 Presidential Election*

By Dennis Loo, Ph.D.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] 2004 Election Fraud

One thing I recall, is that kerry actually ended up technically
winning ohio and florida, but being as he QUIT at about 4am EST (I
remember this, because I was driving home from the bar and listening
to it on the radio), before all the votes were counted, it didn't
really matter. If he would have waited it out, he could have won those
states too.

>From an overall vote count, I believe bush did win though.

I remember reading a few articles on what scared people, what they
liked most about the candidates.

Kerry's #1 complaint was his lack of ability to take a firm stand on
any issue, which was viewed as a sign of weakness to the American
people. Even saturday night live made fun of this in november, while
the presidential debates were going on.
Bush's #1 complaint was that he didn't know what he was doing, and
that his tenacity towards his personal goals was going to tear the
United States apart.

Kerry's primary good point was his education and understanding of the law.
Bush's primary good point was his ability to take a stand, regardless
of whether or not it was right, and stick with it.

Personally, I'd rather have had Dean win the election. I thought he
was a better candidate than either of them. I dislike both Kerry and
Bush. He had charisma, intelligence, and leadership ability.
Apparently he also doesn't know how to use a unidirectional
microphone, but that's not his fault.

As for the election being rigged? doesn't matter. Kerry gave up before
the final tally came in anyhow. If you want to start screaming
conspiracy, start by pointing fingers at the guy who quit before the
votes were all in.

Anyhow, that's my .02

:)

Subject: Re: [sfraves] bounced back emails?

This list will bounce mail if:

- the message size is over 50K (Karina's calendar is almost always under 
50K)

- you are crossposting to more than 5 other addresses

- you have posted more than 20 times in one day

All 3 requirements have been raised in the last 6 months. I generally 
just react to collective feedback from you guys in adjusting the above 
requirements, so if you have any, shoot me an email.

-terry

Message-ID: <20051005181955.68749.qmail@web32415.mail.mud.yahoo.com>
Date: Wed, 5 Oct 2005 11:19:55 -0700 (PDT)
From: Peter Rothman <dangrsmind@yahoo.com>
To: Acid Totem <acidtotem@gmail.com>, sfraves <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
In-Reply-To: <642c2150510050830v553f6e04sd2b57f43cb2cf0a1@mail.gmail.com>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] 2004 Election Fraud

The problem with arguing that the exit polls show
election fraud is that you don't have sufficient
information to actually analyze the poll data. 
Without knowing the weighting function used by the
poll takers, you simply can't analyze the data.  This
is statistics 101 stuff.  Only the polling firm knows
that information and they apparently aren't going to
talk.  

This is the problem with having corporate control of
exit polling; the exit polls have become a
mulit-million dollar entertainment business.  They're
more of a play by play of the election, instead of a
means of verifying the election results.  And polling
firms have no interest in seeing the accuracy of their
polls questioned since it might jeopordize their
business.

Regards,

Peter

Peter in your comments regarding polling firms, like I said in the first
initial email I sent out. EXIT POLLS ARE THE GOLD STANDARD to determin the
POSSIBILITY of FRAUD. In fact, Exit Polls have time and time again proven t=
o
be the most precise counting of votes, aside from the actual vote tallies
them self- which is kind of hard to do when you don't have a papertrail! In
fact, exit polls are so strongly trusted, that Germany uses them to announc=
e
results for top political positions in their country, then the actual vote
counting precides the day[s] after to determine that everything is in line.
Time and time again the US and UN monitor elections in many nations
throughout the world, and what is their method to determine voting fraud,
EXIT POLLS. Of course you have your right to disagree, but did you read the
entire article? Don't you find it more than just a little strange that exit
polls matched up just about everywhere except for battle ground states alon=
g
with open seats on capital hill. How is it in the places where electronic
voting took place, but no paper trail was left, that Bush + cronies
exceeded, 100%, 200%, even 300% of the registered republicans in such a
district. How does Bush overwhelmingly take counties in florida in blue
district strongholds with over 80%+ registered democrats by a substantial
margin? And why do irregularites occur time and time again in swing states
in districts that have electronic voting machines THAT LEAVE NO PAPER TRAIL=
.
Kerry giving up the fight is his own decision. But it is the right of the
American People to have what is promised to them in their constition. Just
like 9-11, we are left with a plethora of unaswered questions, and I begin
to wonder if thesethey will ever be addressed by anyone in political office=
,
and if then it is, will anyone else listen?

> election fraud is that you don't have sufficient
> information to actually analyze the poll data.
> Without knowing the weighting function used by the
> poll takers, you simply can't analyze the data. This
> is statistics 101 stuff. Only the polling firm knows
> that information and they apparently aren't going to
> talk.
>
> This is the problem with having corporate control of
> exit polling; the exit polls have become a
> mulit-million dollar entertainment business. They're
> more of a play by play of the election, instead of a
> means of verifying the election results. And polling
> firms have no interest in seeing the accuracy of their
> polls questioned since it might jeopordize their
> business.

  b=b0ciA7HRYesUdYsvvoajcrYVwpaFq1sWxFk0amarypCKX0LAVbBvmxMCJvxhnDIidQWzwJHFFVTu0WSaxgTPgboUrHzyHtXxwetVLiKi0qcFM5cDsMc5mu3mnvM1azwGuPi7JFmiHWQP0PFExGqFlSrUn2i28GxncysW2COzoQI=  ;
Message-ID: <20051005203720.85719.qmail@web32403.mail.mud.yahoo.com>
Date: Wed, 5 Oct 2005 13:37:20 -0700 (PDT)
From: Peter Rothman <dangrsmind@yahoo.com>
To: Acid Totem <acidtotem@gmail.com>
Cc: sfraves <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
In-Reply-To: <642c2150510051251v44c65764y6ab7656833348b5c@mail.gmail.com>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] 2004 Election Fraud

Do any of the nations you mentioned previously  have
exclusive corporate control over exit polling?  Or are
the polls conducted by various groups of citizens and
not for profit organizations?  

The exit polls in America are controlled by a single
corporation and are really about making the election
exciting to watch on TV, not checking the election
results for fraud.  It strikes me as simply irrational
to expect a corporation that profits from the
spectacle of the election to have any interest in
undermining their main source of revenue by disclosing
the flaws in their polling procedure.  

In order to determine that the exit polls results
disagreed with the election results you need to know
the weighting function used by the poll takers.  This
is because exit polls use highly biased samples. 
Without the weights, we can't extrapolate from the raw
poll results to the sampled population.  Since the
polling corporation has refused to disclose this
information we're left guessing.  

Maybe there was election fraud, and maybe there
wasn't.  I'm not arguing there wasn't.  But the exit
polls can't tell you without the weighting function. 
I'm not arguing against you here, just pointing out
that knowledge of unweighted exit polling results
can't prove anything.  Its just the way that the math
works out.

Regards,

Peter

P.S. If they can fix elections,

A couple excerpts from a link in the article below titled "Pratical Uses of Pee,"  http://www.rotten.com/library/medicine/bodily-functions/pissing/practical-uses/  
 

>>>Cheese making 
Although not a common practice, the addition of urine to cheese-making has been known to make a richer, more piquant cheese, highly sought after by those who've tasted it. 

 

>>>Curing Tobacco 
While it's hard to tell how extensive this practice really was, it is documented that at least some folks found that hanging their tobacco in the outhouse mellowed it and, oddly enough, lessened the stink it created when burned (as in a gentleman's after dinner cigar). Go figure. 
Information about the origin of this practice is sketchy. But it is intriguing to note that the 1771 edition of Encyclopædia Britannica instructs that "A strong decoction of the stalks, with sharp-pointed dock and alum, is said to be of good service, used externally, in cutaneous distempers, especially the itch: some boil them for that purpose in urine. The same is said to be infallible in curing the mange in dogs." We can only speculate whether some accidental steaming of tobacco, during such medicinal concocting, might have led to the discovery of the value of urine fumes. Or then again, perhaps someone was simply hiding his smoke in the outhouse and noticed the subsequent improvement. 


 

>>>Hair Shampoo 
Believe it or not, you can make your hair cleaner by dousing it with urine. Kinda takes those "shower" games you tried to a whole new level doesn't it? I think we can figure out how this one was invented. 
The more intriguing part is actually how it works. It turns out that urine shares some similar chemical properties with soap and detergent. Highly alkaline, urine can cut through greasy build-up and leave hair, dare we say it, "softer and more manageable". 
Naturally the whole process provides more pleasant smelling hair (according to modern standards) if combined with warm water rinsing and, better yet, a sudsy plant product such as soap root. 

 
 
And much, much more! Who would have thought?
 
Rgds,
 
Chuck

Subject: Re: [sfraves]gone to hell, with fish hooks to correct the booty bumps



One night Chester decided to booty bump it, right before his set (he was booked the 1 to 3 slot). 
 Only problem was, it was an oval shaped pill and he launched it at a bad angle.  He could neither
come nor go.   You know how it is, like a vitamin C that doesn't hit your throat right.

It was important he had his things together by 1:00, but this was causing some problems.  Not to
mention his records weren't in order yet.  

Fortunately, Ryan had just gone fishing that day down at the Berkeley marina, and still had his
gear with him.   Delia had this brilliant plan that if we could launch one of Ryan’s hooks up in
there (tenderly, of course),   we could snag the pill and give it a soft tug to straighten it out.

It worked so brilliantly.

Only problem was, Chester tends to get all sissy and squeal like a little schoolgirl if concerned
friends try to work a fish hook up in there.   So there was a lot of wriggling and miscalculations
and arguing about how to do it right.   It took three chicks just to keep the pillow stuffed in
his mouth.   Mind you, Ryan had no lure and no lead weights to make it easier.     Ryan’s tackle
box really ain’t all that, in retrospect, if you think about everything Chester went through that
night.

We snagged a little skin, and Chester wasn’t exactly calm as we straightened out the mislodged
pill, but he managed to pull off a banging set that night.

word is bond,
boom

Subject: [sfraves] Good Cause: Katrina Disaster Relief Benefit

Dear SFRaves Community:

I along with many others who have donated our time and services have been 
working very hard to ensure the success of this benefit, please come down 
and dance with us for a Good Cause... Thank you :) <3 Karina

Friday, October 7th, 2005, Good Cause: Katrina Benefit

Brought to you by Evil Breaks, Karina, Get Yer Freak On, Mighty, Opel 
Productions, Seismic, Sister SF, SFBreaks.org, & Mighty, this event is a 
non-profit benefit for Hurricane Katrina Disaster Relief.

So please, come out and support a worthy cause and dance your ass off to 
some of the best music San Francisco has to offer.

A collaborative effort with many Special thanks to DJ Garth, DJ Tracy, 
Compression, Get Your Freak On, Grayhound, Evil Breaks, Hyperreal, Madame 
Mercury and Mad Wax/NYCBreaks, Mighty, Opel Productions, Pacific Sound, 
Rhythm Method, Seismic, SFBreaks, SFRaves.org,
Simply Jeff, Sister SF, Sleeveless, Subscience, Thump Radio, Violence, DJ 
Jeno (Wicked), Psybertribe, Violence Recordings and all involved.

Located @ Mighty (119 Utah St.), San Francisco, CA
$5 presales available @ Mighty119.com

http://www.groovetickets.com/OrderSystem/groove/eventviewqb.asp?affilid=93&EventsID=187
14&PGName=Mighty+Presents

$10 @ the door
10pm-5am

We would like to thank all the DJS and individuals who donated their time 
to ensure the success of this benefit. THANK YOU.

On 10/5/05, Peter Rothman <dangrsmind@yahoo.com> wrote:
>
> Do any of the nations you mentioned previously have
> exclusive corporate control over exit polling? Or are
> the polls conducted by various groups of citizens and
> not for profit organizations?
>
> The exit polls in America are controlled by a single
> corporation and are really about making the election
> exciting to watch on TV, not checking the election
> results for fraud. It strikes me as simply irrational
> to expect a corporation that profits from the
> spectacle of the election to have any interest in
> undermining their main source of revenue by disclosing
> the flaws in their polling procedure.
>
> In order to determine that the exit polls results
> disagreed with the election results you need to know
> the weighting function used by the poll takers. This
> is because exit polls use highly biased samples.
> Without the weights, we can't extrapolate from the raw
> poll results to the sampled population. Since the
> polling corporation has refused to disclose this
> information we're left guessing.
>
> Maybe there was election fraud, and maybe there
> wasn't. I'm not arguing there wasn't. But the exit
> polls can't tell you without the weighting function.
> I'm not arguing against you here, just pointing out
> that knowledge of unweighted exit polling results
> can't prove anything. Its just the way that the math
> works out.
>

>

A papertrail is a paper printout from the electronic voting machine. This
has nothing to do with the polling company. Luckily, in the state of
california we have voting machines that provide a paper printout once your
vote has been casted- so that your vote is not lost in the cyberspace of th=
e
electoral college. So if need there be an audit on the vote, we have a
papertrail which can be counted. Millions of electronic voting machines in
the 2004 did not have paper printouts. So who's to say if you voted on one
of these machines, that your vote was really counted for who you voted. Wha=
t
kind of proof would you have to reassure you that your vote wasn't thrown
out, or altogether changed, by error or by intention?

On 10/5/05, John Dee <antitux@gmail.com> wrote:
>
> well, technically speaking, it's up to the company who did the
> electronic voting to give the paper trail.
>
> Good luck on that one. I think they went out of business on account of

>
> Regardless, Kerry still won ohio and florida when all was said and
> done, and if he hadn't quit, he'd be our president right now.
>
>

> districts
> > that leave a papertrail, and in districts in swing states (new mexico,
> ohio,
> > florida) that use electronic voting with no papertrail, many exit polls
> were
> > well beyond the +/- statistical error always in favor of bush? What can
> the
> > polling company do to explain why their polls match up when the paper i=
s
> > there, but is wrong, often times in excess of 10% points when the

> > is not there....???

> > On 10/5/05, Peter Rothman <dangrsmind@yahoo.com> wrote:
> > >
> > > Do any of the nations you mentioned previously have
> > > exclusive corporate control over exit polling? Or are
> > > the polls conducted by various groups of citizens and
> > > not for profit organizations?
> > >
> > > The exit polls in America are controlled by a single
> > > corporation and are really about making the election
> > > exciting to watch on TV, not checking the election
> > > results for fraud. It strikes me as simply irrational
> > > to expect a corporation that profits from the
> > > spectacle of the election to have any interest in
> > > undermining their main source of revenue by disclosing
> > > the flaws in their polling procedure.
> > >
> > > In order to determine that the exit polls results
> > > disagreed with the election results you need to know
> > > the weighting function used by the poll takers. This
> > > is because exit polls use highly biased samples.
> > > Without the weights, we can't extrapolate from the raw
> > > poll results to the sampled population. Since the
> > > polling corporation has refused to disclose this
> > > information we're left guessing.
> > >
> > > Maybe there was election fraud, and maybe there
> > > wasn't. I'm not arguing there wasn't. But the exit
> > > polls can't tell you without the weighting function.
> > > I'm not arguing against you here, just pointing out
> > > that knowledge of unweighted exit polling results
> > > can't prove anything. Its just the way that the math
> > > works out.
> > >
> > > Regards,

machines that don't produce papertrails.

> > > that leave a papertrail, and in districts in swing states (new mexico=

> > ohio,
> > > florida) that use electronic voting with no papertrail, many exit
> > polls were
> > > well beyond the +/- statistical error always in favor of bush? What
> > can the
> > > polling company do to explain why their polls match up when the paper
> > is
> > > there, but is wrong, often times in excess of 10% points when the
> > papertrail
> > > is not there....???
> > >
> > > On 10/5/05, Peter Rothman <dangrsmind@yahoo.com > wrote:
> > > >
> > > > Do any of the nations you mentioned previously have
> > > > exclusive corporate control over exit polling? Or are
> > > > the polls conducted by various groups of citizens and
> > > > not for profit organizations?
> > > >
> > > > The exit polls in America are controlled by a single
> > > > corporation and are really about making the election
> > > > exciting to watch on TV, not checking the election
> > > > results for fraud. It strikes me as simply irrational
> > > > to expect a corporation that profits from the
> > > > spectacle of the election to have any interest in
> > > > undermining their main source of revenue by disclosing
> > > > the flaws in their polling procedure.
> > > >
> > > > In order to determine that the exit polls results
> > > > disagreed with the election results you need to know
> > > > the weighting function used by the poll takers. This
> > > > is because exit polls use highly biased samples.
> > > > Without the weights, we can't extrapolate from the raw
> > > > poll results to the sampled population. Since the
> > > > polling corporation has refused to disclose this
> > > > information we're left guessing.
> > > >
> > > > Maybe there was election fraud, and maybe there
> > > > wasn't. I'm not arguing there wasn't. But the exit
> > > > polls can't tell you without the weighting function.
> > > > I'm not arguing against you here, just pointing out
> > > > that knowledge of unweighted exit polling results
> > > > can't prove anything. Its just the way that the math
> > > > works out.
> > > >
> > > > Regards,
> > > >
> > > > Peter
> > > >
> > > > P.S. If they can fix elections,
> > > >
> > > > --- Acid Totem <acidtotem@gmail.com > wrote:
> > > >

> > > > > I said in the first
> > > > > initial email I sent out. EXIT POLLS ARE THE GOLD
> > > > > STANDARD to determin the
> > > > > POSSIBILITY of FRAUD. In fact, Exit Polls have time
> > > > > and time again proven to
> > > > > be the most precise counting of votes, aside from
> > > > > the actual vote tallies
> > > > > them self- which is kind of hard to do when you
> > > > > don't have a papertrail! In

> > > > > Germany uses them to announce
> > > > > results for top political positions in their
> > > > > country, then the actual vote
> > > > > counting precides the day[s] after to determine that
> > > > > everything is in line.
> > > > > Time and time again the US and UN monitor elections
> > > > > in many nations
> > > > > throughout the world, and what is their method to
> > > > > determine voting fraud,

> > > > > with open seats on capital hill. How is it in the
> > > > > places where electronic
> > > > > voting took place, but no paper trail was left, that
> > > > > Bush + cronies
> > > > > exceeded, 100%, 200%, even 300% of the registered
> > > > > republicans in such a
> > > > > district. How does Bush overwhelmingly take counties
> > > > > in florida in blue
> > > > > district strongholds with over 80%+ registered
> > > > > democrats by a substantial
> > > > > margin? And why do irregularites occur time and time
> > > > > again in swing states
> > > > > in districts that have electronic voting machines
> > > > > THAT LEAVE NO PAPER TRAIL.
> > > > > Kerry giving up the fight is his own decision. But
> > > > > it is the right of the

> > > > > their constition. Just

> > > > > and if then it is, will anyone else listen?
> > > > > On 10/5/05, Peter Rothman < dangrsmind@yahoo.com>
> > > > > wrote:
> > > > >
> > > > > > The problem with arguing that the exit polls show
> > > > > > election fraud is that you don't have sufficient
> > > > > > information to actually analyze the poll data.
> > > > > > Without knowing the weighting function used by the
> > > > > > poll takers, you simply can't analyze the data.
> > > > > This
> > > > > > is statistics 101 stuff. Only the polling firm
> > > > > knows
> > > > > > that information and they apparently aren't going
> > > > > to
> > > > > > talk.
> > > > > >
> > > > > > This is the problem with having corporate control
> > > > > of
> > > > > > exit polling; the exit polls have become a
> > > > > > mulit-million dollar entertainment business.
> > > > > They're
> > > > > > more of a play by play of the election, instead of
> > > > > a

> > > > > polling
> > > > > > firms have no interest in seeing the accuracy of
> > > > > their
> > > > > > polls questioned since it might jeopordize their

it would be best and easiest to just talk to the reservationist, she is a 
doll and very helpfull.
415 348-0900
she is filled in a bit more on upcoming performances/details of certain 
evennings as well as pricing and whatnot.
her name is Blue.
generally it is a 5 course prix fixe meal for 60$ not including 
drinks/gratuity.  We love it when people dress in costume and play with us.  
The dinner takes about 3 hours, one seating, we accomodate all dietary needs 
and we have fun.  Fridays and saturdays are a lot of fun. after 11:30 or so, 
the bar rouge opens to flood  the dining area and turns into a big party, 
often we have well known dj's stopping in and playing, like last night with 
Keoki.  He will be back next wek as well, we are not sure when.  But rumor 
has it SF will be able to see him for a few weeks  ;)
You never know what will happen at SupperClub, it is always a surpise.
www.supperclub.com
:)

"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] srr: fighting over pacifiers

imagine if it happend at a candy rave!!!



Cops Handle Kids' Fist Fight Over Pacifier
-
Wednesday, October 5, 2005

(10-05) 12:51 PDT Pawtucket, R.I. (AP) --

Normally, a fight between two children over a pacifier might be
resolved by their mothers. But in Pawtucket, the police had to step
in. It all started Monday afternoon, when a 6-year-old boy dropped a
pacifier.

Another 6-year-old boy picked it up and refused to give it back,
allegedly prompting the first child to deliver a punch. Police said
the boy with the pacifier then punched back.

Pawtucket Police Detective Donti Rosciti said one of the mothers
called police, saying she wanted the fist fight documented because her
son had three minor scratches on his face, and she didn't want his
school accusing her of abuse.

A patrolman wrote up a report, then went to the home of the other
child to speak with his parents, Rosciti said. He called the case very
unusual.

"I've never seen a report with two kids this young," he said.

Rosciti said that as far as police are concerned, the matter is over.

"A 6-year-old can't be held criminally responsible," he said.

Hi,
If you want glowsticks, now is the time to get them.

I was in the mood for glowstickin' in the living room, dancing like crazy, wanting to show off to the neighbors and any pedestrians since I am on the 2nd floor.

I went to Safeway. Had a feeling they would have them. 

They are on sale, with the Club card, regularly 2.99 for a 3 pack, now for a limited time only 2.39.

Only problem is they are MONSTER GLOWSTICKS, 2-green, 1-orange.

Ha, ha, I didn't care about the color, I opened the patio door, turned off the lights, turned on the lava lamp, turned up the stereo, broke the glowsticks, and had a good old time.

So, it's Happy Halloween time. Have fun with CRAZY GLOWSTICKS everyone and it's all GRATE.

Greg
--NextPart_Webmail_9m3u9jl4l_19499_1128754298_0--

> Cops Handle Kids' Fist Fight Over Pacifier
> -
> Wednesday, October 5, 2005
>
> (10-05) 12:51 PDT Pawtucket, R.I. (AP) --
>
> Normally, a fight between two children over a pacifier might be
> resolved by their mothers. But in Pawtucket, the police had to step
> in. It all started Monday afternoon, when a 6-year-old boy dropped a
> pacifier.
>
> Another 6-year-old boy picked it up and refused to give it back,
> allegedly prompting the first child to deliver a punch. Police said
> the boy with the pacifier then punched back.
>
> Pawtucket Police Detective Donti Rosciti said one of the mothers
> called police, saying she wanted the fist fight documented because her
> son had three minor scratches on his face, and she didn't want his
> school accusing her of abuse.
>
> A patrolman wrote up a report, then went to the home of the other
> child to speak with his parents, Rosciti said. He called the case very
> unusual.
>
> "I've never seen a report with two kids this young," he said.
>
> Rosciti said that as far as police are concerned, the matter is over.
>
> "A 6-year-old can't be held criminally responsible," he said.

Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Type: text/plain;

	delsp=yes;
	format=flowed

Fifty years of "Howl" today

Fifty years ago today, Oct 7, 1955, six poets held a
reading in San Francisco: They were Philip Lamantia,
Michael McClure, Philip Whalen, Allen Ginsberg, and Gary
Snyder.

Ginsberg read the poem "Howl" for the first time.


 From Howl


by Allen Ginsberg
For Carl Solomon


                            I

        I saw the best minds of my generation destroyed by
               madness, starving hysterical naked,
        dragging themselves through the negro streets at dawn
               looking for an angry fix,
        angelheaded hipsters burning for the ancient heavenly
               connection to the starry dynamo in the machin-
               ery of night,
        who poverty and tatters and hollow-eyed and high sat
               up smoking in the supernatural darkness of
               cold-water flats floating across the tops of cities
               contemplating jazz,
        who bared their brains to Heaven under the El and
               saw Mohammedan angels staggering on tene-
               ment roofs illuminated,
        who passed through universities with radiant cool eyes
               hallucinating Arkansas and Blake-light tragedy
               among the scholars of war,
        who were expelled from the academies for crazy &
               publishing obscene odes on the windows of the
               skull,
        who cowered in unshaven rooms in underwear, burn-
               ing their money in wastebaskets and listening
               to the Terror through the wall,
        who got busted in their pubic beards returning through
               Laredo with a belt of marijuana for New York,
        who ate fire in paint hotels or drank turpentine in
               Paradise Alley, death, or purgatoried their
               torsos night after night
        with dreams, with drugs, with waking nightmares, al-
               cohol and cock and endless balls,
        incomparable blind; streets of shuddering cloud and
               lightning in the mind leaping toward poles of
               Canada & Paterson, illuminating all the mo-
               tionless world of Time between,
        Peyote solidities of halls, backyard green tree cemetery
               dawns, wine drunkenness over the rooftops,
               storefront boroughs of teahead joyride neon
               blinking traffic light, sun and moon and tree
               vibrations in the roaring winter dusks of Brook-
               lyn, ashcan rantings and kind king light of mind,
        who chained themselves to subways for the endless
               ride from Battery to holy Bronx on benzedrine
               until the noise of wheels and children brought
               them down shuddering mouth-wracked and
               battered bleak of brain all drained of brilliance
               in the drear light of Zoo,
        who sank all night in submarine light of Bickford's
               floated out and sat through the stale beer after
               noon in desolate Fugazzi's, listening to the crack
               of doom on the hydrogen jukebox,
        who talked continuously seventy hours from park to
               pad to bar to Bellevue to museum to the Brook-
               lyn Bridge,
        lost battalion of platonic conversationalists jumping
               down the stoops off fire escapes off windowsills
               off Empire State out of the moon,
        yacketayakking screaming vomiting whispering facts
               and memories and anecdotes and eyeball kicks
               and shocks of hospitals and jails and wars,
        whole intellects disgorged in total recall for seven days
               and nights with brilliant eyes, meat for the
               Synagogue cast on the pavement,


MORE:  http://members.tripod.com/~Sprayberry/poems/howl.txt




apollo@speakeasy.org

MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo

Tribenet:   http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm



"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path  
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and  
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras,  
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and  
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can  
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and  
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond  
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative  
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in  
squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of  
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will  
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"



--Apple-Mail-1-184602421--

and i got a little more insight to what he's about, because i never 
really heard much about him since he's not a san francisco based dj 
(unless he's now moved).  if all the events from the movie are true, on 
one hand, it re-affirms to me that nearly anyone can be a successful 
dj, and it has little to do with mixing skills, more rather, who you 
know and how well you promote yourself; on the other hand, you got to 
give the guy a hand for staying away from too much of the drug side of 
the scene, which i think we've all seen some of our friends become a 
complete mess because they couldn't control themselves.

and of course, "party monster" is a prime example of the worst case 
scenario.  it's chilling that story really happened!

-d

Subject: [sfraves] SRR: Let's get technical: glowstick advice

--NextPart_Webmail_9m3u9jl4l_20145_1128911375_0
Content-Type: text/plain
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

OK, my arms are sore today, I had too much fun with miniature glowsticks Friday night. I had no idea how intense this can be if you let the music guide you.

Now I wonder: what is the best glowstick size? Small, large, oh boy, that sounds risque without intending to be.

I used the 4" lightsticks, held them in my hands with good, comfortable results. That's why I am sore, too many rapid arm movements up in the air. Ironically, we also do arm movements in water aerobics so I am somewhat in shape for this exercise.

Also, turning off the TV works best cause you can see the reflection, thus guiding your practice movements.

Finally, I went to Home Depot today and bought the 6" lightsticks, which seem a bit awkward to me (too long). Maybe you have to tie a string on them and try swinging them, but when I tried it I had no control.

So far my best results have been with self-control--no strings--just my hands on the sticks, and waving my arms. 

This sounds so incredibly juvenile but what the hell, I am having fun and maybe light shows are part of what makes life happy, I did one for a friend and he asked for more, and we weren't even high.

Oh yeah, one of the 6-inchers from Home Depot was busted right out of the wrapper, what a disappointment, didn't light up at all. And it says "Homeland Security--Lasts for 12 hours" on the wrapper! 

It think it is ironic that the Halloween sticks (MONSTER GLOW) from Safeway were better--they are made my OmniGlow--"the world's leader in Glow fun"--which sounds like a Martha Stewart tag line. I wonder if she has tried glowsticking?

Greg
--NextPart_Webmail_9m3u9jl4l_20145_1128911375_0--

Subject: [sfraves] Saturday Night Adventure: Rhythm Method

OK.. so like ya know, OK... ummm... I had no ride 2 bus stop or BART.. so
I walked 2 the Bus stop come like well.. late afternoonish... stopped by
my cousin's pad 2 visit my niece, went 2 McD's & yelled @ these like 7
lil' black girls who had 2 B like age ranged from 10-12.. but it wqas
fucking annoying... I was standing there like ready 2 order 4 like 10
mintues & God knows htey may hve been there like longer b4 i got there..
but they kept changing their orders, adding bacon 2 all their bugers,
changing their orders 'cause something or another... 10 fuckin' minutes..
then 1 of the girls wearing this Tinkerbell back pack was the most
annoying 'cause she changed her order like 30 times or something like
since i got there... & she was changing it again.. so i just said, "OH MYU
GOODNESS MAN, YO TINK, all the bugers taste the same.. just order
something Girl.. FUCK".. 'cause all I wanted was a dble cheese brgr & 2
pies... well.. needl3ess 2 say I think i kinda scared them & some of the
employees.. but yeah.. they opened up a register LoL, just 4 me & I swear
man.. my shit only took 3 mintues & those girls were still fighting about
what they wanna eat when i was leaving.. Heeeeeeeeello 2Daaay!!  Ya know?!
 LoL

Anywaze.. got 2 Ashby.. Mz Kittie picked me up @ the station!!  YAY!!! 
Got 2 her pad when Ms Kitty & the kids were performing Hula dances w/
music from Don Ho... Nice.. & they wre eating pinapples on toothpicks...
fun fun!

OK.. so me & the Lainta Feline Bitches Groovy Twosome of the Bay Area got
2 Shadow Lounge 4 the Rhythm Method monthlie.. OK... I'm gonna be like
honest.. 'cause like earlier in the day, i was listen 2 my friends spin
Jungle in the UK on their stations & shit.. so i was hella hyped about
goin' 2 RM 'cause like alota the shit's my UK Homie's spun theat day was
like all this ummm... like it was uplifting dnb kinda, yaknow??  LIke
tracks that made me pump my hand in the air & like stand up & kick step
all over the computer room.. well.. hopefully my Mom won't notice the
crack on the closet door 'cause i painted the crack w/ white out & put
glossy nail polish over it...

But I dunno... I expected 2 go 2 RM & get all inspired by the Jungle i was
gonna hear. Groove 2 all night!  But I dunno... I mean.. all the DJs were
good... The Doctor, Binoculous, ummm... ooh... wait.. his DJ name's not
Trinidad.. ummm.. grr. .. i 4got... but i keep calling him that 4 some
reason...  I mean.. aaaaaaaaaall the DJs were fuckin' Sick!!  Loved it!!! 
I danced my ass off, hd fun.. la la la.. but i dunno... i didn't hear
nothing uplifting like I did that afternoon.. so I was slightly
disappointed in gettng my hopes up 4 nothing.. I mean.. not nothing
nothing 'cause it was still bad ass.. but hnmmm... I just didn't hear
anything uplifting that night.. but the music was fuckin' Bad Ass.. YAY!!!

Ummm.. 4 those who remember Andy aka Kung Fu Special who lurked, didn't
really post on here... well.. he moved 2 LA like a few months ago.. but
has been makin' frequent trips up here to Bay Area & he was hard up 4 a
place 2 crash out Sat night after the club.. so he came over & we kicked
it hardcore 'cause we ain't kicked it since.. well.. the Breaks after
party 4 LP... lol.. but b4 that.. like months!

But yeah.. the usual RM crowd was there.. not packin like it usually is...
but enough people to like talk to some1 new like every 37 minutes.. it wa
Dope!  Saw hella heads out there!!  YAY!~!!

So that was Saturday night!  Hello 2Day.. ok.. I"m seriously still like
fluffy from Sat night still.. literally.. so yeah... LOLOLOLMAO, OK... I
4got what I was gonna say.. I'm so confuzed...

Love U SFR! :)

Subject: [sfraves] SRR: How Glowsticks Can Help You

--NextPart_Webmail_9m3u9jl4l_15835_1129050378_0
Content-Type: text/plain
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Hi,
I wrote a few messages recently about the joy of using glowsticks.
 
I thought about it and decided to explain why glowstick activity was important to me because I never expressed an interest before.
 
I have been working out a lot lately, at the swimming pool, and it has been great therapy for me, losing weight, being active, moving around. Unfortunately, I will not be able to participate anymore because I am having surgery later this month.
 
I will be laid up in a cast for 6 weeks--this is reconstruction for a quadriceps tendon repair from last year that failed.
 
Oddly, I have no pain and I can jump around in the pool like a dancing fool. I even made it to a nightclub where I moved like mad to the house music (you’re not likely to fall when you are body-to-body on a packed floor).
 
The surgery is necessary because I have a 30-degree lag for a left leg extension, which is potentially dangerous in everyday life (but not in the pool, where the water buoyancy helps).
 
Anyway, I am worried about the onset of depression due to inactivity, but I am trying to make the most of it, so I tried the glowsticks on a whim Friday night, and found that it was exercise, too.
 
The rapid arm movements were exciting and I built up lactic acid, felt fatigue and soreness the next day. I even felt that I had used my abdominal muscles while waving frenetically. I decided that I will be dancing, however I can do it, even with my shoulders, arms, hands.
 
I remember a raver from a few years ago, whose name escapes me, but who was in a wheelchair and still made it to the floor, wheeling around in circles and waving her arms like crazy. I will never forget the bravery of that person. 
 
Sincerely,
Greg
--NextPart_Webmail_9m3u9jl4l_15835_1129050378_0--

Wow, this sounds like a great night! There's just something about minimal techno.

> *Saturday, October 15th* 
> 
> It's time for Episode 5...

> *[ K O N T R O L ]*

> minimal techno + avant house 
> every 3rd Saturday at Rx Gallery

> 
> why have one headliner when you can have two? 
> 
> featuring from Seattle: 
> 
> *CARO** – live p.a. *(orac. tigerbeat6 . halucination ltd.) 
> 
> *Orac Records* founder *CARO* comes to us from Seattle armed with a 
> microphone and a laptop running self-written audio software. Witness this 
> rising star's innovative live performance, including his hit *"My Little 
> Pony,"* and hear for yourself just why *CARO* and *ORAC* are names you'll 
> not soon forget! 
> 
> ...and from Los Angeles: 
> 
> * * 
> 
> *[A]PENDICS.SHUFFLE** – live p.a. *(orac . proptronix . adjunct) 
> 
> Following a stellar new full-length album on ORAC, LA's electronic wonder *Ken 
> Gibson* - known to many as *Eight Frozen Modules* and *DubLoner* - brings 
> his signature moody, dirty minimal techno to SF for a special LIVE 
> performance. Don't miss this rare opportunity to experience the prodigious 
> talent of the man XLR8R magazine has called "an American Richard D. James." 
> 
>

> 
>

>

> "a place where passion, obsession, fashion, and ugliness collide."

> http://www.michellehandelman.com/ 
>

>

> ________________________________________________ 
>

> *9pm-2am / $10 / 21+* 
> 
> *http://www.kontrolsf.com* 
> ________________________________________________ 
> 
> *Biography: Caro* 
> 
> A native of Madison, Wisconsin, Caro (Orac Records co-founder Randy Jones) 
> grew up in an environment just connected enough for him to receive hazy 
> transmissions from dance music's cultural centers. The Midwest dance scene, 
> resonating from the founding influence of the Hot Mix 5, was fiercely 
> eclectic. "A few local DJs brought techno music to Madison. Those guys would 
> mix genres like crazy. 
> 
> On Nick Nice's night at the Cardinal bar in 1991 you could hear everything 
> from Speedy J to Inner City to Smells Like Teen Spirit." "Around this time," 
> tells Jones, "I started making tracks to play for friends. Since I was a kid 
> I had always been into playing with computers and synths, but I had to be 
> hit over the head with the whole rave scene to realize that other people 
> might actually want to dance to my weird sounds." 
> 
> In 1993, Jones moved to Seattle where he honed his programming skills and 
> eventually found work combining computers and music. With Joshua "Kit" 
> Clayton at the helm, he helped create the audiovisual software Jitter for 
> Cycling '74. 
> 
> Meanwhile he had never stopped delving into dance music. "I was listening 
> to a lot of electro, new wave, Detroit techno, and this crazy techno that 
> the San Franciscans were making." Armed with this panoply of influences, in 
> 2000 Jones started the Orac label with partner Konstantin Gabbro, and 
> shortly thereafter the ROBO.trash weekly, which became a focal point for a 
> new generation of Northwest producers. At ROBO.trash, Jones honed his DJ 
> skills playing sets as eclectic as the ones he started dancing to. 
> 
> Spinning led to producing, and the alter ego Caro. His first full-length, 
> "The Return of Caro," follows a string of three critically-lauded 12"s which 
> bring to mind Bam Bam as much as sleeker modern techno. Always pushing the 
> technology forward along with his music, Jones performs live using software 
> he has written in Max/MSP. "It's a combination of remixing the tracks with 
> live singing and processing. Computers offer so many possibilities for 
> performance that people are just beginning to tap into. I want my 
> performance process to be open and as live as possible because that way it's 
> a deeper communication. I want it to be obvious when I'm doing great, and 
> also when I'm making mistakes." 
> 
> *Caro's website:* 
> 
> http://orac.vu/ 
> 
> *Caro's discography:* 
> 
> http://www.discogs.com/artist/Caro 
> 
> _____________________________________________ 
> 
> *Biography: [a]pendics.shuffle* 
> 
> [a]pendics.shuffle is but one of many aliases used by LA's electronic music 
> mastermind Kenneth James Gibson. Since he first began producing in 1997, his 
> style has morphed and expanded into a number of different genres, each 
> released under a different production name (seven to date, with more on the 
> way!) 
> 
> From the glitchy abstract breaks of Eight Frozen Modules, to the minimal 
> dubscapes of Dubloner, to the experimental tech-house of The Premature Wig, 
> to his recent Hiss and Buzz collaboration with electronic pioneer Jack 
> Dangers (Meat Beat Manifesto, Tino Corp.,) Ken Gibson refuses to be 
> pigeon-holed and is limited only by his own (seemingly limitless) 
> creativity. His consistently exciting and highly prolific output has landed 
> him releases on such diverse and respected labels as Tigerbeat6, Mille 
> Plateaux, and Planet Mu, but it is on Seattle's ORAC where his 
> four-to-the-floor dancefloor tendencies come out to play as 
> [a]pendics.shuffle. With releases also on Matthew "Saftey Scissors" Curry's 
> Proptronix and his own label Adjunct (featuring the likes of Bruno Pronsato, 
> John Tejada, and Pheek,) [a]pendics.shuffle busts out moody, dirty, thumping 
> minimal techno aimed squarely at the arse. 
> 
> Recently back in the States after a successful tour of Germany and the rest 
> of Europe, do not miss this rare opportunity to witness the man XLR8R 
> magazine has called "an American Richard D. James" in a very special, very 
> LIVE performance. 
> 
> *[a]pendics.shuffle's website:* 
> 
> http://www.eight-frozen-modules.com/ 
> 
> *[a]pendics.shuffle's discography:* 
> 
> http://www.eight-frozen-modules.com/Discography.htm 
> 
> _____________________________________________ 
> 
> *http://www.kontrolsf.com/*

Subject: [sfraves] Warning to party people - Saturday night bridge CLOSED

Anyone leaving the city after midnight on Saturday will NOT be able to
take the bay bridge.  Caltrans is shutting down the eastbound
direction, completely.

http://www.511.org/promo/baybridge/default.asp

"As part of its West Approach seismic retrofit project, Caltrans will
perform major demolition work in the eastbound and westbound
directions of Interstate 80 in San Francisco. This will require
complete closure of the eastbound direction of the Bay Bridge in the
early morning hours of Saturday, Oct. 15 and Sunday, Oct. 16, plus the
closure of several lanes and ramps in both directions at other times."

BART will be running all night to compensate:
http://bart.gov/news/press/news20051011.asp

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: Fuzzy Logic is this Saturday! 

FYI: The lower deck of the Bay Bridge is going to be closed from 1am to 
9am Sunday morning.  Fuzzy Logic will be located in the East Bay, so if 
you're coming from San Francisco, make sure to head over before the 
Eastbound span closes.  Another alternative would be to take the Golden 
Gate Bridge to 101 North, then take the Richmond-San Rafael bridge to 
the East Bay. Bart will also be running 24 hours on Saturday 
night/Sunday morning.


For more info on the bridge closure:
http://www.511.org/promo/baybridge/default.asp

on Bart serivce:
http://bart.gov/news/press/news20051011.asp


Our best advice:  Come early and stay late!  But shouldn't that always 
be the case?  ;-)


Love Chel-C Faith for DEF

and supported the past year, when George and I first started the night we
envisioned a small spot where we could charge no cover, pack in our
friends, and cause a house music ruckus.  It's really turned out to be
that and more and it's by far my favorite day of the month, feels great to
get so many familiar faces together on the regular, last Friday was no
different.

What he said.  Folded is the first club thing I've ever co-thrown, and
I really never expected, at first, for it to be anything more than a
place to play the music we make and love every month and showcase our
musical friends who need to be heard.  

Instead it's become sort of like a monthly
family-reunion-cum-weekend-party-times-jump-off-point.  I have so much
fun dancing and catching up with all'yall every first Friday it should
be like, criminal. :)

Anyway, *gush off*, thanks for a year of fun, surprises, and great
dancefloor antics.  

Luv,
-george C | origami

Engineering opportunities in the past. Any and all referrals are welcome 
and appreciated....

Request for QA Opportunities in Open Source Projects, Employment, 
Full-Time, Contract, Consulting

I'm seeking interesting Full Time, Contract, Consulting/Freelance 
Opportunities *and* Open Source Projects that are looking for a QA 
engineer with a solid background and diverse technical skillset. I've been 
in Software / Hardware Quality Assurance for 12+ years and am seeking 
projects to contribute towards the quality of the Gnu Public license 
and/or any Open Source model. I also am interested in Full-time 
employment, contract/consulting roles, as well as part-time/freelance work 
on any projects that seek a stellar QA engineer. If you know of someone 
who needs help or is looking for a tester with a technical edge, please 
feel free to refer them to me.

Roles: Full-time employment, contract, freelance, W2 opportunities in the 
QA field.

Objective: Senior QA Engineer, Lead Quality Assurance Engineer or QA 
Manager role
Summary & Qualifications: 12 years experience in Hardware/Software QA 
Engineering
- 6 years experience managing Quality Assurance organizations, leading 
multiple QA engineers and projects.
- 8 years experience in a Product Support and Technical Support 
Engineering role.
- 12 years experience in a Senior QA Engineer and Lead QA Engineer role.
- 12 years experience establishing various QA processes and procedures 
including: Product Development and Software LifeCycle, the QA Lifecycle 
process, Defect Submittal, Reporting, Tracking and Escalation Lifecycle, 
Product Validation, Certification and Release Lifecycle, QA Project 
Planning and QA Test Methodologies and Processes.
- 12 Years planning and executing Test Plans as part of the design, 
development and QA cycle of various projects.
- 12 years experience authoring and conducting Acceptance, Ad-Hoc, Black 
Box (Behavioral, Functional, Closed Box, Opaque box), GUI, Functional, 
Integration, Installation, Manual, Navigation, Module and Regression 
Tests.
- 11 Years performing release certification and validation, Unit and 
Integration Checks, Source Code Management.
- 10 years conducting White Box tests (Structural, Glassbox, Clearbox, 
System Internals, Branch/Path Coverage Tests).
- 12 years authoring and executing Performance, Database, Security, 
Smokescreen, Stress, Boundary, Load, Validation, SW & HW Compatibility 
Tests using advanced and innovative Test Methodologies in Macintosh, 
Windows, Unix, WAP, WML, Console game systems and Palm OS environments.
- 12 years authoring, documenting and defining standards for QA (Test 
Plans, Test Cases, Test Scripts and Test Procedures).
- 7 years experience administrating QA Lab Operations (Network/Test/Lab 
Environment), QA Release Cycle and QA Intranet website. Functions of this 
capacity included: QA Website Webmaster, QA Lab Administrator, QA 
Production Lab Administrator, QA Release certification and Defect Tracking 
Systems Administrator.

Resume and extensive references furnished upon request

Subject: [sfraves] Marco's Mix Breaks me open !!!

Everynight I go to bed with my big studio monitor Sony V6 headphones
and my mini ipod. I  only listen to mixes, because I want to know that
a dj has seamlessly placed songs together in some meaningful fashion.
Often times this consists of ambient stuff (blue mars, redstick man
mixes, Drone Zone, Cafe Del Mar, Chilled euphoria) psy trance, and
progressive trance stuff (xtcradio, james holden, Sasha, Digweed).

Well I've had this mix by Marco for some time now, but I never really
listened to it because I knew it was breaks and breaks always makes me
feel like I've had sex for hours and I am not allowed to orgasm. It's
like, if the fucking DJ could just throw in a 4/4 for 30 seconds after
I've listened to this great break beat buildup for hours on end I
could be in eternal ecstacy, but that never happens with breaks.
Breaks is like a prog trance dj playing his most energy filled banging
records for the entire set instead of creating peaks and valleys.
Something I could listen to while on speed...

So anyway, last night I listened to Marco's mix while laying in bed
and I was completely moved. It was an awesome experience. that mix
seriously blew me away and I would love to hear you play live some
time. Even if you are Violet Beuregaurd's twin brother.

Smaug is in the mainframe.
www.tussinspace.com

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Maybe some of you have heard of Acid Totem, maybe you haven't. About us:
We're a collective primarily focusing on outdoor renegades, day parties, an=
d
full moons with a focus on house music. We celebrated our 2 yr anniversary
this summer, and have had around 7 (I think, maybe more) successful parties
in 2005. As much as we love house, progressive, techno, etc, we really
wanted to open up the door for a much wider spectrum of music, so the theme
Rebel Sound was born. We will be digging deep into our crates and dusting
off our more obscure musical collections, as well as booking dj's you might
not otherwise hear at acid totem parties. Revelling in the warm days of
October's Indian summer, we've decided to to plan at least one more party
for 2005.
 Under the moon n stars, free as always
Sat. Oct 22, 2005

Sorry folks, but after posting our info to a few lists and due to us "using
so much network resources" (apparently from lots of people downloading the
free music sets at once) our webhost blocked our site all day yesterday.
Apologies if you tried to visit it and were denied.

Sure, sell us a website with 400gigs of transfer per month, then take it
down when it's actually getting used, nice. Always read the fine print,
kids!

Anyway, we had to pull a bunch of the sets that were getting linked to from
elsewhere to ease the load on the server for a bit, but the site is back up
and running.

guests, both of whom are doing LIVE PA's. It's gonna be a really fun show!

 Caro + [a]pendics.shuffle - both performing LIVE.

sandwich stashed in the rafters, dammit ;-)

Homebase and I had a love/hate relationship, of sorts. I've had my most 
negatively shocking rave experiences there, as well as some wonderful 
memories.

Shall we have a moratorium/eulogy thread? I would love to hear everyone's 
stories as this legendary (yet equally shady) venue goes up in flames =)

-terry

apollo@speakeasy.org

Tribenet:   http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm



"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path  
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and  
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras,  
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and  
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can  
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and  
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond  
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative  
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in  
squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of  
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will  
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

planet rock parties
all the feel good parties like love-a-fair, mega-buzz, feel good forever, 
spirit of giving

the planet rock parties i remember being a little on the scary side, esp the 
hip hop big room.  a bunch of us ended up kinda hiding in the trance room 
b/c most of the thug-types we saw were not into trance at all.

the feel good parties i went to at home base were really fun overall.  i had 
a blast at one party dancing outside to happy kid marty's set.  good beats, 
no sweatbox, fun friends.

back in the olden days...

with love,
kriss  =)

My first and only party ever attended there was (I think the very first)
Metropolis. It was not too long after moving to the city, so I'd guess like
'99 or so? Not sure if that place was indeed the "Home Base" but I think it
was. It was definitely really BIG. As I recall, myself and a couple female
friends all ate some acid, had nothing else whatsoever to take the edge off=
,
and were all quite appalled at how drugged out (ironic, i know) and rude
everyone seemed to be. I think the music was pretty good though. I think I
remember seeing like Terry Mullan and Donald Glaude or something.
 Ahh, the good old days. I can't wait to tell "rave" stories to my
great-grandkids out on the front porch in my rocking chair.
 -----> Greg

oh yes... that Gathering was off the hook.

Dr. Alex Patterson closed out the chill room (armed with Mark Wayne's 
4-channel monstrosity, the "M2" sound system) with Orbital's Belfast.  
oh... my... god....  my girlfriend had to leave the room because it was 
just too intense for her!  the chill room itself was a huge den of 
fluff, with the decks in the middle of the room on a low table and a 
beanbag for the DJ.

it was PACKED to the gills, and the vibe was good... 4 sound systems if 
i remember correctly.

woo. good times - then it started getting sleazy...

bye home base!

Got a chance to introduce a friend of mine back in DC to Alex Patterson when 
he was opening for Juno Reactor, I think it was '99 or '00. My friend (who's 
massively inspired by The Orb) gave Alex some green clovers, and the guy was 
so humbled that fans would bother doing anything like that. It was a bit 
surreal sitting on a tour bus in front of what's now the Black Cat on 14th 
Street (near U Street) in DC, exchanging pleasantries and illicits w/ 
someone like that. Very cool guy...

Sorry for the totally pointless anecdote, lol.

"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment. These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not. Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in 
squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Please excuse the lurking, but I usually don't speak up unless I have something to impart - 
Sorry, no - Violet Beauregard is the girl who chews gum and becomes a blueberry. She eats the all-in-one gum, blows up, and the oompa loompas roll her away to be juiced. Veruca Salt is the spoiled girl who pockets the everlasting gobstopper earlier in the story, but she gets hers when she's sent to the incinerator for being a bad egg. Veruca Salt was then the adopted moniker of that cute chick band from a few years back - one or two hit wonder.
 
Just clarifying for the record..KF

Wow... So I guess I can de-lurk for this one. 

Home Base burning down brings back a lot of good
memories, a lot of bad ones... but most of all, just
memories about a time when the disconnect between
pparents, media, and children allowed us to do
whatever we wanted... where the excuses were simple
and believed, you couldn't track your kids via their
phone on internet, and fire marshalls signed your
occuopancy permits if you simply agreed to help their
kids through college.

Then came 20/20, lawyers, real fire marshalls, and the
end.

As far as "being a ho" or being in trouble again...
Whatchoo talkin 'bout Willis? I either don't get it
cause im too old, or am  missing something that y'all
are laughing at.

Nonetheless... my .02.

E
