Hey everyone the time is almost apon us. We have assembles 7 of the most
beloved crews in the bay for one special event. We have worked very hard to
make this the best event of the year. Please join us as we go mad!!!*
||||Mad Hatters Halloween Tea Party|||| *
*Room 1 (hosted by HCFTP, Nu Vision, DTS and Nocturnalisim)*
*GRIDLOK* (Project51/Violence Recordings-SF) As one of America's hardest
working producers and DJs, Gridlok has charted a steady, methodical path
into the vanguard of drum and bass. His tracks enjoy the support of drum an=
d
bass' finest, from Andy C to Bailey. His work ethic and tireless efforts to
advance the sonic breadth of the music have yielded tremendous dividends fo=
r
drum and bass fans worldwide. Recent releases on Project 51 and Violence
have become staples of countless major league DJs worldwide, and are huge
crowd favorites

*SUNRIZE* (Pitched Up Recordings/HCFTP/Blatant Beats UK-MA) - *Final Happy
Hardcore Perfomance* Since his first hardcore release in the spring of 2002=
,
he has released on a handful of labels, some including Pitched Up
Recordings, Blatant Beats, Destructive Force, Rave N Beats, and Madness &
Mayhem. This DJ's name has become unanimous with American Hardcore and has
played all across the country at events with artists like Scott Brown, DJ
SY, UFO, Brisk, and others. This will be his final performance as dj
sunrize. Don't miss the last chance to see him play happy hardcore.

*MAYHEM* (AZ Hardcore
Junkies.com/CompleteDJ.com<http://Junkies.com/CompleteDJ.com>)
vs. *vs. Second Base*In 2001, Steve Van Holton, better known to West Coast
hardcore fans as Mayhem, began playing records. His motivation? Simply to
listen to the music he loved by artists such as Digital Boy, Anger Fist,
Noize Supressor, Sonik, The Wish Master, Armageddon Project and The
Headbanger. Mayhem joined the Arizona Hardcore Junkies in 2003 only a shot
time after he began playing and in 2004 was asked to play Nocturnal
Wonderland in Los Angeles. Playing parties with the likes of Scott Brown,
Neophyte, Panic, Ophidian, Delta 9, D-passion and Dj delirium. The AZ
Hardcore Junkies expect big things to come from Mayhem in the near future.

the AXIS (The Doc & Arize)
Sideshow & Go-Zania & Leon Cook
Yagi & Reclipse
Happy Freaks (Hi-C, Kid Orange, & Cracker Jack)
2qt & Rye Bread

*Room 2 (Hosted by Zapatistas and Andy P)*

*DIG-DUG* (USC Events-WA) Known for his incredible track selection and
polished technical skills, DJ Dig-Dug has managed to develop an undeniably
unique style. While his sets often travel through several different types o=
f
breaks (Funky, Progressive, Dark), his underlying theme of warped basslines
and intelligent drum loops brings a sense of unity to his signature sound.
With his impressive beat juggling, cross-fader cutting, and creative but
tasteful use of the Pioneer DJM-600's onboard effects, DJ Dig-Dug has
developed a following based on skills, not hype.

*FilterGrinder* (Kontrast/Phat & Phunkie-TX) Doug Siebenthal, a.k.a.
Filtergrinder, has been djing for the last seven years. Filtergrinder
started producing techno when he met Bryan Cox in 2001. BC and Filtergrinde=
r
went on to produce the hit record "Alpine". Alpine (BC remix) got quick
recognition by DJ Dan and was featured on his Mixed Live DJ Dan, Ruby Skye
(Moonshine) CD. Both the original and the remix went on to have great
notoriety on BBC Radio One, and top rotation of such djs as Carl Cox,
Fergie, Joey Beltram, and Mauro Picotto. Filtergrinder currently resides in
the L.A. area as he continues to dj on a monthly basis and for the year of
2005, he is also launching Whiplash Records; the first release, "Rockin the
Disco", is coming out in March with the remix being done by Bryan Cox. You
can also expect other records from Filtergrinder in 2005 including
"Repeater" on the Afficinado label, with remixes from Granite & Phunk and
Carbon Community.

Filter Freq 2x4 Dj Doza
Ron Reeser 2x4 Felipe Avelar
Aaron Jae 2x4 M.O.D.
Andy P 2x4 Vinyl Junkies - Special 1hr 30min set.
Soul 1 2x4 Rob Base
Hard Stompers aka Riff Raff 2x4 Spell
ill-D the DJ 2x4 Hyjinx

*Room 3 (Hosted By SSP and Illumination Records)*
*DUTCH* (Thump Radio-SF) A 12 yr veteran of the SF scene, Dutch made his
name early in the rave scene. Beginning with a party known as A Rave called
Sharon, Dutch's name spread quickly throughout SF. Known for seamless
mixing, and remarkable sets, Dutch has made a huge impact at the SF Thump
parties as resident DJ. Keep your eyes on this kid and check him out if he
comes to your city! nuff said

Officer Bunch (Ooze System / Saturated Mind)
Michael Liu
Majere
Epsilon
Durty & Viticus
Precision
Tim Stephanic

*Details:*
1000 Person Capacity
Safe and Secure Venue
East Bay Location
Friendly Security
Amazing Wall of Sound provided by HardScience Sound.
Refreshment Booth
Lazers, Lights, and Props

If there is a sin against life, it consists perhaps not so

> My first and only party ever attended there was (I think the very first)
> Metropolis. It was not too long after moving to the city, so I'd guess like
> '99 or so? Not sure if that place was indeed the "Home Base" but I think it
> was. It was definitely really BIG. As I recall, myself and a couple female
> friends all ate some acid, had nothing else whatsoever to take the edge off,
> and were all quite appalled at how drugged out (ironic, i know) and rude
> everyone seemed to be. I think the music was pretty good though. I think I
> remember seeing like Terry Mullan and Donald Glaude or something.
> Ahh, the good old days. I can't wait to tell "rave" stories to my
> great-grandkids out on the front porch in my rocking chair.
> -----> Greg
>

Bcc: 
Date: Thu, 13 Oct 2005 18:28:56 +0000
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; format=flowed
X-OriginalArrivalTime: 13 Oct 2005 18:28:56.0809 (UTC) FILETIME=[F8E49590:01C5D023]
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] Thanks for the homebase memories

As I watched a bit of the news again this morning and they said how they 
just let the fire burn it's self out and gut the "Home base" building I 
couldn't help to be a lil sad even though we all know Fully permitted 
parties are over in oak town. in the back of my mind I always thought that 
maybe some grand thing would fall out of the sky and some one would bring 
home base back again. But after that fire it makes it that much more surreal 
that homebase is truly gone forever now.

I attened the first and last party and "Gatherings" at that warehouse and 
all the ones in between alot of good times, watching Eric spire rock the am 
crowd at one of the quest's that he put together. Or Garth rocking the big 
room. And even watching the beloved Mars and Mystre play in a side hall. Im 
sure that hurt there ego a bit, And even having someone come up to me after 
playing there one night and ask if I was Derek may. Now that was an awesome 
compliement but I had to say no I wasn't the only thing that we have in 
common is that we are both black and not very tall. But all and all it was 
pretty good. It also meant the end of all night large warehouse parties 
which most of us at the time despised but you can't deny that having 10,000 
people rocking out to a DJ is a magnificent thing.

the Memories also reminded me of all the large spaces that can no longer be 
used due to politics or other issues  in the scene such as:

Richmond Civic (Awesome parties there Vision,come-unity,Cool world etc)
Richmond Armory (Tribal Funk, bagok tribe)
3@custer Now a recycling center (Cool word and a few others did parties 
there)
The movie stage on 3rd as well (Space Children,mind the gap)
Ceasars latin palace (FTT,A rave called sharon,mind the gap)
85@baldwin (Area 51,Space children etc) Awesome space with many memories
16@harrison (Wally world,Sin,SIN again, Juice FTT etc) okay space but was 
sketchy


I know there are alot more spaces im missing but I have to get back to work 
now :-)

If you read this far thanks for reading my ramblings!!


Pouring out some liquor for da homies at homebase!  R.I.P

Macadio



---------------------------------------------------------------------

"Macadio G." <macadio@hotmail.com> wrote:
As I watched a bit of the news again this morning and they said how they 
just let the fire burn it's self out and gut the "Home base" building I 
couldn't help to be a lil sad even though we all know Fully permitted 
parties are over in oak town. in the back of my mind I always thought that 
maybe some grand thing would fall out of the sky and some one would bring 
home base back again. But after that fire it makes it that much more surreal 
that homebase is truly gone forever now.

I attened the first and last party and "Gatherings" at that warehouse and 
all the ones in between alot of good times, watching Eric spire rock the am 
crowd at one of the quest's that he put together. Or Garth rocking the big 
room. And even watching the beloved Mars and Mystre play in a side hall. Im 
sure that hurt there ego a bit, And even having someone come up to me after 
playing there one night and ask if I was Derek may. Now that was an awesome 
compliement but I had to say no I wasn't the only thing that we have in 
common is that we are both black and not very tall. But all and all it was 
pretty good. It also meant the end of all night large warehouse parties 
which most of us at the time despised but you can't deny that having 10,000 
people rocking out to a DJ is a magnificent thing.

the Memories also reminded me of all the large spaces that can no longer be 
used due to politics or other issues in the scene such as:

Richmond Civic (Awesome parties there Vision,come-unity,Cool world etc)
Richmond Armory (Tribal Funk, bagok tribe)
3@custer Now a recycling center (Cool word and a few others did parties 
there)
The movie stage on 3rd as well (Space Children,mind the gap)
Ceasars latin palace (FTT,A rave called sharon,mind the gap)
85@baldwin (Area 51,Space children etc) Awesome space with many memories
16@harrison (Wally world,Sin,SIN again, Juice FTT etc) okay space but was 
sketchy


I know there are alot more spaces im missing but I have to get back to work 
now :-)

If you read this far thanks for reading my ramblings!!


Pouring out some liquor for da homies at homebase! R.I.P

Macadio



---------------------------------------------------------------------

Subject: [sfraves] RIP event locales / venues that are no longer in use


I wanted to thank Macadio for his thoughts on Home Base. I definitely will 
miss that space as well. I wanted to add a few spots to this list - and 
create a thread for venues / spaces that are no longer in use - but once 
were. (See Below):

-- 
**************************************************************
******************>karina@hyperreal.org<**********************
If there is a sin against life, it consists perhaps not so
much in despairing of life as in hoping for another life
& in eluding the implacable grandeur of this life.
-- Albert Camus -- *******************************************
**************************************************************

>
> the Memories also reminded me of all the large spaces that can no longer be 
> used due to politics or other issues  in the scene such as:
>
> Richmond Civic (Awesome parties there Vision,come-unity,Cool world etc)
> Richmond Armory (Tribal Funk, bagok tribe)
> 3@custer Now a recycling center (Cool word and a few others did parties 
> there)
> The movie stage on 3rd as well (Space Children,mind the gap)
> Ceasars latin palace (FTT,A rave called sharon,mind the gap)
> 85@baldwin (Area 51,Space children etc) Awesome space with many memories
> 16@harrison (Wally world,Sin,SIN again, Juice FTT etc) okay space but was 
> sketchy
>

To add to this: (please correct me if these are not accurate) - some of 
these are not large spaces, or closed due to politics, but aren't used 
as much due to noise complaints, over-usage, or another reason) but are 
worthy to note due to the location / use in the past:

People's Park in Bezerkeley (parties in the park)
Berkeley Marina (there is an occasional renegade)
Maritime Hall
177 Townsend
Cactus Club in San Jose (It is in use as another venue, but not the same)
Hamburger Mary's (it is in use now, but not the same as before)
One Step Beyond in Santa Clara
Bonny Doon in Santa Cruz
Castle Rock in Santa Cruz
2nd and (Crack)Jackson in Oaktown
Spaz Warehouse in Berkeley
DV8, the Trocadero (reopened as the Glas Kat), and VSF/Oasis

Starcleaners, on Sycamore Street, Club Komotion, and the 17th and Capp and 
Shotwell warehouses, plus bars such as the Kilowatt, the Chameleon, and 
the Tip-Top Inn.

What happened to 550 Barneveld in SF?

Just recently:

Sofa Lounge in SJ, CA



---------------------------------------------------------------------

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: Re: [sfraves] RIP event locales / venues that are no longer in use

Oh, I've got one.  And best of all, it comes with a great tie-in to one 
of my favorite television shows.  I'm not going to bother to describe 
Mythbusters.  If you've seen it, you already know why it's so great.  
If you haven't, then do see it.  You'll love it.

Mythbusters is filmed mostly in San Francisco, and the surrounding Bay 
Area.  It's obvious, from watching the show, that they operate mostly 
out of somewhere in Portero Hill, but not exactly where from the brief 
outside shots of their workshop.

Last night, I followed a link from a Slashdot discussion to the 
Wikipedia article on the show, and from there to the site of Jamie 
Hyneman's "M5 Industries" workshop; where most of the indoor portions 
of the show (ie. When they don't have to remote-rig a car or blow 
anything big up.) take place.

The address looked familiar... damn familiar.  I used to live pretty 
close to that part of town.  But it turns out that wasn't why.  So, I 
plug the address into Google Maps and I see.  Turns out I've walked 
right past the place who-knows-how-many times on my way from the 
parking lot over by the community center to one of my absolute top 
favorites of the ex-rave-venues.

Myths are busted on the opposite side of the block from the old dance 
studio place @ Army and Connecticut!!!


cya,
john

>>
>> the Memories also reminded me of all the large spaces that can no 
>> longer be used due to politics or other issues  in the scene such as:
>>
>> Richmond Civic (Awesome parties there Vision,come-unity,Cool world 
>> etc)
>> Richmond Armory (Tribal Funk, bagok tribe)
>> 3@custer Now a recycling center (Cool word and a few others did 
>> parties there)
>> The movie stage on 3rd as well (Space Children,mind the gap)
>> Ceasars latin palace (FTT,A rave called sharon,mind the gap)
>> 85@baldwin (Area 51,Space children etc) Awesome space with many 
>> memories
>> 16@harrison (Wally world,Sin,SIN again, Juice FTT etc) okay space but 
>> was sketchy
>>
>
> To add to this: (please correct me if these are not accurate) - some 
> of these are not large spaces, or closed due to politics, but aren't 
> used as much due to noise complaints, over-usage, or another reason) 
> but are worthy to note due to the location / use in the past:
>
> People's Park in Bezerkeley (parties in the park)
> Berkeley Marina (there is an occasional renegade)
> Maritime Hall
> 177 Townsend
> Cactus Club in San Jose (It is in use as another venue, but not the 
> same)
> Hamburger Mary's (it is in use now, but not the same as before)
> One Step Beyond in Santa Clara
> Bonny Doon in Santa Cruz
> Castle Rock in Santa Cruz
> 2nd and (Crack)Jackson in Oaktown
> Spaz Warehouse in Berkeley
> DV8, the Trocadero (reopened as the Glas Kat), and VSF/Oasis
>
> Starcleaners, on Sycamore Street, Club Komotion, and the 17th and Capp 
> and Shotwell warehouses, plus bars such as the Kilowatt, the 
> Chameleon, and the Tip-Top Inn.
>
> What happened to 550 Barneveld in SF?
>
> Just recently:
>
> Sofa Lounge in SJ, CA

>
> To add to this: (please correct me if these are not accurate) - =20
> some of these are not large spaces, or closed due to politics, but =20
> aren't used as much due to noise complaints, over-usage, or another =20=

> reason) but are worthy to note due to the location / use in the past:

Many potential and former warehouse-type venues are unavailable now =20
because of the gentrification that began during the boom times in the =20=

late nineties.  The Eden collective sausage factory is blossoming =20
into condos, for example.  177 Townsend sold off the rest of its long =20=

term lease to accommodate a garage and condos.

Many former EDM venues are off the map for us here at sfraves because =20=

they don't host the kind of music of vibe preferred here:  the Oasis =20
is now a Hispanic dance club;  Gus still does gay parties at 550 as =20
well as hip hop events;  Kelly's Mission Rock (not mentioned) does =20
lots of SRO hip hop parties now;  the Glas Kat reopens regularly now =20
for "Remember the Troc" disco parties;  and so on.

I don't think it's so much politics that closes venues for good in =20
the Bay;  rather folks lookin' for a jingle in the pocket.  Money =20
talks dancers walk.

Apollo

Subject: [sfraves] News: (*recent) 'Rave' parties become mainstream

  HOME  >  OTHER ENTERTAINMENT NEWS  >  Lifestyle NEWS

'Rave' parties become mainstream

UPI News Service, 09/23/2005

The huge, often controversial techno dance parties of the 1980s and 1990s 
known as raves have gone mainstream.

ADVERTISEMENT
Not only are they no longer seen as threatening hotbeds of teenage drug 
use, but one of the nation's largest dance parties -- the Loveparade, 
which will be held in the Bay Area on Saturday -- is celebrated with a 
parade, the San Jose Mercury News reported.

"The rave crowd grew up," Ross Ivika, dance concert promoter and co-host 
of "House Nation" on KYLD-FM, told the newspaper.

More than 35,000 people attended the Loveparade festival last year. 
Corporate sponsors include Heineken, Friendster and iTunes.

"Techno has become more about the music, as opposed to something to listen 
to while on E (ecstasy)," said Ivika.

The culture "has come more above ground," said Robert Davis, executive 
director of the city and county of San Francisco's entertainment 
commission, which was created in response to events like raves.

Source: http://www.realitytvworld.com/index/articles/story.php?s=1004747

Seconded. Thanks Macadio. : )
 
And though I certainly had, like Terry, a love-hate relationship with  
Homebase, you can't deny the profound impact it had on the scene during that  time 
period. If/when someone writes a book about our bay area rave  culture, 
homebase will certainly have it's own chapter. : )
 
When I first started partying in '98, I was caught by Son (aka BBoiBreaks)  
with a FeelGood flyer in my hands. He said to me, "Honey.. if the flyer is big  
enough to sit on- DON'T GO!"  
 
I stuck to it for the most part, so to record I can count the number  of 
massives I've been to on one hand, but I made a few exceptions, with  Homebases's 
Love Affair '99 and Megabuzz '99 being two of the  few.
 
 
Anyway, I can't believe no one has mentioned the space my first  party was 
at- J.J. Newberry's! Weee!
 
Good times. Any one remember that place? I remember being outside as we  
waited to pay and getting butterflies in my stomach as I noticed the  rebellious 
symbolism of all the windows blacked out with garbage bags. THUMP  THUMP THUMP. 
This was some underground shit. 
 
I was suddenly struck with the profound knowledge that when I  walked through 
those doors, I was going to be apart of something that would  make history. 
"Have fun," the doorman smiled. "The shits going off in there!  You're in for a 
good night!"
 
Oh, the enchantment of that first sight as I entered. I don't know  that you 
can truly capture the delicious experience that hits you as you  walk into 
your first rave. It's still etched in my head, over seven years  later.
 
I remember that at the time, my friends and I had no idea what the  painter's 
masks were for, but somehow we had the idea that people used them to  huff 
NO2. Oh, the naivety of newbies. ; )
 
And  well... fuck it. In remembrance of Homebase, I give you my  long-retired 
SFR sign-off:
 
TiCkLeS aNd GiGgLeS,
~*SwEeT PeA*~
 
RIP Homebase

-------------------------------1129249456--

Rave party
>From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.

     This article is about a form of party. For other uses of the term, see 
rave (disambiguation).

A rave party, more often called a rave and sometimes called a free party, 
is typically an all-night dance event where DJs and other performers play 
electronic dance music and rave music. The slang expression rave was 
originally used by people of Caribbean descent in London during the 1960s 
to describe a party. In the late 1980s, the term began to be used to 
describe the subculture that grew out of the acid house movement that 
began in Chicago and flourished in the United Kingdom club scene.

The availability of drugs — particularly ecstasy — and/or alcoholic 
beverages have caused them to be targeted and criticized by law 
enforcement officials and parents' groups.
Contents
[hide]

     * 1 History
           o 1.1 1980s
           o 1.2 1990s: United Kingdom
           o 1.3 1990s: Europe
           o 1.4 2000s
     * 2 Rave culture in the USA
           o 2.1 Types of ravers
           o 2.2 Glowsticking
           o 2.3 Drug use
     * 3 Notable raves (rave series)
     * 4 See also
     * 5 External links

[edit]

History

Mainstream raves began in the mid to late 1980s as a product of, reaction 
to, and rebellion against, trends in popular music, nightclub culture, and 
commercial radio.

In an effort to maintain distance and secrecy from the mainstream club 
scene (or perhaps for lack of affordable, receptive venues), warehouses, 
rental halls, and outside locations most often served as raves' venues. In 
an effort to control and curtail rave parties, some police and 
governmental bodies effectively outlawed raves in some areas. Such laws 
consequently forced regional electronic dance music events to move to 
formal venues, such as nightclubs and amphitheatres. Some venues and 
jurisdictions additionally prohibited certain types of rave fashion and 
paraphernalia.

Early raves were completely do it yourself; only a small number of people 
contributed to event production and promotion. Self-styled production and 
promotion companies have increasingly organized raves; the "companies" 
were usually unofficial or loosely defined. Some of the more well-known 
rave promotion companies have included Brotherhood of Boom, Mushgroove, 
Freebass Society, and Pure. The companies promote their events by creating 
and distributing fliers and online bulletins.

As law enforcement agencies increasingly began paying attention to raves, 
concealing a party's location became important to an event's success. To 
that end, event organizers sometimes either promoted events solely by 
word-of-mouth, or would only reveal the date and location of the event to 
subscribers of an electronic mailing list or via voicemail. Some even went 
so far as to provide a series of clues or map checkpoints that ultimately 
led to the location of the rave.
[edit]

1980s

What could arguably be called raves existed in the early 1980s in the 
Ecstasy-fueled club scene in clubs like NRG, and in the drug-free, 
all-ages scene in Detroit at venues like The Music Institute. However, it 
was not until the mid to late 1980s that a wave of psychedelic and other 
electronic dance music, most notably acid house and techno, emerged and 
caught on in the clubs, warehouses and free-parties of London and 
Manchester, England. These early raves were called the Acid House Summers. 
They were mainstream events that attracted thousands of people (up to 
25,000) to come, dance and take LSD.

The noise and disturbance of thousands of people appearing at rural 
locations caused outrage in the national media. The government branded 
them Public Enemy number 1 and made the fine for holding an illegal party 
£20,000 and six months in prison. This, along with ecstasy becoming 
scarce, ended the early raves.

Police crackdowns on these often-illegal parties drove the scene into the 
countryside. The word "rave" somehow caught on to describe these 
semi-spontaneous weekend parties occurring at various locations outside 
the M25 Orbital motorway. (It was this that gave Orbital their name.)

The early rave scene also flourished underground in some U.S. cities such 
as San Francisco and Los Angeles and as word of the budding scene spread, 
raves quickly caught on in other cities such as San Diego and New York 
City and in major urban centers across the European continent.
[edit]

1990s: United Kingdom

Raves began to expand into a global phenomenon around 1989-1992, mostly on 
a grassroots basis: people who had traveled to attend the first raves in 
each region began setting up promotion companies, often informally, to 
organize their own parties. By the mid-1990s, major corporations were 
sponsoring events and adopting the scene's music and fashion for their 
"edgier" advertising, making the scene become more commercialized.

In 1994, the United Kingdom's Criminal Justice Bill passed as the Criminal 
Justice and Public Order Act which contained several sections designed to 
suppress the growing free-party and anti-road protest movements (sometimes 
embodied by ravers and travellers).

Sections 63, 64 & 65 of the Act targeted electronic dance music, defining 
it as "wholly or predominantly characterised by the emission of a 
succession of repetitive beats". The Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 
empowered police to arrest citizens who appeared to be: preparing to hold 
a rave (2 or more people), waiting for a rave to start (10+), or attending 
a rave (100+). Section 65 allows any uniformed constable who believes a 
person is on their way to a rave within a five-mile radius to stop them 
and direct them away from the area; noncompliant citizens may be subject 
to a maximum fine of £1,000.
[edit]

1990s: Europe

In Central Europe and other parts of the world, rave culture was becoming 
part of a new youth movement. DJs and electronic music producers such as 
Westbam proclaimed the existence of a "raving society" and promoted 
electronic music as legitimate competition for rock and roll. Indeed, 
electronic dance music and rave subculture became mass movements. Raves 
had tens of thousands of attendants, youth magazines featured styling tips 
and television networks launched music magazines on house and techno 
music. The annual Love Parade festivals in Berlin attracted more than one 
million partygoers between 1997 and 2000.
[edit]

2000s

In the early 2000s, the apparent number of illegal parties began to 
decline, and the number of sanctioned events seemed to be on the rise. The 
few constants in the scene include amplified electronic dance music, a 
vibrant social network built on the ethos of PLUR, percussive music and 
freeform dancing as a basis for drug use, and an ambivalent attitude 
toward "club drugs" such as ecstasy, methamphetamine, speed and Ketamine. 
However, increased cocaine usage, preponderance of adulterated ecstasy 
tablets and organized criminal activity has been detrimental to UK-based 
rave culture, although free parties are now on the rise again.

According to some long-time observers, rave music and its subculture began 
to stagnate by the end of the 1990s. The period of grassroots innovation 
and explosive growth and evolution was over; the flurry of passionate 
activity and the sense of international community were fading.

By the early 2000s, the terms "rave" and "raver" had fallen out of favor 
among many people in the electronic dance music community, particularly in 
Europe. Many Europeans returned to identifying themselves as "clubbers" 
rather than ravers. It became unfashionable among many electronic dance 
music aficionados to describe a party as a "rave", perhaps because the 
term had become bastardized. Some communities preferred the term 
"festival", while others simply referred to "parties". True raves, such as 
"Mayday", continued to occur for a time in Central Europe, with less 
constrictive laws allowing raves to continue in some countries long after 
the death of rave in the United Kingdom. Moreover, traditional rave 
paraphernalia, such as facemasks and pacifiers, ceased to be popular.

Raves and ravers continued to be villified by government authorities. For 
example, following a July 2005 violent raid by police on CzechTek, an 
annual techno music festival, the Czech Republic's Prime Minister said the 
festival's attendees were "no dancing children but dangerous people" and 
that many were "obsessed people with anarchist proclivities and 
international links," who "provoke massive violent demonstrations, fuelled 
by alcohol and drugs, against the peaceful society". [1]

As with any trend that runs on for more than a decade, the Rave scene has 
recently been harking back to the old days of warehouse parties, with a 
surge in "old school" club nights, particularly in the Jungle scene, with 
DJs and producers who had dropped out of the business playing sets of 
music from the founding days of their genre, and producing new records in 
that style. Clubs are increasingly going back to the grimy days of 
warehouses in terms of styling, rather than the interior designed venues 
of the late 90s.
[edit]

Rave culture in the USA
 	The examples and perspective in this article do not represent a 
world-wide view.
Please improve the article or discuss the issue on the talk page.

The upsurge in popularity of rave culture in the United States at a 
certain period in time often lends it characteristics common to a 
'movement' or Subculture. Although raves have existed in the United States 
as long as in any other country, the sudden explosion of mainstream 
popularity in the late nineties has lead to more common approaches to 
defining rave culture as a youth movement, in way which would not be 
possible in the UK or Europe due to a greater diversity amongst 
participants, countries and musical styles. Accordingly, many of the 
descriptions listed below are only appropriate to groups within the USA, 
and may even constitute generalisations within the US itself.

Although not universally agreed upon by those in the rave movement, some 
of the central tenets of the culture are said to be:

     * Openness: to not judge, condemn, or label other people's style of 
clothes, hair, makeup, costume, sexual orientation, musical preference, 
race, age, gender, class or income.
     * Acceptance: to not try to convince anyone of the rightness or 
wrongness associated with most human activities.
     * Positivism: to subscribe to the notion that if something makes 
someone happy without hurting someone else, then that something is okay. 
As such, fights or scuffles at a rave are rare.

Although not a constant among all ravers, one philosophy of rave culture 
is expressed through the acronym "PLUR", for Peace, Love, Unity, Respect. 
The concept itself is found particularly irritating by a large number of 
clubgoers, many of whom have been hoping the concept will fade into 
antiquity, to be replaced by better marketing terminology for positivist 
thinking, at some later date. As of yet the new terminology is still 
unknown, but we're hoping it comes on soon.

Ravers have been compared to both the hippies of the 1960s and new wavers 
of the 1980s due to their interest in non-violence and music.

Technology is inherently central to electronic music, and technological 
innovation has influenced rave subculture in many ways. For example, since 
loud music made it difficult to converse at raves, virtual communities 
were extremely important in rave subculture. Also, access to various 
affordable computer technologies empowered amateurs to compose or 
manipulate electronic music.

On rave parties doing dance tricks of all kinds is very popular. However 
these tricks are not always non-dangerous and can sometimes lead to 
damages, so they are not always tolerated by the organizers of the rave. 
What kind of tricks are allowed and what not differs from party to party.

In opposite to other youth cultures the rave scene is not deterrent for 
older people, which is noticeable by the fact, that there are not so few 
older people visiting technoparades.
[edit]

Types of ravers

Loosely defined terms generated by the rave community. They are 
generalized and not conclusive, complete, nor necessarily current.

     * Old school raver - refers to someone who has been a raver for some 
time, whereas a baby raver or a newbie refers to someone who is new to 
raving or at their first rave. Hardcore ravers are sometimes called pure 
ravers or true ravers or partykids. Something can be rave or have 
raveness.

     * Jaded raver - one who has been in the rave scene for a long time or 
someone who is growing tired of 'the scene' and raving. The newness of the 
experience has long ago worn off and they have noticed the seamier side. 
They may be pissed off at what the raving experience has become or they 
may be lackadaisical to certain aspects of raving that they once held a 
fondness for. Quite often a jaded raver will not appreciate the influx of 
new ravers into the scene because the new ravers are viewed as 
contributing to the scene's decay.

     * Club kid - tends to dress in bright colors and flashy, sometimes 
gaudy clothes, including leather and fur. They might also favor 
fluorescent plastic bead necklaces and candy bracelets. Many club kids 
also wear children's’ backpacks. Male club kids tend to dress in a more 
feminine manner. In some localities, a club kid is viewed as an outsider.

     * Candy raver/candykid - often wears brightly colored and child-like 
fashions such as day-glo wide leg pants, black light reactive or 
glow-in-the-dark bracelets/necklaces and t-shirts featuring cartoon 
characters. They wear homemade bracelets and necklaces made of plastic, 
glass, or felt beads or candy. Candy ravers or candykids are often found 
exchanging or giving out small gifts. These small gifts will usually be 
hugs, toys, glowsticks, drugs, CDs, necklaces, bracelets, and/or candy.

     * Liquid dancer - a person who performs liquid dancing (a fluid 
gesticulation of the arms and body)

     * Junglist refers to an urban-based sub-culture of the rave scene 
defined by Drum and Bass (DnB) / Jungle music. Junglists often detest 
mainstream rave music and prefer darker and deeper vibes. Hostility 
between ravers and junglists has lead to a disconnect between the two 
groups. Many junglists refuse to refer to themselves as 'ravers' because 
of the drug connotations and the rave style of dress and attitude. Many 
junglists were once doe-eyed ravers or even candy kids who, after becoming 
jaded, left that part of the scene.

[edit]

Glowsticking

Some ravers participate in a light-oriented dance called glowsticking, and 
a similar dance called glowstringing, or poi. These dances, however, are 
independent of the raving community, and often the stereotyped association 
may be resented. Glow sticks in the dark stimulate the pupils and it is 
claimed that they relieve the effects of Ecstasy. Therefore at some rave 
places they are presented as "safety materials". On the other hand, in 
some cases the sales of glow sticks during rave parties was presented as a 
proof of illegal drug use. Glow sticks have been considered drug 
paraphernalia because they are used in "blowing (someone) up," or giving 
someone on Ecstasy a "light show." The recipient of the "light show" sits 
or stands facing the show giver who moves the glow sticks away and towards 
the face of the recipient in various stylized movements. This lightshow is 
sometimes accompanied by a facial massage and/or by blowing mentholated 
vapors into the nose, mouth, and eyes of the recipient. This is intended 
to increase the effects of Ecstasy.

However glowsticks can be used on most raves for interesting dancing 
effects, because most raves, except of some open air raves as 
technoparades are in dark or nearly dark rooms. Because rave parties are 
popular at people with intensions to show dances, the use of glowsticks 
can give material for creative freestyle dance.
[edit]

Drug use

In the U.S. the subculture has been branded by the mainstream media and 
law enforcement agencies as a purely drug-centric culture similar to the 
hippies of the 1960s. As a result, ravers have been effectively run out of 
business in many areas (Media Awareness Project). Although they continue 
in major coastal cities like New York and LA, and notably the Winter Music 
Conference in Florida, most other areas have been relegated to 
word-of-mouth-only underground parties and nightclub events. In some parts 
of Europe, raves are common and mainstream, although they are now more 
often known as "festivals," highlighting multiple acts over a whole day 
period, and often including non-dance music acts.

Groups that have addressed drug use at raves include the Electronic Music 
Defence and Education Fund (EMDEF) and DanceSafe, which advocate harm 
reduction approaches. Paradoxically, drug safety literature (such as those 
distributed by DanceSafe) are used as evidence of condoned drug use (EMDEF 
press release). Other groups, such as Drug Free America Foundation, Inc., 
characterize raves as being rife with gang activity, rape, robbery, and 
drug-related deaths. [2]

In 2005, Antonio Maria Costa, Executive Director of the United Nations 
Office on Drugs and Crime, advocated drug testing on highways as a 
countermeasure against drug use at raves[3].
[edit]

Wikipedia for "rave music"

Rave music
>From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.

Rave music consists of forms of electronic music for dancing that are 
associated with the rave scene. Most often, it is used to describe techno 
music that depends heavily on samples and is high energy, upbeat, and 
dance inducing.

Rave music got its start in Britain in the mid 1980s, closely following 
the acid house phenomenon. Initially "rave music" was considered a 
particular style that was a combination of fast breakbeat and more 
hardcore forms of techno. Early 1990s efforts by Nebula 2, The Prodigy 
(The Prodigy Experience), Utah Saints and The Shamen (En-Tact) were 
quintessential "rave music".

By the early 2000s, the term was used more generically to mean any one of 
a number of different styles (or combinations thereof) that might be 
played at a rave party. In this sense, rave music is more associated with 
an event than a particular genre, per se. At a rave there can be different 
"arenas" or areas which play different styles of rave music. Very large 
raves called massives may include ten or more separate arenas, each with 
their own music style.

Raver styles of music continue to grow and evolve. Some genres and an 
iconic artist include (not an exhaustive list):

     * house styles: progressive house - John Digweed, Bad Boy Bill
     * trance - Armin van Buuren, Ferry Corsten, DJ Tiësto, Paul van Dyk
     * Goa trance - Hallucinogen, Astral Projection
     * drum and bass/jungle - Andy C, Goldie, Dieselboy
     * breaks - The Chemical Brothers, The Prodigy, Adam Freeland, Baby 
Anne
     * hardcore techno styles - Happy hardcore, Hardcore trance, Gabba, 
Luke Slater, Dave Clarke

Non-dance styles which might be heard in a rave "chill-out" room include:

     * ambient music - Brian Eno, Harold Budd, The Orb
     * IDM - Aphex Twin, Autechre

Some ravers are selective between genres, showing little or no interest in 
one area while finding great satisfaction and joy in another. House often 
has roots in funk and disco while trance has its roots in new age and 
symphonic music. Many DJs mix genres, remix existing sounds, or leave 
electronic music entirely.

A new form of rave is appearing based on the genre "Makina" mainly 
produced in spain but also in Italy, Germany and France, it has exploded 
in the North East of England with many clubs and all night raves.

Source: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rave_music

Wikipedia for "rave act"

RAVE Act
>From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.

The RAVE Act (an acronym for 'Reducing Americans' Vulnerability to 
Ecstasy') was a bill (S.2633) proposed, but not passed, during the 107th 
US Congress [1]. It was later passed (S.226) as the Illicit Drug 
Anti-Proliferation Act during the 108th US Congress, mostly unchanged and 
backed by the same sponsors.[2] The original RAVE Act attracted a fair 
amount of attention and protest within the electronic music community, and 
although the act was ultimately passed under a different name, the term 
"RAVE Act" is quite well known and will be used in this discussion.

The original bill was introduced by Senator Joe Biden (D-DE) in 2002. The 
key provisions of the RAVE Act are modifications to the US Code (22 USC 
856) [3], creating new civil penalties for owners or users of property 
upon which illegal drug trafficking activities are conducted. In 
particular, defendants could be fined up to $250,000, or double their 
gross receipts, whichever is greater.

The announced intent of the RAVE Act was to stem the distribution of 
controlled substances. However, opponents have argued that the bill 
unfairly depicts "rave culture" as so inseparable from "drug culture" as 
to legitimize the former as a target of drug enforcement. The Act is 
considered by some in the rave and electronic music community to be 
evidence of a "moral panic" regarding raves.

Opponents' complaints against the RAVE Act included:

     * It is worded broadly enough that virtually any person conducting a 
trade at a rave could be liable under the law, including such innocuous 
activities as selling, or even handing out for free, bottled water. In 
particular, the 'Offenses' section of the original bill introduced 
language making it a violation to "profit from, or make available for use, 
with or without compensation, [any] place for the purpose of [...] using a 
controlled substance".

     * Along the same lines, it could be considered to criminalize and thus 
discourage harm reduction measures, such as distributing condoms or 
offering testing of possibly illicit drugs to determine if they are some 
other, potentially dangerous, substance. Under this interpretation, if 
rave organizers accept the likelihood that some ravers will take Ecstasy 
no matter whether it is condoned or discouraged, the organizers must face 
a choice of: knowing drug use will happen and not making any preparations 
for it; making harm reduction measures such as chill-out rooms available 
but operating them at a loss; or making harm reduction measures available 
and facing the prospect of being prosecuted for them.

     * It fails to distinguish between illegally and legally conducted 
raves, or for that matter, concerts or events of any kind. A common 
speculation in the electronic music community was that the Act could be 
used to fine a concert promoter for "allowing" an illicit marijuana 
transaction during a concert, even if the promoter took security measures 
to prevent such transactions from taking place.

Rebuttals to these complaints included:

     * The Act does not criminalize any of these activities. Defendants 
could be fined, perhaps substantially, but would not face jail time for 
breaking the law.

     * The RAVE Act includes "knowingly and intentionally" in its language, 
which would seem to put the burden of proof on the government in any such 
case. It would thus not imply penalties for the mere presence of vendors 
at an event where drug trafficking takes place.

The original RAVE Act (but not the eventually passed bill) contained a 
"Findings" section which stated the findings of Congress as reasons to 
pass the bill. The Findings section was rather harsh and sweeping in its 
indictment of raves in general, and was likely the cause of much of the 
outcry over the bill in the rave community. Point 4 of this section 
implied that providing security for a rave was an attempt to portray an 
unsafe event as safe:

     [Rave promoters] even go so far as to hire off-duty, uniformed police 
officers to patrol outside of the venue to give parents the impression 
that the event is safe.[4]

This did not address the fact that hiring off-duty police officers for 
security is a practice common to many social gatherings, or the 
possibility that rave organizers might be hiring such security not just to 
create an appearance of safety but to actually provide a safer 
environment. Point 6 was undoubtedly a source of concern for rave vendors:

     Because rave promoters know that Ecstasy causes the body temperature 
in a user to rise and as a result causes the user to become very thirsty, 
many rave promoters facilitate and profit from flagrant drug use at rave 
parties or events by selling over-priced bottles of water and charging 
entrance fees to 'chill-rooms' where users can cool down.[5]

The "Findings" section was eventually deleted from the Act as passed, and 
Senator Biden was careful to explain why:

     Critics of the bill have also claimed that it would provide a 
disincentive for promoters to take steps to protect the public health of 
their patrons including providing water or air conditioned rooms, making 
sure that there is an ambulance on the premises, etc. That is not my 
intention. And to underscore that fact, I plan to remove the findings, 
which is the only place in the bill where these items are mentioned, from 
the bill. Certainly there are legitimate reasons for selling water, having 
a room where people can cool down after dancing, or having an ambulance on 
hand. Clearly, the presence of any of these things is not enough to 
signify that an event is "for the purpose of" drug use.[6]

Sourc:
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RAVE_Act

Still canâ€™t believe Home Base is actually gone. Ah man I have so many memories there. My first party there was metropolis back in 99, I remember those days like it was yesterday. I was playing Zelda on N64 when my sister asked me if I wanted to go with her to a party, I was like wtf. She then told me there was going to be music lots of people and it would all be fun. I was still reluctant to go at first, but after days of talking I finally decided to go with her. I spent the whole day b4 Metropolis making beads and what not with my sis and her friend. Her friend made me like these beaded star glasses type things, so after that we knocked out and got ready for the day. I got up the following morning and started playing my video games for a good bit till I had to get ready for the party. Me, my sis, her friend and my mom all went up to Frisco to post up before Metropolis. My mom just drove us she didnâ€™t go into the party with us. So we posted up, walking around the city till its
 time to head out to the party. When we got there I was just blown away by everything I saw, from the entrance to the inside of the party. I thought it was kind of weird at first that there was a group of adults with pacifiers in their mouths}8^). People buckin in the corners, crap loads of people dancing to the music just about anything you could think of you saw it. Thatâ€™s what I like about parties, you got a sense of freedom everyone was kick back, and you can be yourself. It was like an adventure I got lost then found my sister, then got lost again then found her again. Itâ€™s the memories of the scene the memories of the parties Iâ€™ve been to that kept me going. Was always nice to go to a party to hear the Dj lay it down. Seeing that video trips me out. That place is gone, I wonder what they going to do with that area now.

Memories going up in smoke it is a shame

Macadio

Ahhhh big flyers....at least they're good for a few things...fanning
yourself off, protecting your nice clean phat pants from floor covered in
rave slime, sheilding your eyes from the sun...etc. I remember when i first
started to see the huge ass flyers up in Portland back in 97 i think. Up
until then i had only really ever come across smallish pocket sized flyers.
Usually they were hand drawn and photo copied, occasionally you'd come
across an actual flyer where the graphic were still pretty minimal and
cheesy, but you got the info. One night at an outdoor party in the middle o=
f
nowhere, my friend and i took a few hits of acid and were having a good
time. We were getting flyers all through out the party, and i started to
notice that each flyer was getting a little bigger then the flyer before it=
.
It wasn't too long before i turned to my friend and mentioned my new
discovery, and cracked a joke about how the flyers can't get any bigger.
They were getting to be almost too big to fit in to the huge packets of my
raver pants. No sooner had i said that, i turned around and was face to fac=
e
with another person handing me a flyer. This wasn't a flyer, It was a book.
It was a flyer to Cyberfest (if i remember correctly). My jaw hit the floor
and my friend and i stared at each other in awe. We were starting to wonder
if the huge size was all in our acid laced minds. We started to flip throug=
h
the many pages of this flyer. I think it was like 6 or 7 pages of
almost 8.5"x11"
paper. It was insane. We couldnt believe it and of course right in the mids=
t
of our bewilderment we saw spot lights sweeping back and forth across the
crowd. Awwwww shit here come the Po Po's. This being my friends first "rave=
"
he wasnt sure what to make of this and started to walk back to the car
dragging me along with. I had to grab his arm and tell him to calm down and
to not freak out like that cause it'll just make things worse. They probabl=
y
weren't going to do anything but tell everyone to go home. We stuck it out =
a
little to see what was going on, and thankfully all they came to do was to
make the party kids put out the fire they had created to keep warm. Once
that was out, they left and we continued to dance the night away.
 Anyway, that was the day i knew the face of raving was altered forever.
Flyers big enough to make for decent reading and wallpapering. crazy acid
shit man...crazy acid shit.
 --
Chester Copperpot

"Goonies never say die!"
"Meth Monsters are my Anti-Drug"
"I feel like I'm taking crazy pills"

 On 10/13/05, LittleEtoile@aol.com <LittleEtoile@aol.com> wrote:
>
> Seconded. Thanks Macadio. : )
>
> And though I certainly had, like Terry, a love-hate relationship with
> Homebase, you can't deny the profound impact it had on the scene during
> that time
> period. If/when someone writes a book about our bay area rave culture,
> homebase will certainly have it's own chapter. : )
>
> When I first started partying in '98, I was caught by Son (aka BBoiBreaks=
)
> with a FeelGood flyer in my hands. He said to me, "Honey.. if the flyer i=
s
> big
> enough to sit on- DON'T GO!"
>
> I stuck to it for the most part, so to record I can count the number of
> massives I've been to on one hand, but I made a few exceptions, with
> Homebases's
> Love Affair '99 and Megabuzz '99 being two of the few.
>
>
> Anyway, I can't believe no one has mentioned the space my first party was
> at- J.J. Newberry's! Weee!
>
> Good times. Any one remember that place? I remember being outside as we
> waited to pay and getting butterflies in my stomach as I noticed the
> rebellious
> symbolism of all the windows blacked out with garbage bags. THUMP THUMP
> THUMP.
> This was some underground shit.
>
> I was suddenly struck with the profound knowledge that when I walked
> through
> those doors, I was going to be apart of something that would make history=
.
> "Have fun," the doorman smiled. "The shits going off in there! You're in
> for a
> good night!"
>
> Oh, the enchantment of that first sight as I entered. I don't know that
> you
> can truly capture the delicious experience that hits you as you walk into
> your first rave. It's still etched in my head, over seven years later.
>
> I remember that at the time, my friends and I had no idea what the
> painter's
> masks were for, but somehow we had the idea that people used them to huff
> NO2. Oh, the naivety of newbies. ; )
>
> And well... fuck it. In remembrance of Homebase, I give you my
> long-retired
> SFR sign-off:
>
> TiCkLeS aNd GiGgLeS,
> ~*SwEeT PeA*~
>
> RIP Homebase
>

how about the masonic temple, for the r.i.p. list? has anybody mentioned

On 10/14/05, Chester Copperpot <chester.copperpot420@gmail.com> wrote:
>
> Ahhhh big flyers....at least they're good for a few things...fanning
> yourself off, protecting your nice clean phat pants from floor covered in
> rave slime, sheilding your eyes from the sun...etc. I remember when i
> first
> started to see the huge ass flyers up in Portland back in 97 i think. Up
> until then i had only really ever come across smallish pocket sized
> flyers.
> Usually they were hand drawn and photo copied, occasionally you'd come
> across an actual flyer where the graphic were still pretty minimal and
> cheesy, but you got the info. One night at an outdoor party in the middle
> of
> nowhere, my friend and i took a few hits of acid and were having a good
> time. We were getting flyers all through out the party, and i started to
> notice that each flyer was getting a little bigger then the flyer before
> it.
> It wasn't too long before i turned to my friend and mentioned my new
> discovery, and cracked a joke about how the flyers can't get any bigger.
> They were getting to be almost too big to fit in to the huge packets of m=
y
> raver pants. No sooner had i said that, i turned around and was face to
> face
> with another person handing me a flyer. This wasn't a flyer, It was a
> book.
> It was a flyer to Cyberfest (if i remember correctly). My jaw hit the
> floor
> and my friend and i stared at each other in awe. We were starting to
> wonder
> if the huge size was all in our acid laced minds. We started to flip
> through
> the many pages of this flyer. I think it was like 6 or 7 pages of
> almost 8.5"x11"
> paper. It was insane. We couldnt believe it and of course right in the
> midst
> of our bewilderment we saw spot lights sweeping back and forth across the
> crowd. Awwwww shit here come the Po Po's. This being my friends first
> "rave"
> he wasnt sure what to make of this and started to walk back to the car
> dragging me along with. I had to grab his arm and tell him to calm down
> and
> to not freak out like that cause it'll just make things worse. They
> probably
> weren't going to do anything but tell everyone to go home. We stuck it ou=
t
> a
> little to see what was going on, and thankfully all they came to do was t=
o
> make the party kids put out the fire they had created to keep warm. Once
> that was out, they left and we continued to dance the night away.
> Anyway, that was the day i knew the face of raving was altered forever.
> Flyers big enough to make for decent reading and wallpapering. crazy acid
> shit man...crazy acid shit.
> --
> Chester Copperpot
>
> "Goonies never say die!"
> "Meth Monsters are my Anti-Drug"
> "I feel like I'm taking crazy pills"

MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: multipart/alternative; boundary="NextPart_Webmail_9m3u9jl4l_1761_1129310655_0"
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] (nrr) Nostalgia: Changing times, artists lost or reborn

--NextPart_Webmail_9m3u9jl4l_1761_1129310655_0
Content-Type: text/plain
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

I love the music from previous decades such as the 70s and 80s. I also enjoy listening to 1940s music on XM satellite radio.
 
So today I was listening to some older 80s tracks on minidisc (a format that did not take off in the US). Specifically, I heard Alison Moyet (formerly of Yazoo) singing, “Honey for the Bees” and “Love Resurrection.” When she was with Yazoo she sang that popular song, “Situation” from the album Upstairs At Eric's (1982). It went something like this:
 
Blue eyed dressed for every situation
Moving through the doorway of a nation
Pick me up and shake the doubt, baby I can't do without
(Move out) don't mess around, (move out) you bring me down
(Move out) how you get about, don't make a sound, just move out
 
Alison Moyet has a new album, Voice (US release date: 6 September 2005). It has a light classical sound backed by an orchestra and arranged by a movie composer. You could say this is a disco-pop diva dream come true, an album recorded in front of an orchestra.
 
I also pulled out the soundtrack for Footloose, and listened to the title track by Kenny Loggins. What fun it was to hear this again! 
"You can fly if you’d only cut loose, footloose; Kick off your Sunday shoes"
Kenny Loggins is touring the country with Messina and he has a relatively new album, too (It’s About Time, release date 2003).
 
Finally, I had to hear “Self Control” by Laura Brannigan, a good dance song that didn’t make it far. However, Laura Brannigan almost made it to #1 on the Billboard pop chart in 1982 with a song called “Gloria.” You probably know this one:
Gloria!
I think they got your number!
I think they got the alias 
that you've been living under!
 
Back in the 80s, she was all over TV, promoting that song, pushing her arm up into the air, punctuating the beats. Laura died in her sleep in 2004 from a brain aneurysm, very sad to lose such talent.
 
I can remember dancing around the house to these tracks but now they seem a little old-fashioned--I still enjoy them, but I realize my tastes have moved on to harder or progressive beats from genres like D&B or house and so on.

Dance on,
GregVP
 
--NextPart_Webmail_9m3u9jl4l_1761_1129310655_0--

Mailing-List: contact sfraves-help@hyperreal.org; run by ezmlm

>album Upstairs At Eric's (1982). It went something like this:
>
>Blue eyed dressed for every situation
>Moving through the doorway of a nation
>Pick me up and shake the doubt, baby I can't do without
>(Move out) don't mess around, (move out) you bring me down
>(Move out) how you get about, don't make a sound, just move out
>
>Alison Moyet has a new album, Voice (US release date: 6 September 2005). It

>composer. You could say this is a disco-pop diva dream come true, an album 
>recorded in front of an orchestra.

>track by Kenny Loggins. What fun it was to hear this again!
>"You can fly if you’d only cut loose, footloose; Kick off your Sunday 
>shoes"

>new album, too (It’s About Time, release date 2003).
>
>Finally, I had to hear “Self Control” by Laura Brannigan, a good dance song 
>that didn’t make it far. However, Laura Brannigan almost made it to #1 on 
>the Billboard pop chart in 1982 with a song called “Gloria.” You probably 
>know this one:
>Gloria!
>I think they got your number!
>I think they got the alias
>that you've been living under!
>
>Back in the 80s, she was all over TV, promoting that song, pushing her arm 
>up into the air, punctuating the beats. Laura died in her sleep in 2004 
>from a brain aneurysm, very sad to lose such talent.
>
>I can remember dancing around the house to these tracks but now they seem a 
>little old-fashioned--I still enjoy them, but I realize my tastes have 
>moved on to harder or progressive beats from genres like D&B or house and 
>so on.
>
>Dance on,
>GregVP

Thanks to blooshaman for suggesting Supperclub tonight (which is only 
10 bucks), but I already bought a 20 dollar ticket for Miss Kittin at 
Mezzanine, as suggested by bird415.  Yikes!  20 bucks!  but I went to 
her website

http://www.misskittin.com/noises/frameset.html

and listened to the Autumn 2004 mix.  The Summer Mix 2005 starts out 
with a long, tedious ostinato that annoyed me without turning me on, so 
I moved to an earlier mix, and Summer 2004 rewarded me well.  It is the 
first DJ mix I've ever heard that gives me honest pleasure as pure 
music all the way through a whole CD.  Ah, I am revealing myself as a 
newbie and stuffy academic...  but anyway, I decided Miss Kittin's 
worth the 20 bucks, and am really stoked about the show tonight.  
Thanks for the tip, Greg!   -BlueFire

-----Original Message-----
From: gregvp@comcast.net [mailto:gregvp@comcast.net] 
Sent: Friday, October 14, 2005 10:24 AM
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Subject: [sfraves] (nrr) Nostalgia: Changing times, artists lost or reborn

I love the music from previous decades such as the 70s and 80s. I also enjoy
listening to 1940s music on XM satellite radio.
 
So today I was listening to some older 80s tracks on minidisc (a format that
did not take off in the US). Specifically, I heard Alison Moyet (formerly of
Yazoo) singing, "Honey for the Bees" and "Love Resurrection." When she was
with Yazoo she sang that popular song, "Situation" from the album Upstairs
At Eric's (1982). It went something like this:
 
Blue eyed dressed for every situation
Moving through the doorway of a nation
Pick me up and shake the doubt, baby I can't do without
(Move out) don't mess around, (move out) you bring me down
(Move out) how you get about, don't make a sound, just move out
 
Alison Moyet has a new album, Voice (US release date: 6 September 2005). It
has a light classical sound backed by an orchestra and arranged by a movie
composer. You could say this is a disco-pop diva dream come true, an album
recorded in front of an orchestra.
 
I also pulled out the soundtrack for Footloose, and listened to the title
track by Kenny Loggins. What fun it was to hear this again! 
"You can fly if you'd only cut loose, footloose; Kick off your Sunday shoes"
Kenny Loggins is touring the country with Messina and he has a relatively
new album, too (It's About Time, release date 2003).
 
Finally, I had to hear "Self Control" by Laura Brannigan, a good dance song
that didn't make it far. However, Laura Brannigan almost made it to #1 on
the Billboard pop chart in 1982 with a song called "Gloria." You probably
know this one:
Gloria!
I think they got your number!
I think they got the alias 
that you've been living under!
 
Back in the 80s, she was all over TV, promoting that song, pushing her arm
up into the air, punctuating the beats. Laura died in her sleep in 2004 from
a brain aneurysm, very sad to lose such talent.
 
I can remember dancing around the house to these tracks but now they seem a
little old-fashioned--I still enjoy them, but I realize my tastes have moved
on to harder or progressive beats from genres like D&B or house and so on.

Dance on,
GregVP

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Yaz and Yazoo are both correct, and are the same band. Yazoo was their
original name in the UK, but when they were marketed in the US their name
was changed to Yaz for some reason.
 Upstairs at Eric's =3D essential listening.
 --->G

Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

Dear Friends of Erowid,

This Announcement message (#60, Oct 14 2005) can be read online at:
http://www.erowid.org/general/announce/announce60_10-14-05.shtml

One of Erowid's two main laptops died last week.  We're now in
need of a functional laptop in the very short term and can't afford
to buy one.  We're asking whether someone in the community
might have a notebook computer less than three or four years old
that they would consider donating to Erowid.

This machine would be used by Sylvia, one of Erowid's three key crew
members and Contributing Editor of Erowid Extracts.  The machine needs
to be fairly recent as it will be used for HTML, SSH, Photoshop,
InDesign, Office, Firefox, and (the biggest resource hog) Eclipse.  It
could be either Windows or Macintosh, but it needs to meet the
following specs:

Minimum Requirements:
--------------------------------------
1) 700 MHz or faster CPU
2) 256 MB RAM (or expandable to that size)
3) 1024 x 768 + screen resolution
4) 2+ hours of battery life or ability to expand
5) 20 GB hard drive
6) Wireless capability or open PCMCIA slot
7) Functioning audio in and out
8) Ability to run WinXP or OSX.4
9) External VGA / Monitor hookup
10) Under 7 pounds, including battery

Preferred Requirements
--------------------------------------
1) 1 GHz+ CPU
2) 1 GB RAM (or expandable to that size)
6) Wireless built in (not PCMCIA)
10) Under 6 pounds including battery

The machine would used for working on Erowid remotely, transcribing
interviews, researching and editing documents, and managing volunteers.
This would often be Sylvia's main interface to the world, so something
that works well is important.  We're happy to reinstall the OS, upgrade
RAM, and do other light upgrades and maintenance.

We need to find something in the next month and need help making
that happen.  If you have a notebook you're not using or are looking for
an excuse to upgrade yours, please reply to this email or contact
donations@erowid.org.

Thanks for your support,

"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] Spare a Laptop?

--=====================_999750==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

Dear Friends of Erowid,

This Announcement message (#60, Oct 14 2005) can be read online at:
http://www.erowid.org/general/announce/announce60_10-14-05.shtml

One of Erowid's two main laptops died last week.  We're now in
need of a functional laptop in the very short term and can't afford
to buy one.  We're asking whether someone in the community
might have a notebook computer less than three or four years old
that they would consider donating to Erowid.

This machine would be used by Sylvia, one of Erowid's three key crew
members and Contributing Editor of Erowid Extracts.  The machine needs
to be fairly recent as it will be used for HTML, SSH, Photoshop,
InDesign, Office, Firefox, and (the biggest resource hog) Eclipse.  It
could be either Windows or Macintosh, but it needs to meet the
following specs:

Minimum Requirements:
--------------------------------------
1) 700 MHz or faster CPU
2) 256 MB RAM (or expandable to that size)
3) 1024 x 768 + screen resolution
4) 2+ hours of battery life or ability to expand
5) 20 GB hard drive
6) Wireless capability or open PCMCIA slot
7) Functioning audio in and out
8) Ability to run WinXP or OSX.4
9) External VGA / Monitor hookup
10) Under 7 pounds, including battery

Preferred Requirements
--------------------------------------
1) 1 GHz+ CPU
2) 1 GB RAM (or expandable to that size)
6) Wireless built in (not PCMCIA)
10) Under 6 pounds including battery

The machine would used for working on Erowid remotely, transcribing
interviews, researching and editing documents, and managing volunteers.
This would often be Sylvia's main interface to the world, so something
that works well is important.  We're happy to reinstall the OS, upgrade
RAM, and do other light upgrades and maintenance.

We need to find something in the next month and need help making
that happen.  If you have a notebook you're not using or are looking for
an excuse to upgrade yours, please reply to this email or contact
donations@erowid.org.

Thanks for your support,
Earth, Fire, & Sylvia



MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo

Tribenet: 
<http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Cool Laser and pyro massive video

Unfortnately most of the VJ videos out there are reels
of 2D and 3D media created by the VJs rather than
video of people at a party interacting with the
graphics and sound.  The original laser/pyro clip was
really good at showing how the display worked in the
context of the party I thought.  If you check out
Bill's previous book, you'll see that he's interested
in how the way music interacts with the mind impacts
its social effects etc.  Its that aspect of VJing,
where its really an integral part of the experience of
the party, that I've been trying to tell him about.

Regards,

Peter

On 10/14/05, Apollo <apollo@speakeasy.org> wrote:
>
> Dear Friends of Erowid,
>
> This Announcement message (#60, Oct 14 2005) can be read online at:
> http://www.erowid.org/general/announce/announce60_10-14-05.shtml
>
> One of Erowid's two main laptops died last week. We're now in
> need of a functional laptop in the very short term and can't afford
> to buy one. We're asking whether someone in the community
> might have a notebook computer less than three or four years old
> that they would consider donating to Erowid.
>
> This machine would be used by Sylvia, one of Erowid's three key crew
> members and Contributing Editor of Erowid Extracts. The machine needs
> to be fairly recent as it will be used for HTML, SSH, Photoshop,
> InDesign, Office, Firefox, and (the biggest resource hog) Eclipse. It
> could be either Windows or Macintosh, but it needs to meet the
> following specs:
>
> Minimum Requirements:
> --------------------------------------
> 1) 700 MHz or faster CPU
> 2) 256 MB RAM (or expandable to that size)
> 3) 1024 x 768 + screen resolution
> 4) 2+ hours of battery life or ability to expand
> 5) 20 GB hard drive
> 6) Wireless capability or open PCMCIA slot
> 7) Functioning audio in and out
> 8) Ability to run WinXP or OSX.4
> 9) External VGA / Monitor hookup
> 10) Under 7 pounds, including battery
>
> Preferred Requirements
> --------------------------------------
> 1) 1 GHz+ CPU
> 2) 1 GB RAM (or expandable to that size)
> 6) Wireless built in (not PCMCIA)
> 10) Under 6 pounds including battery
>
> The machine would used for working on Erowid remotely, transcribing
> interviews, researching and editing documents, and managing volunteers.
> This would often be Sylvia's main interface to the world, so something
> that works well is important. We're happy to reinstall the OS, upgrade
> RAM, and do other light upgrades and maintenance.

> > One of Erowid's two main laptops died last week.
> We're now in
> > need of a functional laptop in the very short term
> and can't afford
> > to buy one. We're asking whether someone in the
> community
> > might have a notebook computer less than three or
> four years old
> > that they would consider donating to Erowid.
> >
> > This machine would be used by Sylvia, one of
> Erowid's three key crew
> > members and Contributing Editor of Erowid
> Extracts. The machine needs
> > to be fairly recent as it will be used for HTML,
> SSH, Photoshop,
> > InDesign, Office, Firefox, and (the biggest
> resource hog) Eclipse. It
> > could be either Windows or Macintosh, but it needs
> to meet the
> > following specs:
> >
> > Minimum Requirements:
> > --------------------------------------
> > 1) 700 MHz or faster CPU
> > 2) 256 MB RAM (or expandable to that size)
> > 3) 1024 x 768 + screen resolution
> > 4) 2+ hours of battery life or ability to expand
> > 5) 20 GB hard drive
> > 6) Wireless capability or open PCMCIA slot
> > 7) Functioning audio in and out
> > 8) Ability to run WinXP or OSX.4
> > 9) External VGA / Monitor hookup
> > 10) Under 7 pounds, including battery
> >
> > Preferred Requirements
> > --------------------------------------
> > 1) 1 GHz+ CPU
> > 2) 1 GB RAM (or expandable to that size)
> > 6) Wireless built in (not PCMCIA)
> > 10) Under 6 pounds including battery
> >
> > The machine would used for working on Erowid
> remotely, transcribing
> > interviews, researching and editing documents, and
> managing volunteers.
> > This would often be Sylvia's main interface to the
> world, so something
> > that works well is important. We're happy to

> > RAM, and do other light upgrades and maintenance.

> On 10/14/05, Chester Copperpot <chester.copperpot420@gmail.com> wrote:
>>
>> Ahhhh big flyers....at least they're good for a few things...fanning
>> yourself off, protecting your nice clean phat pants from floor covered in
>> rave slime, sheilding your eyes from the sun...etc. I remember when i
>> first
>> started to see the huge ass flyers up in Portland back in 97 i think. Up
>> until then i had only really ever come across smallish pocket sized
>> flyers.
>> Usually they were hand drawn and photo copied, occasionally you'd come
>> across an actual flyer where the graphic were still pretty minimal and
>> cheesy, but you got the info. One night at an outdoor party in the middle
>> of
>> nowhere, my friend and i took a few hits of acid and were having a good
>> time. We were getting flyers all through out the party, and i started to
>> notice that each flyer was getting a little bigger then the flyer before
>> it.
>> It wasn't too long before i turned to my friend and mentioned my new
>> discovery, and cracked a joke about how the flyers can't get any bigger.
>> They were getting to be almost too big to fit in to the huge packets of my
>> raver pants. No sooner had i said that, i turned around and was face to
>> face
>> with another person handing me a flyer. This wasn't a flyer, It was a
>> book.
>> It was a flyer to Cyberfest (if i remember correctly). My jaw hit the
>> floor
>> and my friend and i stared at each other in awe. We were starting to
>> wonder
>> if the huge size was all in our acid laced minds. We started to flip
>> through
>> the many pages of this flyer. I think it was like 6 or 7 pages of
>> almost 8.5"x11"
>> paper. It was insane. We couldnt believe it and of course right in the
>> midst
>> of our bewilderment we saw spot lights sweeping back and forth across the
>> crowd. Awwwww shit here come the Po Po's. This being my friends first
>> "rave"
>> he wasnt sure what to make of this and started to walk back to the car
>> dragging me along with. I had to grab his arm and tell him to calm down
>> and
>> to not freak out like that cause it'll just make things worse. They
>> probably
>> weren't going to do anything but tell everyone to go home. We stuck it out
>> a
>> little to see what was going on, and thankfully all they came to do was to
>> make the party kids put out the fire they had created to keep warm. Once
>> that was out, they left and we continued to dance the night away.
>> Anyway, that was the day i knew the face of raving was altered forever.
>> Flyers big enough to make for decent reading and wallpapering. crazy acid
>> shit man...crazy acid shit.
>> --
>> Chester Copperpot
