"...

Positively Malachy
The godfather of Bay Area rave and house culture speaks.
By Amanda Nowinski

HUNDREDS OF CARS left the city well past midnight on Monday, March 8, 
1993, in search of the Full Moon rave. By 3 a.m., alongside Highway 1, 
we'd found it.

Equipped with nothing more than water, blankets, and smokes, we stood at 
the edge of the cliffs at Bonny Doon, gazing down at the swirling masses 
of people on the beach. We were buzzing with anticipation as we raced down 
the sand cliffs, guided only by the white light of the moon and a few 
raging bonfires. Boom. Boom. Boom. Like magic, the sound system kicked in, 
and everyone on the beach simultaneously jumped to their feet. At last, 
the house music ceremony could begin.

It was, all in all, a typically wild full moon night. Dancers and drummers 
pounded the sand flat as cement around the makeshift DJ booth as dogs 
frolicked, naked people dipped into the ocean, and groups of friends and 
strangers gathered by fires and tents, all united by this new, 
euphorically pagan experience. We felt acutely alive. People held hands 
and shared water, cigarettes, jackets, joints, blankets – whatever was 
needed, someone would surely provide. We were highly conscious of being in 
this moment together, although we didn't know exactly what it all meant.

As the sun rose we collected our belongings and posses, kissed everyone 
good-bye, and struggled up the cliffs. We sat in silence riding back to 
the city, exhausted and entirely content.

Later that morning, Malachy O'Brien, a founder of the Full Moon and 
Come-Unity parties, searched for his ride back to the city. It had already 
left. So Malachy helped the remaining crew carry the sound system up to a 
van. After the vehicle was packed, Malachy and his dog Una climbed into 
the back, directly behind the sound system and generator. The van puttered 
away toward the city.

Strange how fate operates.

"I always wonder why it all happened," says Malachy, from inside his 
small, windowless room on the ground floor of a South of Market warehouse. 
But on that particular morning, nearly seven years ago, as Malachy and the 
other passengers in the van nodded off, so did the driver. The van tumbled 
off the road, right near the exit to Candlestick Park – ironically, the 
site of previous Full Moon raves. The van rolled into a mudflat and the 
sound equipment tumbled onto Malachy, crushing his spine and neck, leaving 
him paralyzed. "I tried moving my hands, but it was like I was in thick 
oil, or underwater," he recalls. "I couldn't move my arms, but I could in 
my imagination. To this day I still do that – I can feel my toes and feet 
moving but they're actually not."

When the paramedics arrived, they carefully removed Malachy from the van. 
Una dashed out onto the freeway and was instantly hit and killed.

Word of the accident shot through the underground faster than wildfire. "I 
was staying at S.F. General, and the doctors complained that too many 
people were showing up to support me," he smiles. "At the time I didn't 
have enough energy to talk to people, but it helped me through, knowing 
that people were out there dancing for me." Members of the Wicked, 
Gathering, Full Moon, and Come-Unity parties immediately threw a benefit 
for Malachy, who does not have health insurance to this day. "Being the 
New Age hippie that I am, I could really feel the energy during that 
benefit party. They had hooked up an early Internet mechanism that allowed 
me to hear the party, and people came on and gave me messages throughout 
the night. I swear the next day my finger moved a little bit."

Along with his partners, DJ Simon and Kosmic Jason, Malachy helps organize 
the monthly Come-Unity party at Ten 15 Folsom. The monthly club night is 
the longest-running house party in northern California and is Malachy's 
sole source of income. Later this month he and fellow native of Ireland 
Ciaran O'Hara will release a double-CD compilation, Unity, which will 
serve as a benefit for Malachy – who faces eviction in January and needs a 
new electric wheelchair, which can cost up to $20,000. The Unity 
compilation features a host of local and international talent, including 
Orbital (who donated an exclusive Sasha remix of the track "Belfast"), Doc 
Martin and DJ Buck, Dubtribe, Single Cell Orchestra, Garth, Simon, Onionz, 
and Scott Hardkiss, to name a few. The CDs are mixed by DJs Tony and 
Simon, and capture the psychedelic, funkier sides of house, as well as the 
tranced-out, jungled-up sides of just plain buggin' out music.

Malachy's contribution to the birth of the Bay Area's house and rave scene 
began in 1991 and is chronicled in Simon Reynolds's book Generation 
Ecstasy: Into the World of Techno and Rave Culture. A native of Cookstown, 
Northern Ireland, Malachy moved to San Francisco in 1989 from Manchester, 
England, where he was studying computer science. Once in S.F., he soon 
found a job bar backing at Ten 15 Folsom, where he worked with a few other 
future rave progenitors, including Preston (who helped start Toon Town, 
the city's first major mixed-gay-and-straight house club), as well as his 
Come-Unity partners, Simon and Kosmic Jason. Talk about back in the day.

By 1991 the house scene was just starting to kick off, at parties like 
Osmosis at the old DV8, Sundays at Mission Rock, Colossus, Love, Mr. 
Floppy's Flop House, and Do Not Sit on the Furniture. Malachy, who had 
witnessed the beginning of rave culture in England, was ready to take it 
to the next step: outdoors.

"I was working at Ten 15, and one night word got out that we would do a 
party at Baker Beach," he recalls. "There were only 50 or 60 people that 
night. The DJ decks were set on a crate, and Jëno had to kneel down in a 
hole in the sand. It was very renegade."

Soon Malachy joined forces with the Wicked posse (Marky, Garth, and Jëno), 
and Martin O'Brien of the Gathering, and set the Full Moon parties on 
their full-scale, legendary path. That same year, he and Simon also 
launched the Come-Unity parties at Ten 15 Folsom, which Malachy viewed as 
a communal, peaceful platform for his eco-spiritual views on house music 
culture. Still an active environmentalist and unabashed left-wing radical, 
Malachy was the first to articulate the one-love philosophies of the 
underground in San Francisco, which he disseminated through Xeroxed 
leaflets at Come-Unity. One reads, "When used with positive intention, 
Group energy has the potential to restore the plan of Love in Earth. When 
you open your heart and trust the whole group you dance with; when you 
feel love with everyone, and they return it, a higher vibration can be 
reached. This happens when a crowd is deep into the vibe of house."

"I'm still trying to figure out certain obvious things that we learned 
from that early time," says Malachy, who dreams of someday picking coffee 
beans alongside the Sandinistas in Nicaragua. "Those were mind-opening 
times – there was an explosive curiosity that perhaps had a deeper impact 
on society as a whole, such as the confluence of technology and spiritual 
ethics, and a new ethos of self-employment. Hopefully we can direct 
ourselves into helping each other, and not just focus simply on surviving 
alone."

Malachy is hopeful that the new generations will rediscover the early 
rave- and house-culture ideologies. "It's hard to disassociate or give up 
on those ideals," he says. "I want to see it come back again strong. Not 
to be evangelical, but to see the message come through again would be very 
positive. Those feelings that we had at the time seemed pure; we thought 
we could change the world."

Changing the world is something that occupies Malachy's everyday thoughts. 
His room is filled with evidence of political and spiritual enlightenment; 
literature on Greenpeace, Native American histories, Irish resistance, and 
South American, Asian, and African American activism line his bookshelves. 
An Indian tapestry, and an altar with Gaia imagery, decorate the area near 
his computer, which he is able to operate since gaining some control in 
his bicep muscles. He hosts ecology-information video nights in his 
warehouse, collaborates with Food Not Bombs, and plans to establish a 
veggie-burger empire in the near future ("When I get my act together.").

Still, his living situation is shockingly bare bones. He is able to afford 
assistance only Monday through Friday mornings, from his share of the 
funds from the monthly Come-Unity party, but aside from that and the help 
of friends, he's really on his own. He receives medical assistance – since 
every hospital is required by law to treat such cases – but only in times 
of emergency.

So why doesn't he return to his family's home in Northern Ireland, where 
he could receive free medical assistance? After the accident, Malachy did 
return to Cookstown for two years. "The weather is terrible, and Northern 
Ireland is not at all set up for people with disabilities; buses cannot 
accommodate you, so it's impossible to get around on your own. Plus, the 
country is still very confrontational and unsafe." As it is for the 
hundreds of other ex-pat free spirits who have migrated here, San 
Francisco is Malachy's true home.

"Although I know things aren't healthy enough for me right now, I have to 
live dangerously," he says. Bearded, and dressed in a stocking cap, work 
pants, and a flannel shirt, Malachy looks the part of the anti-materialist 
Marxist icon. "Isabel Allende was talking about America, and she said that 
here there is the possibility that you can be and do something new, and 
not face too much criticism. I've been exposed to a lot of that energy 
here. The Bay Area is full of some of the most progressive consciousness 
on the planet. This was the Golden Gate-way to the '60s. Here your mind 
can open up to synchronicity, to new senses, psychedelic ideas. Here you 
can be more sensitive to good vibes and keep things on a positive tip." He 
rolls his eyes and lets out a shy chuckle. "Whoa – I think I just had a 
flashback!"

Malachy's unlimited optimism is profoundly inspiring to others in the 
house community and beyond. "Malachy was one of the very first people of 
my generation that I heard openly and fearlessly talking about gentleness, 
spirituality, and a positive sense of community through these gatherings 
and dance parties," says Sunshine Jones, of the Dubtribe Sound System. "He 
never lost his head, nor did he ever get too big for his boots. No matter 
where you were, or how amazing the party was, you could always speak to 
him, dance with him, and let him know you loved him."

Malachy anticipates the release of the Unity CD, which he hopes will help 
spread the "energy and vibes" of the San Francisco house movement. He is 
also confident that he will walk again. "I won't ever give up the idea 
that I will walk again," he says. "I don't think I could accept that very 
easily. There is so much healing I need to do myself, which might allow 
the power to come through. But I do believe in the power of the mind, and 
the energy that's out there. When I talk to someone I don't know who says, 
'I was at your party!' all that energy comes back to me. I know it's out 
there in the cosmos."

Malachy's fund: Malachy O'Brien, c/o Life 604-A Haight St., S.F., CA 
94117.

. PHOTO: FARIKA

.... "

Source: http://www.sfbg.com/AandE/34/10/lead.html

Happy Full Moon!

<3 Karina

but what was up with the mixing?  not to sound like a DJ snob but i
heard some straight collision wrecks and more than a few sloppy mixes.
 i was surprised.

-b

From: georgeC | origami <newstylesound@yahoo.com>
To: CHUCK G <chuckg_421@yahoo.com>, SFR <sfraves@hyperreal.org>

Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: 808 vs. 909, TR vs. MC

Like some have already said, the 808 and 909 are beautiful machines,
pure fun and function, but as a "basic toolset" piece of gear, all but
unneccesary today.  

Would I want both if my budget and space were infinite?  Absolutely. :)
 Their value as collectable equipment has plataeu'd out at the moment,
for the most part, both hovering around $1k.  

MC-era Roland stuff is *really* unneccesary today.  Artifacts of the
"groove approved" bullshittery Roland was involved in during the first
electronica explosion, they offer much less functionality than even
basic softsynth/sequencer combinations, are clunky to use, and sound
pretty stilted.  

They are hardware devices, and thus *should* be more immediately
grokable than software, but their poor user interfaces doom them to
being all but unusable.  STAY AWAY.

The only "groovebox"-type machine I see as valid today is the Yamaha
RM-1x, an 8-odd-year-old box which is cheap as chips on the used
market, stuffed with innovative (and still not terribly dated) sounds,
and a large amount of fun ways to warp the sound.  It also has a
wonderful sequencer.  Still, not a "first bits" piece of gear by any
means. 

If you want a drum machine for the sake of having a cool little beatbox
to tweak with, find that Yamaha or maybe a Korg Electribe-R.

If you're looking for an analog drum machine to parallel the 808 and
909 sound/feel and want functionality over collectability, look for a
Jomox Xbase09. 

If you aren't precious about having hardware and want what drum
machines were once neccesary for, buy something like Live, Reason, or
the like, and a decent MIDI controller.  They'll take you much farther.


-george C | origami

Subject: [sfraves] nrr: nazca, peru

I think there's not been enough alien-related content on rave lists in
the last five years, so:

Nazca is home to massive petroglyphs drawn on a thousand-foot-plus
scale. They're so large that they can only be seen from the air, but
the culture which created them had neither aircraft nor large
stationary towers from which to view them. They are therefore
extraordinarily puzzling.

They were drawn at least ten thousand years ago and only recently
rediscovered in the twentieth century after the invention and
industrialized mass-production of the airplane. Prior to this,
anthropologists had theorized that the massive carvings were remnants
of ancient, primitive irrigation systems, or just weird accidents of
nature. But what they actually are is drawings of monkeys -- more
properly, the petroglyphs are drawings of various Earthling critters,
i.e., llamas, humans, and, yes, monkeys, specifically very
mischevious-looking monkeys with long spiralling tails. The Swollen
Eyeball Network believes that these drawings, since they can only be
seen from aircraft, are proof of prehistoric UFO visitations. Maybe
yes, maybe no, but they are definitely weird.

Watch the skies.

--
Giles Soundwave =3D Giles Goat Boy
http://www.gilesgoatboy.org/

References: <20051017230230.94870.qmail@web60825.mail.yahoo.com>
	 <20051018003817.13424.qmail@web60316.mail.yahoo.com>
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: 808 vs. 909, TR vs. MC

Yah.

Buying an 808 or a 909 without years of techno-fiddling, and loads of
other machines, is like buying a mint condition 1969 Les Paul without
learning to play the guitar.

808/909 sounds are essential, which makes them easily available for
any and all samplers.

MCx0x devices are mainly just marketing schemes, toys for kids,
although you can do a lot with the later models in the range, to be
fair.

And the "just get some software and make noise with it first" advice
is excellent.

Hospital Records (home of High Contrast and London Elektricity) have
released a number of records done in only Acid or Reason. Fresh from
Dogs On Acid has done the same thing. To be fair, though, getting a
piece of music out of Reason which you can actually master and press
to vinyl can be a fucking nightmare. The most useful technique with
Reason is to listen to your track, then listen to a track you admire,
and then fix all the frequency range differences, i.e., bass too
muddy, treble too scratchy, that sort of shit. Run it in a couple
different sets of speakers, too. Expensive monitors are very nice, but
it's more important to run the track through multiple sets of speakers
than to make any given set of speakers particularly expensive.
Frequency holes are very common in home studios. Also beware of
overdriving the Reason mixer, it sets off some unnecessary and
undocumented compression.

Giles, who knows way too fucking much about Reason


On 10/17/05, georgeC | origami <newstylesound@yahoo.com> wrote:
> Like some have already said, the 808 and 909 are beautiful machines,
> pure fun and function, but as a "basic toolset" piece of gear, all but
> unneccesary today.
>
> Would I want both if my budget and space were infinite?  Absolutely. :)
>  Their value as collectable equipment has plataeu'd out at the moment,
> for the most part, both hovering around $1k.
>
> MC-era Roland stuff is *really* unneccesary today.  Artifacts of the
> "groove approved" bullshittery Roland was involved in during the first
> electronica explosion, they offer much less functionality than even
> basic softsynth/sequencer combinations, are clunky to use, and sound
> pretty stilted.
>
> They are hardware devices, and thus *should* be more immediately
> grokable than software, but their poor user interfaces doom them to
> being all but unusable.  STAY AWAY.
>
> The only "groovebox"-type machine I see as valid today is the Yamaha
> RM-1x, an 8-odd-year-old box which is cheap as chips on the used
> market, stuffed with innovative (and still not terribly dated) sounds,
> and a large amount of fun ways to warp the sound.  It also has a
> wonderful sequencer.  Still, not a "first bits" piece of gear by any
> means.
>
> If you want a drum machine for the sake of having a cool little beatbox
> to tweak with, find that Yamaha or maybe a Korg Electribe-R.
>
> If you're looking for an analog drum machine to parallel the 808 and
> 909 sound/feel and want functionality over collectability, look for a
> Jomox Xbase09.
>
> If you aren't precious about having hardware and want what drum
> machines were once neccesary for, buy something like Live, Reason, or
> the like, and a decent MIDI controller.  They'll take you much farther.
>
>
> -george C | origami
>
>
> --- CHUCK G <chuckg_421@yahoo.com> wrote:
>
> > OK, can't think of a better place to ask. Which of the two above is
> > the best deal for the money?
>

Giles, 
 
Thanks for the info. I'm reasonably familiar with Reason, however I def. haven't achieved "knows way too fucking much." 
 
After checking out the Rebirth Muesum link Steve hooked me up with earlier, I cruised over to its parent site, http://www.propellerheads.se and checked out some of the articles (click articles up top on homepage, cannot link- sorry) they had to see if there was any more info on the comparison of analog vs. digital. 
 
Interestingly enough, there's an interview with Liam Howlett where he says that although he wrote most of the Prodigy's new album (at the time) in Reason, he's still "pure analog" when it comes to bass sounds. This seems to back up the assertion that 'gear might have a little more to offer than blinking lights (yey!). The uc33's lights are just fine. I'm going to research the alternate machines you suggest below this week.
 
Thanks,
 
Chuck

I completely agree Giles.
 If you really want to make a high quality track you need a proper
multitrack midi/audio sequencer (Sonar, Pro Tools, Logic, Cubase, Acid,
Nuendo, ect...). Reason type programs are great as a scratch pad, or as
creating single tracks, but you really need to export them track by track o=
r
"rewire" it to a sequencer to get best quality and also the ability to
properly add effects.
 I usually switch between FL Studio and Reason rewired, do loops in Acid,
and export it all to Sonar. Multitrack it there and use Sonar for midi of m=
y
external hardware.
 Mixdown
 Then
 Master in Sound Forge
 ymmv
 Examples of my tracks can be found here: http://www.tussinsspace.com
 Comments and suggestions always welcome!
 Steve (playing with midi since ~89)

> I think there's not been enough alien-related
> content on rave lists in

> 
> Nazca is home to massive petroglyphs drawn on a
> thousand-foot-plus
> scale. They're so large that they can only be seen
> from the air, but
> the culture which created them had neither aircraft
> nor large
> stationary towers from which to view them. They are
> therefore
> extraordinarily puzzling.
> 
> They were drawn at least ten thousand years ago and
> only recently
> rediscovered in the twentieth century after the
> invention and
> industrialized mass-production of the airplane.
> Prior to this,
> anthropologists had theorized that the massive
> carvings were remnants
> of ancient, primitive irrigation systems, or just
> weird accidents of
> nature. But what they actually are is drawings of
> monkeys -- more
> properly, the petroglyphs are drawings of various
> Earthling critters,
> i.e., llamas, humans, and, yes, monkeys,
> specifically very
> mischevious-looking monkeys with long spiralling
> tails. The Swollen
> Eyeball Network believes that these drawings, since
> they can only be
> seen from aircraft, are proof of prehistoric UFO
> visitations. Maybe
> yes, maybe no, but they are definitely weird.

CHUCK G <chuckg_421@yahoo.com> wrote: Giles, 

Thanks for the info. I'm reasonably familiar with Reason, however I def. haven't achieved "knows way too fucking much." 

After checking out the Rebirth Muesum link Steve hooked me up with earlier, I cruised over to its parent site, http://www.propellerheads.se and checked out some of the articles (click articles up top on homepage, cannot link- sorry) they had to see if there was any more info on the comparison of analog vs. digital. 

Interestingly enough, there's an interview with Liam Howlett where he says that although he wrote most of the Prodigy's new album (at the time) in Reason, he's still "pure analog" when it comes to bass sounds. This seems to back up the assertion that 'gear might have a little more to offer than blinking lights (yey!). The uc33's lights are just fine. I'm going to research the alternate machines you suggest below this week.

Thanks,

Chuck

Giles Soundwave wrote:
Yah.

Buying an 808 or a 909 without years of techno-fiddling, and loads of
other machines, is like buying a mint condition 1969 Les Paul without
learning to play the guitar.

808/909 sounds are essential, which makes them easily available for
any and all samplers.

MCx0x devices are mainly just marketing schemes, toys for kids,
although you can do a lot with the later models in the range, to be
fair.

And the "just get some software and make noise with it first" advice
is excellent.

Hospital Records (home of High Contrast and London Elektricity) have
released a number of records done in only Acid or Reason. Fresh from
Dogs On Acid has done the same thing. To be fair, though, getting a
piece of music out of Reason which you can actually master and press
to vinyl can be a fucking nightmare. The most useful technique with
Reason is to listen to your track, then listen to a track you admire,
and then fix all the frequency range differences, i.e., bass too
muddy, treble too scratchy, that sort of shit. Run it in a couple
different sets of speakers, too. Expensive monitors are very nice, but
it's more important to run the track through multiple sets of speakers
than to make any given set of speakers particularly expensive.
Frequency holes are very common in home studios. Also beware of
overdriving the Reason mixer, it sets off some unnecessary and
undocumented compression.

Giles, who knows way too fucking much about Reason


On 10/17/05, georgeC | origami wrote:
> Like some have already said, the 808 and 909 are beautiful machines,
> pure fun and function, but as a "basic toolset" piece of gear, all but
> unneccesary today.
>
> Would I want both if my budget and space were infinite? Absolutely. :)
> Their value as collectable equipment has plataeu'd out at the moment,
> for the most part, both hovering around $1k.
>
> MC-era Roland stuff is *really* unneccesary today. Artifacts of the
> "groove approved" bullshittery Roland was involved in during the first
> electronica explosion, they offer much less functionality than even
> basic softsynth/sequencer combinations, are clunky to use, and sound
> pretty stilted.
>
> They are hardware devices, and thus *should* be more immediately
> grokable than software, but their poor user interfaces doom them to
> being all but unusable. STAY AWAY.
>
> The only "groovebox"-type machine I see as valid today is the Yamaha
> RM-1x, an 8-odd-year-old box which is cheap as chips on the used
> market, stuffed with innovative (and still not terribly dated) sounds,
> and a large amount of fun ways to warp the sound. It also has a
> wonderful sequencer. Still, not a "first bits" piece of gear by any
> means.
>
> If you want a drum machine for the sake of having a cool little beatbox
> to tweak with, find that Yamaha or maybe a Korg Electribe-R.
>
> If you're looking for an analog drum machine to parallel the 808 and
> 909 sound/feel and want functionality over collectability, look for a
> Jomox Xbase09.
>
> If you aren't precious about having hardware and want what drum
> machines were once neccesary for, buy something like Live, Reason, or
> the like, and a decent MIDI controller. They'll take you much farther.
>
>
> -george C | origami
>
>
> --- CHUCK G wrote:
>
> > OK, can't think of a better place to ask. Which of the two above is
> > the best deal for the money?

>The most useful technique with
Reason is to listen to your track, then listen to a track you admire,
and then fix all the frequency range differences, i.e., bass too
muddy, treble too scratchy, that sort of shit. Run it in a couple

I got some good solid/punchy sound out of routing the digital signal out and
back through an anolog mixer.  Add some subtle compression..mostly for
warmth, and record that back into the audio editor of your choice and throw
a Waves UltraMax on that puppy and yer goood.  Nice, solid, punchy, crisp
and very lovely.  My sound waves are HUGE...which translates into a DAMN
good pressing!

pieces of gear in the right folks hands - and then they become totally 
different tools.

have mad love for the 808 too...

after seeing the Future Retro in action (

tweak knobs on that thing for DAYS....

>From: Giles Soundwave <dj.soundwave@gmail.com>
>To: The Twilight Laser Outpost <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
>Subject: [sfraves] nrr: nazca, peru
>Date: Mon, 17 Oct 2005 19:16:18 -0600
>
>I think there's not been enough alien-related content on rave lists in
>the last five years, so:
>
>Nazca is home to massive petroglyphs drawn on a thousand-foot-plus
>scale. They're so large that they can only be seen from the air, but
>the culture which created them had neither aircraft nor large
>stationary towers from which to view them. They are therefore
>extraordinarily puzzling.
>
>They were drawn at least ten thousand years ago and only recently
>rediscovered in the twentieth century after the invention and
>industrialized mass-production of the airplane. Prior to this,
>anthropologists had theorized that the massive carvings were remnants
>of ancient, primitive irrigation systems, or just weird accidents of
>nature. But what they actually are is drawings of monkeys -- more
>properly, the petroglyphs are drawings of various Earthling critters,
>i.e., llamas, humans, and, yes, monkeys, specifically very
>mischevious-looking monkeys with long spiralling tails. The Swollen
>Eyeball Network believes that these drawings, since they can only be
>seen from aircraft, are proof of prehistoric UFO visitations. Maybe
>yes, maybe no, but they are definitely weird.
>
>Watch the skies.
>
>--
>Giles Soundwave = Giles Goat Boy
>http://www.gilesgoatboy.org/

Van Mundegaarde <electrofunk138@hotmail.com> wrote:
The Nazca drawings plain mystify me. So fucking cool. They are only just now

>From: Giles Soundwave 
>To: The Twilight Laser Outpost 
>Subject: [sfraves] nrr: nazca, peru
>Date: Mon, 17 Oct 2005 19:16:18 -0600
>
>I think there's not been enough alien-related content on rave lists in
>the last five years, so:
>
>Nazca is home to massive petroglyphs drawn on a thousand-foot-plus
>scale. They're so large that they can only be seen from the air, but
>the culture which created them had neither aircraft nor large
>stationary towers from which to view them. They are therefore
>extraordinarily puzzling.
>
>They were drawn at least ten thousand years ago and only recently
>rediscovered in the twentieth century after the invention and
>industrialized mass-production of the airplane. Prior to this,
>anthropologists had theorized that the massive carvings were remnants
>of ancient, primitive irrigation systems, or just weird accidents of
>nature. But what they actually are is drawings of monkeys -- more
>properly, the petroglyphs are drawings of various Earthling critters,
>i.e., llamas, humans, and, yes, monkeys, specifically very
>mischevious-looking monkeys with long spiralling tails. The Swollen
>Eyeball Network believes that these drawings, since they can only be
>seen from aircraft, are proof of prehistoric UFO visitations. Maybe
>yes, maybe no, but they are definitely weird.
>
>Watch the skies.
>
>--
>Giles Soundwave = Giles Goat Boy
>http://www.gilesgoatboy.org/

Subject: [sfraves] nrr: playing a building

--0-1272972653-1129653660=:69730
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit


Playing the Building 
Playing the building is a sound installation in which the infrastructure, the physical plant of the building, is converted into a giant musical instrument. Devices are attached to the building structure — to the metal beams and pillars, the heating pipes, the water pipes — and are used to make these things produce sound. The activations will be of three types: wind, vibration, striking. The devices do not produce sound themselves, but they cause the building elements to vibrate, resonate and oscillate so that the building itself becomes a very large musical instrument.

 
More w. pictures @:
 
http://www.davidbyrne.com/art/art_projects/playing_the_building/index.php

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: 808 vs. 909, TR vs. MC

Maybe I should have said  "in my opinion", because, personally I find
909 sounds to be so overplayed that hearing it in new songs make me
doubt the artist's creativity and sound design ability.

As for the future retro $700 thingy, it sure looks cool, but the QA
engineer in me starts wondering about the form vs. function of it's
UI. Western music theory states that music is bars in time and
mathmatically seperated tones, which is a straight line or a perfect
circle. Which one is more confusing to work with? Imagine a 1 octave
piano keyboard in a circle.

 Also, those knobs look like they are not positioned in an optimum
postion for anyone with hands bigger then a 7 year olds.

Marketing, it's all marketing bullshit. Wanna see some real cool equipment?

Go here: http://www.mysterycircuits.com/

Mr. Osteen

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: 808 vs. 909, TR vs. MC

Well, all I mean is I had a bunch of boxes, sold them all, and sort of
deliberately confined myself to Reason for a while. You learn a lot
that way but some of the things you learn end up just being specific
limitations of Reason. I've actually been picking up little bits of
hardware here and there to balance things out, but it's not been a
priority; I'm more into learning to drum these days, and eventually
picking up a decent set of electronic drums. I don't want to be
overwhelmed with toys, I've done that and it's fun but eventually it's
just wasted time. Discipline -- it's not just for dominatrices any
more.

s that although he wrote most of the Prodigy's new album (at the time) in R=
eason, he's still "pure analog" when it comes to bass sounds. This seems to=
 back up the assertion that 'gear might have a little more to offer than bl=
inking lights (yey!). The uc33's lights are just fine. I'm going to researc=
h the alternate machines you suggest below this week.

> Chuck
>
> Giles Soundwave wrote:
> Yah.
>
> Buying an 808 or a 909 without years of techno-fiddling, and loads of
> other machines, is like buying a mint condition 1969 Les Paul without
> learning to play the guitar.
>
> 808/909 sounds are essential, which makes them easily available for
> any and all samplers.
>
> MCx0x devices are mainly just marketing schemes, toys for kids,
> although you can do a lot with the later models in the range, to be
> fair.
>
> And the "just get some software and make noise with it first" advice
> is excellent.
>
> Hospital Records (home of High Contrast and London Elektricity) have
> released a number of records done in only Acid or Reason. Fresh from
> Dogs On Acid has done the same thing. To be fair, though, getting a
> piece of music out of Reason which you can actually master and press
> to vinyl can be a fucking nightmare. The most useful technique with
> Reason is to listen to your track, then listen to a track you admire,
> and then fix all the frequency range differences, i.e., bass too
> muddy, treble too scratchy, that sort of shit. Run it in a couple
> different sets of speakers, too. Expensive monitors are very nice, but
> it's more important to run the track through multiple sets of speakers
> than to make any given set of speakers particularly expensive.
> Frequency holes are very common in home studios. Also beware of
> overdriving the Reason mixer, it sets off some unnecessary and
> undocumented compression.
>
> Giles, who knows way too fucking much about Reason
>
>
> On 10/17/05, georgeC | origami wrote:
> > Like some have already said, the 808 and 909 are beautiful machines,
> > pure fun and function, but as a "basic toolset" piece of gear, all but
> > unneccesary today.
> >
> > Would I want both if my budget and space were infinite? Absolutely. :)
> > Their value as collectable equipment has plataeu'd out at the moment,
> > for the most part, both hovering around $1k.
> >
> > MC-era Roland stuff is *really* unneccesary today. Artifacts of the
> > "groove approved" bullshittery Roland was involved in during the first
> > electronica explosion, they offer much less functionality than even
> > basic softsynth/sequencer combinations, are clunky to use, and sound
> > pretty stilted.
> >
> > They are hardware devices, and thus *should* be more immediately
> > grokable than software, but their poor user interfaces doom them to
> > being all but unusable. STAY AWAY.
> >
> > The only "groovebox"-type machine I see as valid today is the Yamaha
> > RM-1x, an 8-odd-year-old box which is cheap as chips on the used
> > market, stuffed with innovative (and still not terribly dated) sounds,
> > and a large amount of fun ways to warp the sound. It also has a
> > wonderful sequencer. Still, not a "first bits" piece of gear by any
> > means.
> >
> > If you want a drum machine for the sake of having a cool little beatbox
> > to tweak with, find that Yamaha or maybe a Korg Electribe-R.
> >
> > If you're looking for an analog drum machine to parallel the 808 and
> > 909 sound/feel and want functionality over collectability, look for a
> > Jomox Xbase09.
> >
> > If you aren't precious about having hardware and want what drum
> > machines were once neccesary for, buy something like Live, Reason, or
> > the like, and a decent MIDI controller. They'll take you much farther.
> >
> >
> > -george C | origami
> >
> >
> > --- CHUCK G wrote:

> > > the best deal for the money?

>
> >From: Giles Soundwave <dj.soundwave@gmail.com>
> >To: The Twilight Laser Outpost <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
> >Subject: [sfraves] nrr: nazca, peru
> >Date: Mon, 17 Oct 2005 19:16:18 -0600
> >
> >I think there's not been enough alien-related content on rave lists in
> >the last five years, so:
> >
> >Nazca is home to massive petroglyphs drawn on a thousand-foot-plus
> >scale. They're so large that they can only be seen from the air, but
> >the culture which created them had neither aircraft nor large
> >stationary towers from which to view them. They are therefore
> >extraordinarily puzzling.
> >
> >They were drawn at least ten thousand years ago and only recently
> >rediscovered in the twentieth century after the invention and
> >industrialized mass-production of the airplane. Prior to this,
> >anthropologists had theorized that the massive carvings were remnants
> >of ancient, primitive irrigation systems, or just weird accidents of
> >nature. But what they actually are is drawings of monkeys -- more
> >properly, the petroglyphs are drawings of various Earthling critters,
> >i.e., llamas, humans, and, yes, monkeys, specifically very
> >mischevious-looking monkeys with long spiralling tails. The Swollen
> >Eyeball Network believes that these drawings, since they can only be
> >seen from aircraft, are proof of prehistoric UFO visitations. Maybe
> >yes, maybe no, but they are definitely weird.
> >
> >Watch the skies.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr: nazca, peru

To keep the alien and ancient cultures kick going I've been studying a
cross relationship between the Dogon tribe of Africa that predicted Sirius
had a smaller, darker companion which was very heavy which wasn't prooved
to the 1930's when it was found out that Sirius is a binary star and has a
white dwarf which is the smallest possible and heaviest star without
collapsing on itself.  They also have a 4 calendar system which doesn't
seem based off any normal calendar system and are based off the (very DNA
looking) flight path and 49 - 50 year cycle of Sirius A and B. They also
predicted a 3rd star in the system which hasn't been found but who knows,
there might be or at least might've been.  They're legend says that
visitors gave them the calendars and that they were from these stars. 
Here's a link to some of their mythos
http://www.crystalinks.com/dogon.html. This website has a lot of ancient
cultures cross connected as well and it is definitely an interesting
website to start in studying ancient cultures, their prophecies and how
they're related to each other.  Of course it doesn't have everything but
thats up to you to keep googling out the things you read about.

Other interesting topics to cross reference regarding aliens and ancient
cultures is of course the Mayan and Tibetan calendars, the pyramids in
China including the mysterious white pyramid, another pyramid that sits on
a salt lake in the middle of nowhere and has pipes running underground and
into the lake that the locals believe was used as an alien launch pad. 
Some of the materials at the lake, like components in the pipes have not
quite been identified either.  Unfortunately, scientists have always had
hard time studying these relics due to communism in China as well as they
don't want the tombs of their ancestors investigated.  Another myth for an
area in souther China near the border with india is of a tribe of 'very
ugly people' who once inhabited the area who were very small, and their
legend consists of an alien spaceship crash.  These humanoids are
described as neither looking asian nor indian and are still a mystery. 
They've also found strange disks in caves that were supposedly brought
with them as well (these artifacts are listed at somewhere around 12k
years old as are some of the remains they've found.  Just recently,
remains matching the ugly people have been found in the phillipenes or
indonesia and have also been dated about 12k years old.

So much info out there... no wonder I'm an insomniac.

-Rayn

>> >Nazca is home to massive petroglyphs drawn on a thousand-foot-plus
>> >scale. They're so large that they can only be seen from the air, but
>> >the culture which created them had neither aircraft nor large
>> >stationary towers from which to view them. They are therefore
>> >extraordinarily puzzling.
>> >
>> >They were drawn at least ten thousand years ago and only recently
>> >rediscovered in the twentieth century after the invention and
>> >industrialized mass-production of the airplane. Prior to this,
>> >anthropologists had theorized that the massive carvings were remnants
>> >of ancient, primitive irrigation systems, or just weird accidents of
>> >nature. But what they actually are is drawings of monkeys -- more
>> >properly, the petroglyphs are drawings of various Earthling critters,
>> >i.e., llamas, humans, and, yes, monkeys, specifically very
>> >mischevious-looking monkeys with long spiralling tails. The Swollen
>> >Eyeball Network believes that these drawings, since they can only be
>> >seen from aircraft, are proof of prehistoric UFO visitations. Maybe
>> >yes, maybe no, but they are definitely weird.

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Is Sex Necessary? (You might want to read NOT at work)

  Your Health
Is Sex Necessary?
Alan Farnham



Fans of abstinence had better be sitting down. "Saving yourself" before 
the big game, the big business deal, the big hoedown or the big bakeoff 
may indeed confer some moral benefit. But corporeally it does absolutely 
zip. There's no evidence it sharpens your competitive edge. The best that 
modern science can say for sexual abstinence is that it's harmless when 
practiced in moderation. Having regular and enthusiastic sex, by contrast, 
confers a host of measurable physiological advantages, be you male or 
female. (This assumes that you are engaging in sex without contracting a 
sexually transmitted disease.)

In one of the most credible studies correlating overall health with sexual 
frequency, Queens University in Belfast tracked the mortality of about 
1,000 middle-aged men over the course of a decade. The study was designed 
to compare persons of comparable circumstances, age and health. Its 
findings, published in 1997 in the British Medical Journal, were that men 
who reported the highest frequency of orgasm enjoyed a death rate half 
that of the laggards. Other studies (some rigorous, some less so) purport 
to show that having sex even a few times a week has an associative or 
causal relationship with the following:

- Improved sense of smell: After sex, production of the hormone prolactin 
surges. This in turn causes stem cells in the brain to develop new neurons 
in the brain's olfactory bulb, its smell center.

- Reduced risk of heart disease: In a 2001 follow-on to the Queens 
University study mentioned above, researchers focused on cardiovascular 
health. Their finding? That by having sex three or more times a week, men 
reduced their risk of heart attack or stroke by half. In reporting these 
results, the co-author of the study, Shah Ebrahim, Ph.D., displayed the 
well-loved British gift for understatement: "The relationship found 
between frequency of sexual intercourse and mortality is of considerable 
public interest."

- Weight loss, overall fitness: Sex, if nothing else, is exercise. A 
vigorous bout burns some 200 calories--about the same as running 15 
minutes on a treadmill or playing a spirited game of squash. The pulse 
rate, in a person aroused, rises from about 70 beats per minute to 150, 
the same as that of an athlete putting forth maximum effort. British 
researchers have determined that the equivalent of six Big Macs can be 
worked off by having sex three times a week for a year. Muscular 
contractions during intercourse work the pelvis, thighs, buttocks, arms, 
neck and thorax. Sex also boosts production of testosterone, which leads 
to stronger bones and muscles. Men's Health magazine has gone so far as to 
call the bed the single greatest piece of exercise equipment ever 
invented.

- Reduced depression: Such was the implication of a 2002 study of 293 
women. American psychologist Gordon Gallup reported that sexually active 
participants whose male partners did not use condoms were less subject to 
depression than those whose partners did. One theory of causality: 
Prostoglandin, a hormone found only in semen, may be absorbed in the 
female genital tract, thus modulating female hormones.

- Pain-relief: Immediately before orgasm, levels of the hormone oxytocin 
surge to five times their normal level. This in turn releases endorphins, 
which alleviate the pain of everything from headache to arthritis to even 
migraine. In women, sex also prompts production of estrogen, which can 
reduce the pain of PMS.

- Less-frequent colds and flu: Wilkes University in Pennsylvania says 
individuals who have sex once or twice a week show 30% higher levels of an 
antibody called immunoglobulin A, which is known to boost the immune 
system.

- Better bladder control: Heard of Kegel exercises? You do them, whether 
you know it or not, every time you stem your flow of urine. The same set 
of muscles is worked during sex.

- Better teeth: Seminal plasma contains zinc, calcium and other minerals 
shown to retard tooth decay. Since this is a family Web site, we will omit 
discussion of the mineral delivery system. Suffice it to say that it could 
be a far richer, more complex and more satisfying experience than 
squeezing a tube of Crest--even Tartar Control Crest. Researchers have 
noted, parenthetically, that sexual etiquette usually demands the brushing 
of one's teeth before and/or after intimacy, which, by itself, would help 
promote better oral hygiene.

- A happier prostate? Some urologists believe they see a relationship 
between infrequency of ejaculation and cancer of the prostate. The causal 
argument goes like this: To produce seminal fluid, the prostate and the 
seminal vesicles take such substances from the blood as zinc, citric acid 
and potassium, then concentrate them up to 600 times. Any carcinogens 
present in the blood likewise would be concentrated. Rather than have 
concentrated carcinogens hanging around causing trouble, it's better to 
evict them. Regular old sex could do the job. But if the flushing of the 
prostate were your only objective, masturbation might be a better way to 
go, especially for the non-monogamous male. Having sex with multiple 
partners can, all by itself, raise a man's risk of cancer by up to 40%. 
That's because he runs an increased risk of contracting sexual infections. 
So, if you want the all the purported benefits of flushing with none of 
the attendant risk, go digital. A study recently published by the British 
Journal of Urology International asserts that men in their 20s can reduce 
by a third their chance of getting prostate cancer by ejaculating more 
than five times a week.

While possession of a robust appetite for sex--and the physical ability to 
gratify it--may not always be the cynosure of perfect health, a reluctance 
to engage can be a sign that something is seriously on the fritz, 
especially where the culprit is an infirm erection.

Dr. J. Francois Eid, a urologist with Weill Medical College of Cornell 
University and New York Presbyterian Hospital, observes that erectile 
dysfunction is extension of vascular system. A lethargic member may be 
telling you that you have diseased blood vessels elsewhere in your body. 
"It could be a first sign of hypertension or diabetes or increased 
cholesterol levels. It's a red flag that you should see your doctor." 
Treatment and exercise, says Dr. Eid, can have things looking up again: 
"Men who exercise and have a good heart and low heart rate, and who are 
cardio-fit, have firmer erections. There very definitely is a 
relationship."

But is there such a thing as too much sex?

The answer, in purely physiological terms, is this: If you're female, 
probably not. If you're male? You betcha.

Dr. Claire Bailey of the University of Bristol says there is little or no 
risk of a woman's overdosing on sex. In fact, she says, regular sessions 
can not only firm a woman's tummy and buttocks but also improve her 
posture.

Dr. George Winch Jr., an obstetrician/gynecologist in Elko, Nev., concurs. 
If a woman is pre-menopausal and otherwise healthy, says Dr. Winch, her 
having an extraordinary amount of intercourse ought not to pose a problem. 
"I don't think women can have too much intercourse," he says, "so long as 
no sexually transmitted disease is introduced and there's not an 
inadvertent pregnancy. Sometimes you can have a lubrication problem. If 
you have that, there can be vaginal excoriation--vaginal scrape."

Women who abstain from sex run some risks. In postmenopausal women, these 
include vaginal atrophy. Dr. Winch has a middle-aged patient of whom he 
says: "She hasn't had intercourse in three years. Just isn't interested. 
The opening of her vagina is narrowing from disuse. It's a condition that 
can lead to dysparenia, or pain associated with intercourse. I told her, 
'Look, you'd better buy a vibrator or you're going to lose function 
there.'"

As for men, urologist Eid says it's definitely possible to get too much of 
a good thing, now that drugs such as Viagra and Levitra have given men far 
more staying power than may actually be good for them.

The penis, says Eid, is wonderfully resilient. But everything has its 
limits. Penile tissues, if given too roistering or prolonged a pummeling, 
can sustain damage. In cases you'd just as soon not hear about, permanent 
damage.

"Yes," says Dr. Eid, "It is possible for a young man who is very forceful 
and who likes rough sex, to damage his erectile tissue." The drugs 
increase rigidity; moreover, they make it possible for a man to have 
second and third orgasms without having to wait out intermission.

"I see it in pro football players," says Eid. "They use Viagra because 
they're so sexually active. What they demand of their body is 
unreasonable. It's part of playing football: you play through the pain." 
This type of guy doesn't listen to his body. He takes a shot of cortisone, 
and keeps on going. And they have sex in similar fashion."

There's a reason the penis, in its natural state, undergoes a period of 
flaccidity: That's when it takes a breather. The blood within it is 
replenished with oxygen. "During an erection," explains Eid, "very little 
blood flows to the penis. During thrusting, pressure can go as high as 200 
mil of water. Zero blood flows into penis at that time." To absorb oxygen, 
the tissue must become relaxed. "If you do not allow the penis to rest, 
then the muscle tissue does not get enough oxygen. The individual gets 
prolonged erections, gets decreased oxygen to tissue, and could 
potentially suffer priapism." (We recommend you get a medical encyclopedia 
and look it up.) "The muscle becomes so engorged, it's painful. Pressure 
inside starts to increase. Cells start dying. More pressure and less blood 
flow. Eventually the muscle dies. Then there's scarring. That's why it's 
considered an emergency."

Content-transfer-encoding: 7bit

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: 808 vs. 909, TR vs. MC

While you're at it- check out the XL7/MP7 boxes by Emu.

(I've owned both, as well as many other HW sequencers)
My main problem with the RM1x was the buttons-
(secondarily, the non-standard and unresponsive interface)
Non-velocity sensitive and they tend to just stop working quickly...
The XL7 is the hardware sequencer I've stuck with- the synthesis section is
a ROMpler but nobody does those better than Emu...

For uber-cheap the mentioned electribes are endless fun (if very limited in
the A and R versions)- and also check out the AN/DX200 boxes by yamaha-
Serious synthesis capabilies combined with ROMpler drums, proper modulation,
and a decent FX section with an onboard sequencer- lots of fun and
capability for the $129 or so...

-SS

On 10/17/05 9:55 PM, "CHUCK G" <chuckg_421@yahoo.com> wrote:

> Correction: Going to try alternate machine that georgeC had suggested.* Sorry
> for any misimplication.
> 
> CHUCK G <chuckg_421@yahoo.com> wrote: Giles,
> 
> Thanks for the info. I'm reasonably familiar with Reason, however I def.
> haven't achieved "knows way too fucking much."
> 
> After checking out the Rebirth Muesum link Steve hooked me up with earlier, I
> cruised over to its parent site, http://www.propellerheads.se and checked out
> some of the articles (click articles up top on homepage, cannot link- sorry)
> they had to see if there was any more info on the comparison of analog vs.
> digital. 
> 
> Interestingly enough, there's an interview with Liam Howlett where he says
> that although he wrote most of the Prodigy's new album (at the time) in
> Reason, he's still "pure analog" when it comes to bass sounds. This seems to
> back up the assertion that 'gear might have a little more to offer than
> blinking lights (yey!). The uc33's lights are just fine. I'm going to research
> the alternate machines you suggest below this week.
> 
> Thanks,
> 
> Chuck
> 
> Giles Soundwave wrote:
> Yah.
> 
> Buying an 808 or a 909 without years of techno-fiddling, and loads of
> other machines, is like buying a mint condition 1969 Les Paul without
> learning to play the guitar.
> 
> 808/909 sounds are essential, which makes them easily available for
> any and all samplers.
> 
> MCx0x devices are mainly just marketing schemes, toys for kids,
> although you can do a lot with the later models in the range, to be
> fair.
> 
> And the "just get some software and make noise with it first" advice
> is excellent.
> 
> Hospital Records (home of High Contrast and London Elektricity) have
> released a number of records done in only Acid or Reason. Fresh from
> Dogs On Acid has done the same thing. To be fair, though, getting a
> piece of music out of Reason which you can actually master and press
> to vinyl can be a fucking nightmare. The most useful technique with
> Reason is to listen to your track, then listen to a track you admire,
> and then fix all the frequency range differences, i.e., bass too
> muddy, treble too scratchy, that sort of shit. Run it in a couple
> different sets of speakers, too. Expensive monitors are very nice, but
> it's more important to run the track through multiple sets of speakers
> than to make any given set of speakers particularly expensive.
> Frequency holes are very common in home studios. Also beware of
> overdriving the Reason mixer, it sets off some unnecessary and
> undocumented compression.
> 
> Giles, who knows way too fucking much about Reason
> 
> 
> On 10/17/05, georgeC | origami wrote:
>> Like some have already said, the 808 and 909 are beautiful machines,
>> pure fun and function, but as a "basic toolset" piece of gear, all but
>> unneccesary today.
>> 
>> Would I want both if my budget and space were infinite? Absolutely. :)
>> Their value as collectable equipment has plataeu'd out at the moment,
>> for the most part, both hovering around $1k.
>> 
>> MC-era Roland stuff is *really* unneccesary today. Artifacts of the
>> "groove approved" bullshittery Roland was involved in during the first
>> electronica explosion, they offer much less functionality than even
>> basic softsynth/sequencer combinations, are clunky to use, and sound
>> pretty stilted.
>> 
>> They are hardware devices, and thus *should* be more immediately
>> grokable than software, but their poor user interfaces doom them to
>> being all but unusable. STAY AWAY.
>> 
>> The only "groovebox"-type machine I see as valid today is the Yamaha
>> RM-1x, an 8-odd-year-old box which is cheap as chips on the used
>> market, stuffed with innovative (and still not terribly dated) sounds,
>> and a large amount of fun ways to warp the sound. It also has a
>> wonderful sequencer. Still, not a "first bits" piece of gear by any
>> means.
>> 
>> If you want a drum machine for the sake of having a cool little beatbox
>> to tweak with, find that Yamaha or maybe a Korg Electribe-R.
>> 
>> If you're looking for an analog drum machine to parallel the 808 and
>> 909 sound/feel and want functionality over collectability, look for a
>> Jomox Xbase09.
>> 
>> If you aren't precious about having hardware and want what drum
>> machines were once neccesary for, buy something like Live, Reason, or
>> the like, and a decent MIDI controller. They'll take you much farther.
>> 
>> 
>> -george C | origami
>> 
>> 
>> --- CHUCK G wrote:
>> 
>>> OK, can't think of a better place to ask. Which of the two above is
>>> the best deal for the money?

Or, Ranger, this lovely party is right in your back yard:

OK folks the time of all Hallows eve fast approaches the pumpkins
are everywhere you look, kids are dusting off their favorite candy receptacle
And we are working night and day to make this years Freaker's Ball the
an over the top dance till you sing good to the last freakin drop experience

Tickets are on sale with no service charge @ the following locations
they are starting to go fast
please get on it if you have not already

Street Light Records in Santa Cruz 939 Pacific Ave.
BPM Hayes and Filmore in San Francisco

or for the convienence of online 
http://www.inticketing.com/evinfo.php?eventid=9464

We are very proud to announce the
Eleventh Annual Freaker's Ball
Halloween costume party
Sat October 29th 2005 doors open at 8pm
we will be taking over all three floors and the outside of
Veterans Memorial building 846 Front St Santa Cruz
costume required for entrance

And now the finest line-up ever created covering a wide variety of music

  DJ and live electronic music from Line up includes
Tipper (Tippermusic, http://www.tipper.cc/ )
Lorin (Bassnectar, http://www.bassnectar.net/ )
  Jeno (Wicked ,http://djjeno.com/ ) Lil John (Raindance,13 Moon tribe)
Random Rab (El Circo ), An-ten-nea (Live, Get Freaky),Brother (13 
Moon Tribe, Raindance)
Kraddy (Muti music), Mozaic (13 Moon Tribe, Raindance), Rodman
Boreta (Meta, Raindance), Strydah (13 Moon Tribe), Olivia (Santa 
Cruz), N-Man (colors/Flow)
Alia (13 Moon Tribe, Raindance), Rob Monroy (Raindance)
Cool Hand Luke , Taina, Jason Kristos (Full Circle)


Organic Live music from
Temple of Funk ( Santa Cruz funk monsters )
Goddess of Funk and friends (Female Brazilian drumming ensemble) 
http://www.goddessfunk.com/
And the Freaker's all star band

Visuals by Dax, Satsi and friends

vaudevillian undulations by Hipnautica
Areal Dance and Circus performers performances,
informal costume contest
Special top secret Halloween performance !!! not to be missed
+ many surprises

organic tricks and treats by convergence

Presale is recommended this event always sells out
Available online NOW @ inticketing.com
click > http://www.inticketing.com/evinfo.php?eventid=9464
Presale Tickets are $20 @ the following locations available on Wed Oct 12th
Street Light Records in Santa Cruz 939 Pacific Ave.
BPM Hayes and Filmore in San Francisco

party location
Veterans Memorial building
846 Front St Santa Cruz (next to the post office)

See you at the Ball

"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

I have to definitely agree with Van on this one. MBM is just flat out
amazing. Especially if you've never seen them before, do yourself a favor
and check them out. Their music has kind of a heavy, spooky edge to it that
will go great with the Haloween thing too. In fact, Tino Corp. (another
Dangers / Stokes project) even did a "Halloween Dub" album!
 And while I'm on the topic, I was recently lucky enough to catch an AMAZIN=
G
audio/visual performance by Tino Corp. at the Elbo Room. I took some friend=
s
along who had never heard of them and everyone was blown away! Check the
Tino Corp. website now and again, they occasionally do shows like this at
small venues with very little advertising. Four guys, synched audio/video
scratching, absolutely dope combo of breaks/dub/electro/techno. unbelievabl=
y
GRATE!
 ------> Greg
 btw Adriana, I'll FOR SURE be at the boat party, but the costume (as
always) is top secret! (last year I was DuctTape Man, and the year before
that, The Hamburglar!)

Subject: [sfraves] http://www.ferrapsylix.com     

Man - I noticed that your sig said "sub atomic breakbeat", and you just KNOW 
that I had to peep the style.

I must say - I am VERY impressed! The uptempo breaks have a very psy-breaks 
feel to them, which I have a soft spot for (acciiiiiiied!!), and the 
downtempo breaks are like a hybrid between nuskool breaks & hip-hop. 
Something I've been interested in spinning, but can rarely find any 
material. I know guys like Tipper, T-Power and some locals produce it, but 
it's hard to track down, and rare that I really dig the style. My hat's 
off!!! Everything I checked out was reallllly cool!!!

Go to the site and check out Troys stuff y'all!!!! Two big thumbs up!!!

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Wassup for Holloween PeoplZ ??

MBM is just so critical to the electronic music scene, it's not only going 
to be a dope show, but it'll be like taking electronica 101. They really 
pushed electro, techno, techno-dub, IDM and even jungle to some extent 
before half those genres really existed. Jack Dangers is pretty much on par 
with someone like Danny Elfman....pushing the envelope, his hands in 
everything - a true innovator.

Adding to that, I have some industrial music video comps from back in 
the day (when they were on VHS) that have meat beat videos on them. Old 
school and classic. MBM introduced me into a whole new level of 
electronic music that i was never exposed to as an industrial nut for so 
long. I bought one of their early albums on a whim after seeing a video 
because it mixed so well between psychic tv, kmfdm, laibach and front 
242 but still maintained this weird edge of surreal degenerate 
fuckedupedness.

That said, no way will I miss Halloween. I'll be chaplin.

-a_tim

Subject: [sfraves] <<NOW-LOWEEN>> Saturday, October 29th, 2005

The time is NOW!


What: NOW-LOWEEN
When: Saturday, Oct. 29th, 2005
Where: A secret Gold Rush town
Info: 775.321.9887

WWW.MOVEMENTNOW.COM

* A celebration of life and enjoyment of the moment as well as one of our
favorite holiday's.

DJ's:

Dj Brian - Los Angeles - (moontribe, Ritual Sounds)

  In 1995, Brian became the first DJ in 2 years to join Daniel and John
Kelly as resident djs for Moontribe's Full moon gatherings.
  Since then Brian has released 4 mixed CD's with the L.A. label Moonshine
Music, "Hard Desert Trance 1, 2 & 3" and most recently "Psychotrance 2002".
Brian's ears, eyes, and mind are always open. His musical diversity and
willingness to experiment elevates his listeners to new heights, changing
the way we listen and dance.

Serch - Chicago, Illinois - (theserch, Fresh Out, M13 Graphics)

G.A.M.M.A. - (stilldream, techno truth)
Phokus - (korpus kallosum, phokus music
David Aaron - (stilldream, mixlife)

Wavelength - (oneiromancey)
Mr. Rogers - (the doramey fossilotti, ooze system)
Officer Bunch - (saturated mind, ooze system)

Bird - (BAMF)
Dj Chipy - ( 530 techno, Classic Grooves)
XiM - ( 530 techno, Classic Grooves)
Covert (Transcend)
Sundance (Transcend)
Dj Rizin (Midtown Mayhem)

More Info:
- This is a Costume party so come dressed up and ready to dance we are going
all night and until the sun pushes us back into our coffins!
- Music: Breaks, Techno, Trance, House, Downtempo
- This show will be limited to 150 people and WILL sell out.
- Location to be announced, but trust me its going to be an amazing, virgin
venue, fitting to the theme.
- Tickets will be sold through family and djs that are playing. So if you
want to go let one of us know, or there will be a small amount of tickets on
sale at Channelz 916 in Sacramento.
- A portion of the proceeds will be donated to help thoose in need with the
Huricane Katrina Disaster Relief Fund.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr: nazca, peru

on the 12,000 years old thing, there's an ecologist who says he can
prove that the Sphinx is at least 12,000 years old, because it has a
lot more rainforest erosion on it than desert erosion. (ie much more
gentle sloping downwards erosion, as in water flowing down, than harsh
abrasive sideways erosion, as in sand scraping as it's blown by wind.)

Aleister Crowley believed that the Greeks knew about Sirius also,
although how they were supposed to have gotten the information from
the Dogons is a bit of a puzzle.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr: nazca, peru

Yea - that theory has been disproven a bunch of times tho. That particular 
type of stone that the Sphinx is made up of has changing layers, and often 
times some layers soften and crumble well before the others, leaving a 
similar effect as water erosion.

Hey everyone the time is almost upon us. We have assembles 7 of the most
beloved crews in the bay for one special event. We have worked very hard to
make this the best event of the year. Please join us as we go mad!!!*
||||Mad Hatters Halloween Tea Party|||| *
*Room 1 (hosted by HCFTP, Nu Vision, DTS and Nocturnalisim)*
*GRIDLOK* (Project51/Violence Recordings-SF) As one of America's hardest
working producers and DJs, Gridlok has charted a steady, methodical path
into the vanguard of drum and bass. His tracks enjoy the support of drum an=
d
bass' finest, from Andy C to Bailey. His work ethic and tireless efforts to
advance the sonic breadth of the music have yielded tremendous dividends fo=
r
drum and bass fans worldwide. Recent releases on Project 51 and Violence
have become staples of countless major league DJs worldwide, and are huge
crowd favorites

*SUNRIZE* (Pitched Up Recordings/HCFTP/Blatant Beats UK-MA) - *Final Happy
Hardcore Performance* Since his first hardcore release in the spring of
2002, he has released on a handful of labels, some including Pitched Up
Recordings, Blatant Beats, Destructive Force, Rave N Beats, and Madness &
Mayhem. This DJ's name has become unanimous with American Hardcore and has
played all across the country at events with artists like Scott Brown, DJ
SY, UFO, Brisk, and others. This will be his final performance as dj
sunrize. Don't miss the last chance to see him play happy hardcore.

*MAYHEM* (AZ Hardcore
Junkies.com/CompleteDJ.com<http://Junkies.com/CompleteDJ.com>)
vs. *vs. Second Base*In 2001, Steve Van Holton, better known to West Coast
hardcore fans as Mayhem, began playing records. His motivation? Simply to
listen to the music he loved by artists such as Digital Boy, Anger Fist,
Noize Supressor, Sonik, The Wish Master, Armageddon Project and The
Headbanger. Mayhem joined the Arizona Hardcore Junkies in 2003 only a shot
time after he began playing and in 2004 was asked to play Nocturnal
Wonderland in Los Angles. Playing parties with the likes of Scott Brown,
Neophyte, Panic, Ophidian, Delta 9, D-passion and Dj delirium. The AZ
Hardcore Junkies expect big things to come from Mayhem in the near future.

the AXIS (The Doc & Arize)
Sideshow & Go-Zania & Leon Cook
Yagi & Reclipse
Happy Freaks (Hi-C, Kid Orange, & Cracker Jack)
2qt & Rye Bread

*Room 2 (Hosted by Zapatistas and Andy P)*

*DIG-DUG* (USC Events-WA) Known for his incredible track selection and
polished technical skills, DJ Dig-Dug has managed to develop an undeniably
unique style. While his sets often travel through several different types o=
f
breaks (Funky, Progressive, Dark), his underlying theme of warped bass line=
s
and intelligent drum loops brings a sense of unity to his signature sound.
With his impressive beat juggling, cross-fader cutting, and creative but
tasteful use of the Pioneer DJM-600's onboard effects, DJ Dig-Dug has
developed a following based on skills, not hype.

*FilterGrinder* (Kontrast/Phat & Phunkie-TX) Doug Siebenthal, a.k.a.
Filtergrinder, has been djing for the last seven years. Filtergrinder
started producing techno when he met Bryan Cox in 2001. BC and Filtergrinde=
r
went on to produce the hit record "Alpine". Alpine (BC remix) got quick
recognition by DJ Dan and was featured on his Mixed Live DJ Dan, Ruby Skye
(Moonshine) CD. Both the original and the remix went on to have great
notoriety on BBC Radio One, and top rotation of such djs as Carl Cox,
Fergie, Joey Beltram, and Mauro Picotto. Filtergrinder currently resides in
the L.A. area as he continues to dj on a monthly basis and for the year of
2005, he is also launching Whiplash Records; the first release, "Rockin the
Disco", is coming out in March with the remix being done by Bryan Cox. You
can also expect other records from Filtergrinder in 2005 including
"Repeater" on the Afficinado label, with remixes from Granite & Phunk and
Carbon Community.

Filter Freq 2x4 Dj Doza
Ron Reeser 2x4 Felipe Avelar
Aaron Jae 2x4 M.O.D.
Andy P 2x4 Vinyl Junkies - Special 1hr 30min set.
Soul 1 2x4 Rob Base
Hard Stompers aka Riff Raff 2x4 Spell
ill-D the DJ 2x4 Hyjinx

*Room 3 (Hosted By SSP and Illumination Records)*
*DUTCH* (Thump Radio-SF) A 12 yr veteran of the SF scene, Dutch made his
name early in the rave scene. Beginning with a party known as A Rave called
Sharon, Dutch's name spread quickly throughout SF. Known for seamless
mixing, and remarkable sets, Dutch has made a huge impact at the SF Thump
parties as resident DJ. Keep your eyes on this kid and check him out if he
comes to your city! nuff said

Officer Bunch (Ooze System / Saturated Mind)
Michael Liu
Majere
Epsilon
Durty & Viticus
Precision
Tim Stephanic

*Details:*
1000 Person Capacity
Safe and Secure Venue
East Bay Location
Friendly Security
Amazing Wall of Sound provided by HardScience Sound.

Lasers, Lights, and Props

For this Tantra Halloween, we're going with two rooms of trance to  
keep the groove and psychedelic sounds going all night long.  Also a  
nicely appointed outdoor chill tent, original psychedelic paintings  
by Indonesian artist Daya Cayung and the always fabulous Day of the  
Dead art maze by SomArts.

TANTRA HALLOWEEN

Saturday, October 29th, 10pm-8am, 18+
The SomArts Gallery, 934 Brannan St. SF

IN THE PSYCHEDELIC ROOM

HIGHKO  (Noise Poison Records/Berlin, Germany)  Highko took the  
trance world by storm this past year with his own powerful tracks and  
co-productions with Cosmo, aka High Cosmos.  We're thrilled to  
present his first US performance.

Ocelot - Dropout Productions
Liam Shy - Tantra
Parus - Auraquake Records
Wichdokta - Full Circle Productions

IN THE GROOVY ROOM

MEKKANIKKA (Spirit Zone Records/Barcelona, Spain) Nikka developed his  
trance style in SF with Biodegradable, then went international with  
his Mekkanikka release on Spirit Zone.  He's greatly looking forward  
to playing in his favorite town on halloween and seeing old friends.

Chromatone - Vaporvent and Timecode Records
KJ - Tantra
Kode IV - Ceiba Records
Helios - Bioharmonics

IN THE CHILL TENT

RENA JONES (Native States Records)  - "Ethno, IDM, Breakbeat, down- 
tempo...all set to live cello and violin. Emotional, beautiful and  
deep".  Accompanied by Scott Sterling on percussion

Cyril - Waterjuice/Vaporvent Records
Maer - OEM radio
Afut - FutureOctave.com, Psybooty
Dr. Spook - Geomagnetic.tv
Sina - back from school and ready to party!

ART

Original Psychedelic paintings by Daya Cayung (Indonesia) http:// 
www.dayavision.50megs.com/
Day of the Dead art exhibit by Somarts www.somarts.org
Visuals by Dr. Spook www.geomagnetic.tv

Sound by Tantra and Full Circle Productions

$25 presale, $30 at the door
Tickets available online at www.tantrasf.com or at
Distractions 1552 Haight St., SF
Ceiba - 1364 haight St., SF
Skills - 2566A Telegraph Ave. Berkeley

415-820-3201
www.tantrasf.com


--Apple-Mail-1--944926786--

Subject: [sfraves] Technology: spinning a virtual platter from CD tracks

Content-Type: text/plain
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Hello everyone,
Please forgive my ignorance on this topic but I have a goal with some personal urgency. My birthday is Friday and all I want is a DJ mix from my CD collection.
 
Sometimes we buy CDs just because they have a good dance song that we can’t find anywhere else. Often your favorite song is mixed in a continuous pattern per the DJ’s intention.
 
What if you want to take your favorite songs and put them together? You have to eliminate or change the transition to the next track and perform beat matching. 
 
You can’t just “rip” and burn the song, it doesn’t sound right because it cuts off abruptly.
 
You need a DJ!
 
So I called my friend Ben, a young lifeguard who is an aspiring bedroom DJ with a brand new mixer (I do not know the product name). Unfortunately, mixers are generally used with vinyl records, not CDs. 
 
Ben told me that you need something else with the mixer to spin a virtual platter, so I checked online and found Virtual DJ, a product that has “all the professional features a real DJ will need.”
http://www.virtualdj.com/products/
 
I am not sure about this so I thought I would ask my friends on the list. Will this product (or something like it) allow Ben to mix from my favorite CD tracks and create a completely different compilation? Or is it even worth the price/trouble?
 
Thx,
Greg VP
--NextPart_Webmail_9m3u9jl4l_11694_1129841484_0--

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Technology: spinning a virtual platter from CD tracks

On 10/20/05, gregvp@comcast.net <gregvp@comcast.net> wrote:
> What if you want to take your favorite songs and put them together? You h=
ave to eliminate or change the transition to the next track and perform bea=
t matching.
>
> You can't just "rip" and burn the song, it doesn't sound right because it=
 cuts off abruptly.
>
> You need a DJ!

first- read the "advanced vinyl handling" tutorial on hyperreal for
enough theory to build a good understanding of how mixing is done.

then, find and play with software called Ableton Live. i've done one
mix w/ it recently (industrial/power-noise, really should have started
learning the software w/ something more conventional but oh well) and
am mostly done with a lighter, more accessible breaks mix.

> So I called my friend Ben, a young lifeguard who is an aspiring bedroom D=
J with a brand new mixer (I do not know the product name). Unfortunately, m=
ixers are generally used with vinyl records, not CDs.

you can use a mixer with either, all it does is take in signals on
multiple channels, and, well, mix them :) the main difference is that
turntables put out a phono signal and CD decks w/ pitch control
usually do line-level; but almost all mixers have a toggle switch
above each channel to go back & forth between the two.

but yeah, lowest-investment way to get what you want is Ableton Live.
mixing with that is pretty much a 3-step process-

1. let Ableton analyze the track, then correct any errors it made w/
regards to timing the beats
2. line the incoming track up w/ the outgoing track (this is called
phrasing, i'm being brief because the hyperreal doc mentioned above
will tell you all you need to know)
3. proof-listen to the mix, make sure it sounds good

repeat until finished.

-dk

--- gregvp@comcast.net wrote:

> Hello everyone,
> Please forgive my ignorance on this topic but I have a goal
> with some personal urgency. My birthday is Friday and all I
> want is a DJ mix from my CD collection.
>  
> Sometimes we buy CDs just because they have a good dance song
> that we can’t find anywhere else. Often your favorite song is
> mixed in a continuous pattern per the DJ’s intention.
>  
> What if you want to take your favorite songs and put them
> together? You have to eliminate or change the transition to
> the next track and perform beat matching. 
>  
> You can’t just “rip” and burn the song, it doesn’t sound
> right because it cuts off abruptly.
>  
> You need a DJ!
>  
> So I called my friend Ben, a young lifeguard who is an
> aspiring bedroom DJ with a brand new mixer (I do not know the
> product name). Unfortunately, mixers are generally used with
> vinyl records, not CDs. 
>  
> Ben told me that you need something else with the mixer to
> spin a virtual platter, so I checked online and found Virtual
> DJ, a product that has “all the professional features a real
> DJ will need.”
> http://www.virtualdj.com/products/
>  
> I am not sure about this so I thought I would ask my friends
> on the list. Will this product (or something like it) allow
> Ben to mix from my favorite CD tracks and create a completely
> different compilation? Or is it even worth the price/trouble?
>  
> Thx,
> Greg VP
