Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr: nazca, peru

Actually now I have to play devil's advocate. The legend of Atlantis
actually comes from a story in a dialogue by Plato. The weird thing
about Plato is that his writings are all just transcriptions of
conversations that Socrates had, and Socrates spent a roughly equal
amount of time enlightening people by telling them things they didn't
know and making fun of them by telling them things that were obviously
nonsense. There are really only two ways to make sense of his famous
dialogue on memory, the Meno, which are:

a) Socrates was saying ridiculous things because he was a total fucking mor=
on
b) Socrates was saying ridiculous things because the guy he was
talking to was a total fucking moron.

Most scholars go for interpretation B. The word "meno" in Greek, as
it's spelled in the dialogue, actually means "I stay" or "I don't go
anywhere." But Meno is the name of the guy that Socrates is talking to
in the dialogue. Meno is kind of bullheaded and unimaginative, and
every time Socrates tries to explain an idea, Meno doesn't get it.
Eventually Socrates compares the working of the mind to a chariot
race; if it had happened today, he would have been saying, "OK, Meno;
see if you can figure this out. The mind is like NASCAR." He also
spends some time teaching Meno's slave boy geometry; some people say
the point of it was to demonstrate to Meno that all he had to do was
open his mind and think for five minutes.

Either way -- because of all this I take anything which comes from
Plato with massive grains of salt. It's like quoting Shakespeare -- it
sounds very authoritative, but the reality is that just because he had
a character in a play say it, doesn't mean he actually believed a word
of it. In fact if you're writing a play you might have people say
stuff that is the exact opposite of what you believe, in order to
represent ideas you disagree with, or even have characters say things
that are the exact opposite of what **they** believe, in order to
enable scenes of suspense and deceit, which obviously happens in a
large number of Shakespearean plays.

So -- Plato said that Socrates said there was a continent called
Atlantis. Already we're playing telephone, but assume that this is
what Socrates actually said. The thing is, Socrates was very
knowledgeable, but he was not above making shit up. In addition to
being the kind of guy who did from time to time make things up just to
fuck with people -- which is one of the reasons they killed him -- the
Greeks in that day had great reverence for the Egyptians. The Greeks
got geometry from Egypt, and Plato's dialogues on geometry are almost
religious in their reverence. Actually "almost" is bullshit. Plato
**was** religious about geometry. Pythagoras was too; when he
discovered the Pythagorean Theorem, he actually sacrificed a bull.
Normally in those days people sacrificed bulls to the gods, but
Pythagoras was an atheist. He sacrificed the bull to geometry.

Anyway, long story short, the Greeks had a very high opinion of the
Egyptians at the time, and if Socrates says, as he does in the
dialogue where he introduces the language of Atlantis, that "this is
an ancient Egyptian legend," he could be telling the truth, and he
could be just saying that because it makes the story sound like more
of a big deal in the mind of his audience. There are definitely
dialogues in which he introduces things as "Egyptian legends" which
are almost certainly not actually legends from Egypt. Long story
short, the legend of Atlantis comes from Socrates, and any time it's
Socrates people are talking about, you want to find out not just what
he said, but who he said it to, and what kind of mood he was in at the
time.

That was kind of overkill, but you have to understand, before becoming
the kind of geek who learns computer languages for fun, I was the kind
of geek who learnt classical languages for fun.

All that being said, I haven't actually read the dialogue with
Atlantis in it in a very, very long time, and I have to admit, the
correlations on that web site are surprisingly specific.

Just as a side note, now that Socrates has popped his name into this
conversation. Everytime i see or hear his name i always flash back to
So-Crates (as it was pronounced in Bill and Ted's). God damn did that movie
rock. Too bad my buddy moved away, i'd be all down to dress up like bill an=
d
ted again this year for halloween.
 Now back to atlantis. I remember watching a Discovery channel show about
this and aside from finding that there may be a few possible locations for
atlantis, they discovered on in the mediterranean. I think it was an island
called Santorini, but i'm not totally sure, it was a while back that i saw
this, and all the stuff i pull up about santorini doesnt seem to ring a bel=
l
other then the name. Anywho...they discovered an underwater island of sorts=
.
It was the top of a volcano, and it appears that due to a violent eruption
or earthquake it was shook and sunk under water.
 They have sent divers down to check it out and they have found signs of
civilization. And it does appear to be in the shape of several rings just a=
s
Atlantis much in the way Atlantis was described. They will be continuing to
explorer this site for evidence of Atlantis. It's centralized location to
places like egypt, greece and italy could explain how survivors (if any)
were "deposited around the world" (the known world at the time) and able to
spread the same story among many differant civilizations.
 As a side note to the "known world" the Great Flood with Noah and his ark.
Wasn't a world wide flood per say as it was just a major flood that occured
in an area where when all was said and done appeared to have covered the
whole world. They've found underwater around the edges of the Black Sea
signs of civilization and are hypothosizing that this could have been the
area of the Great Flood. Water from the medditeranean rose (probably due to
melting glaciers) and since the area of the Black sea is below sea level,
the water came across the land and flooded that area in a rather short
amount of time, and thus "flooded the world"
 The one aspect of this that it doesnt really account is the fact that just
about every civilization from around the world has some sort of Great Flood
story in its history. If they all happened at the same time, who knows, if
so were they all caused by the melting of glaciers and such, possibly. The
one thing that sucks is we'll never know. It was too far in the past and
there's no way we would be able to find definitive evidence to support
either side of the argument. Some of these "great floods" could have been
caused by tsunamis either created by earthquakes or land slides. There are
just too many variables to account for, which is so frustrating. I would
love to know the answers. I hope that one day when i finally die, that i do
get to see all the answers. Like a giant cheat shett gets handed to you by
death so you have something to ride as you take your trip across the river
styx (domo arigato mr. roboto). A cheat sheet and a stat sheet is all i
want. I want to know all the answers to life the universe and everything

stats (like in GTA) that would be awesome, in i'm so curious to see if that
really does happen i just might off and kill my *BLAMMO*...............

 On 10/21/05, Giles Soundwave <dj.soundwave@gmail.com> wrote:
>
> Actually now I have to play devil's advocate. The legend of Atlantis
> actually comes from a story in a dialogue by Plato. The weird thing
> about Plato is that his writings are all just transcriptions of
> conversations that Socrates had, and Socrates spent a roughly equal
> amount of time enlightening people by telling them things they didn't
> know and making fun of them by telling them things that were obviously
> nonsense. There are really only two ways to make sense of his famous
> dialogue on memory, the Meno, which are:
>
> a) Socrates was saying ridiculous things because he was a total fucking
> moron
> b) Socrates was saying ridiculous things because the guy he was
> talking to was a total fucking moron.
>
> Most scholars go for interpretation B. The word "meno" in Greek, as
> it's spelled in the dialogue, actually means "I stay" or "I don't go
> anywhere." But Meno is the name of the guy that Socrates is talking to
> in the dialogue. Meno is kind of bullheaded and unimaginative, and
> every time Socrates tries to explain an idea, Meno doesn't get it.
> Eventually Socrates compares the working of the mind to a chariot
> race; if it had happened today, he would have been saying, "OK, Meno;
> see if you can figure this out. The mind is like NASCAR." He also
> spends some time teaching Meno's slave boy geometry; some people say
> the point of it was to demonstrate to Meno that all he had to do was
> open his mind and think for five minutes.
>
> Either way -- because of all this I take anything which comes from
> Plato with massive grains of salt. It's like quoting Shakespeare -- it
> sounds very authoritative, but the reality is that just because he had
> a character in a play say it, doesn't mean he actually believed a word
> of it. In fact if you're writing a play you might have people say
> stuff that is the exact opposite of what you believe, in order to
> represent ideas you disagree with, or even have characters say things
> that are the exact opposite of what **they** believe, in order to
> enable scenes of suspense and deceit, which obviously happens in a
> large number of Shakespearean plays.
>
> So -- Plato said that Socrates said there was a continent called
> Atlantis. Already we're playing telephone, but assume that this is
> what Socrates actually said. The thing is, Socrates was very
> knowledgeable, but he was not above making shit up. In addition to
> being the kind of guy who did from time to time make things up just to
> fuck with people -- which is one of the reasons they killed him -- the
> Greeks in that day had great reverence for the Egyptians. The Greeks
> got geometry from Egypt, and Plato's dialogues on geometry are almost
> religious in their reverence. Actually "almost" is bullshit. Plato
> **was** religious about geometry. Pythagoras was too; when he
> discovered the Pythagorean Theorem, he actually sacrificed a bull.
> Normally in those days people sacrificed bulls to the gods, but
> Pythagoras was an atheist. He sacrificed the bull to geometry.
>
> Anyway, long story short, the Greeks had a very high opinion of the
> Egyptians at the time, and if Socrates says, as he does in the
> dialogue where he introduces the language of Atlantis, that "this is
> an ancient Egyptian legend," he could be telling the truth, and he
> could be just saying that because it makes the story sound like more
> of a big deal in the mind of his audience. There are definitely
> dialogues in which he introduces things as "Egyptian legends" which
> are almost certainly not actually legends from Egypt. Long story
> short, the legend of Atlantis comes from Socrates, and any time it's
> Socrates people are talking about, you want to find out not just what
> he said, but who he said it to, and what kind of mood he was in at the
> time.
>
> That was kind of overkill, but you have to understand, before becoming
> the kind of geek who learns computer languages for fun, I was the kind
> of geek who learnt classical languages for fun.
>
> All that being said, I haven't actually read the dialogue with
> Atlantis in it in a very, very long time, and I have to admit, the
> correlations on that web site are surprisingly specific.
>
>
>

>Actually now I have to play devil's advocate. The legend of Atlantis
>actually comes from a story in a dialogue by Plato. The weird thing
>about Plato is that his writings are all just transcriptions of
>conversations that Socrates had, and Socrates spent a roughly equal
>amount of time enlightening people by telling them things they didn't
>know and making fun of them by telling them things that were obviously
>nonsense. There are really only two ways to make sense of his famous
>dialogue on memory, the Meno, which are:
>
>a) Socrates was saying ridiculous things because he was a total fucking 
>moron
>b) Socrates was saying ridiculous things because the guy he was
>talking to was a total fucking moron.
>
>Most scholars go for interpretation B. The word "meno" in Greek, as
>it's spelled in the dialogue, actually means "I stay" or "I don't go
>anywhere." But Meno is the name of the guy that Socrates is talking to
>in the dialogue. Meno is kind of bullheaded and unimaginative, and
>every time Socrates tries to explain an idea, Meno doesn't get it.
>Eventually Socrates compares the working of the mind to a chariot
>race; if it had happened today, he would have been saying, "OK, Meno;
>see if you can figure this out. The mind is like NASCAR." He also
>spends some time teaching Meno's slave boy geometry; some people say
>the point of it was to demonstrate to Meno that all he had to do was
>open his mind and think for five minutes.
>
>Either way -- because of all this I take anything which comes from
>Plato with massive grains of salt. It's like quoting Shakespeare -- it
>sounds very authoritative, but the reality is that just because he had
>a character in a play say it, doesn't mean he actually believed a word
>of it. In fact if you're writing a play you might have people say
>stuff that is the exact opposite of what you believe, in order to
>represent ideas you disagree with, or even have characters say things
>that are the exact opposite of what **they** believe, in order to
>enable scenes of suspense and deceit, which obviously happens in a
>large number of Shakespearean plays.
>
>So -- Plato said that Socrates said there was a continent called
>Atlantis. Already we're playing telephone, but assume that this is
>what Socrates actually said. The thing is, Socrates was very
>knowledgeable, but he was not above making shit up. In addition to
>being the kind of guy who did from time to time make things up just to
>fuck with people -- which is one of the reasons they killed him -- the
>Greeks in that day had great reverence for the Egyptians. The Greeks
>got geometry from Egypt, and Plato's dialogues on geometry are almost
>religious in their reverence. Actually "almost" is bullshit. Plato
>**was** religious about geometry. Pythagoras was too; when he
>discovered the Pythagorean Theorem, he actually sacrificed a bull.
>Normally in those days people sacrificed bulls to the gods, but
>Pythagoras was an atheist. He sacrificed the bull to geometry.
>
>Anyway, long story short, the Greeks had a very high opinion of the
>Egyptians at the time, and if Socrates says, as he does in the
>dialogue where he introduces the language of Atlantis, that "this is
>an ancient Egyptian legend," he could be telling the truth, and he
>could be just saying that because it makes the story sound like more
>of a big deal in the mind of his audience. There are definitely
>dialogues in which he introduces things as "Egyptian legends" which
>are almost certainly not actually legends from Egypt. Long story
>short, the legend of Atlantis comes from Socrates, and any time it's
>Socrates people are talking about, you want to find out not just what
>he said, but who he said it to, and what kind of mood he was in at the
>time.
>
>That was kind of overkill, but you have to understand, before becoming
>the kind of geek who learns computer languages for fun, I was the kind
>of geek who learnt classical languages for fun.
>
>All that being said, I haven't actually read the dialogue with
>Atlantis in it in a very, very long time, and I have to admit, the
>correlations on that web site are surprisingly specific.
>
>
>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr: nazca, peru

I have seen that show - and Santorini has actually been considered as one of 
the likely spots for Atlantis since at least the late 70's. Also Bimini in 
the Bahamas, and a few other locations worldwide.

The thing about the South American theory that gets me juiced, is that there 
has been evidence of cocaine and other herbs/plants ONLY native to the 
Americas found in Egyptian mummies, dating back to the old kingdom of Egypt 
that suggests that there HAD to have been trade of some sort between the 
continents.

The Norwegian explorer Thor Heyerdahl did research on this, and proved that 
reed boats (used in ancient times) could indeed cross the oceans. Ther's no 
direct EVIDENCE thus far that this has happened, but there's a whole shit 
load of circumstantial evidence that suggests that it had to have happened. 
For instance, there's a temple/pyramid somewhere in South Africa (on an 
island off the coast anyway) that appears to be the same design as all the 
South American pyramids. Not like the Egyptian ones at all.

Interesting shit...

>  On 10/21/05, Giles Soundwave <dj.soundwave@gmail.com> wrote:
> >
> > Actually now I have to play devil's advocate. The legend of Atlantis
> > actually comes from a story in a dialogue by Plato. The weird thing
> > about Plato is that his writings are all just transcriptions of
> > conversations that Socrates had, and Socrates spent a roughly equal
> > amount of time enlightening people by telling them things they didn't
> > know and making fun of them by telling them things that were obviously
> > nonsense. There are really only two ways to make sense of his famous
> > dialogue on memory, the Meno, which are:
> >
> > a) Socrates was saying ridiculous things because he was a total fucking
> > moron
> > b) Socrates was saying ridiculous things because the guy he was
> > talking to was a total fucking moron.
> >
> > Most scholars go for interpretation B. The word "meno" in Greek, as
> > it's spelled in the dialogue, actually means "I stay" or "I don't go
> > anywhere." But Meno is the name of the guy that Socrates is talking to
> > in the dialogue. Meno is kind of bullheaded and unimaginative, and
> > every time Socrates tries to explain an idea, Meno doesn't get it.
> > Eventually Socrates compares the working of the mind to a chariot
> > race; if it had happened today, he would have been saying, "OK, Meno;
> > see if you can figure this out. The mind is like NASCAR." He also
> > spends some time teaching Meno's slave boy geometry; some people say
> > the point of it was to demonstrate to Meno that all he had to do was
> > open his mind and think for five minutes.
> >
> > Either way -- because of all this I take anything which comes from
> > Plato with massive grains of salt. It's like quoting Shakespeare -- it
> > sounds very authoritative, but the reality is that just because he had
> > a character in a play say it, doesn't mean he actually believed a word
> > of it. In fact if you're writing a play you might have people say
> > stuff that is the exact opposite of what you believe, in order to
> > represent ideas you disagree with, or even have characters say things
> > that are the exact opposite of what **they** believe, in order to
> > enable scenes of suspense and deceit, which obviously happens in a
> > large number of Shakespearean plays.
> >
> > So -- Plato said that Socrates said there was a continent called
> > Atlantis. Already we're playing telephone, but assume that this is
> > what Socrates actually said. The thing is, Socrates was very
> > knowledgeable, but he was not above making shit up. In addition to
> > being the kind of guy who did from time to time make things up just to
> > fuck with people -- which is one of the reasons they killed him -- the
> > Greeks in that day had great reverence for the Egyptians. The Greeks
> > got geometry from Egypt, and Plato's dialogues on geometry are almost
> > religious in their reverence. Actually "almost" is bullshit. Plato
> > **was** religious about geometry. Pythagoras was too; when he
> > discovered the Pythagorean Theorem, he actually sacrificed a bull.
> > Normally in those days people sacrificed bulls to the gods, but
> > Pythagoras was an atheist. He sacrificed the bull to geometry.
> >
> > Anyway, long story short, the Greeks had a very high opinion of the
> > Egyptians at the time, and if Socrates says, as he does in the
> > dialogue where he introduces the language of Atlantis, that "this is
> > an ancient Egyptian legend," he could be telling the truth, and he
> > could be just saying that because it makes the story sound like more
> > of a big deal in the mind of his audience. There are definitely
> > dialogues in which he introduces things as "Egyptian legends" which
> > are almost certainly not actually legends from Egypt. Long story
> > short, the legend of Atlantis comes from Socrates, and any time it's
> > Socrates people are talking about, you want to find out not just what
> > he said, but who he said it to, and what kind of mood he was in at the
> > time.
> >
> > That was kind of overkill, but you have to understand, before becoming
> > the kind of geek who learns computer languages for fun, I was the kind
> > of geek who learnt classical languages for fun.
> >
> > All that being said, I haven't actually read the dialogue with
> > Atlantis in it in a very, very long time, and I have to admit, the
> > correlations on that web site are surprisingly specific.
> >
> >
> >

worth of coke would last me a night. Where as $150 worth of meth could last
me a week, although one time a friend and i did about $90 worth in about an
hour and a half. Man was that intense. And with the numberous manufacturers
of meth, it wasnt all that hard to find, where as with coke you had to
search and search and search.
 I look back now and i'm so glad i moved outta oregon. That place would hav=
e
been the death of me. I no longer had to buy meth anymore, i knew so many
people who either did it or dealt it, i got it for free all day everyday.
Granted the very day i moved down here i had already found a meth hook up,
but it didn't pan out for very long because it was a little more involved t=
o
get it rather then calling up a friend and "hanging out" for a while. And m=
y
usage dropped off almost instantly. I still managed to do it a little bit
here and there, but it was growing fewer and further inbetween, and now i'v=
e
been off that shit for 3-4 years. I still sometimes think about it and thin=
k
man it sure would help out in this situation or that situation or whatever,
but then i think about how it lasts a lot longer then any given situation
requires and it just doesn't go away when your done needing it.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: PAOLO MOJO

OK.. all U last minute groovers... check this out!!  Happening 2night..
sorry late w/ BSP.. but hear ya go!

PAOLO MOJO on 10/22/05 at 111 Minna
http://drive.c.topica.com/maad6OCablfrMbPMgUxeaehqpO/
Sure, "genre-fication" is not in the dictionary. But neither is
"genre" in PAOLO MOJO's dictionary. In this day and age of
identifying dance music to ridiculously specified sub-genres
(electrotechydiscopunk or psyraggadrum'ndbreaks come to mind) we are
extremely proud to bring you the San Francisco debut of this UK
DJ/Producer who doesn't have a clue what the word is. PAOLO MOJO
said himself he doesn't understand "this 'genre' bollocks." To him,
music is about selecting the "best bits of a wide range of sounds
and put[ting] them together in a way that just makes sense to
people." Isn't it apropos that his latest CD Release (with Cass of
Cass and Slide) is called "Heretic?"

So join us for an evening of blasphemously good music and dance to
one of the best emerging DJ/Producers today. But don't take our
word for it.

"Paolo is one of the most talented new DJs; he?s a man you?ll be
hearing a lot more from."
? John Digweed

"He is constantly pushing and finding quality house music. One of
the best new DJs for sure."
? Hernan Cattaneo

"He plays GOOD music!"
? Lee Burridge

Enough said. We'll see you on the dancefloor!

WHO: PAOLO MOJO with Hoj, Will Spencer and the Funky Cozy Crew
(Sinukus, Jonathan Beech, and Tim McCormack)

WHEN: Saturday, October 22, 2005 from 9pm to 2am

WHERE: 111 Minna Gallery

DOOR: $10.00 ::: $7.00 presales @ www.groovetickets.com
($7.00 before 10:00 p.m.)

Osby Oi Oi Jamz <osby@viberation.com> wrote:
OK.. all U last minute groovers... check this out!! Happening 2night..
sorry late w/ BSP.. but hear ya go!

PAOLO MOJO on 10/22/05 at 111 Minna
http://drive.c.topica.com/maad6OCablfrMbPMgUxeaehqpO/
Sure, "genre-fication" is not in the dictionary. But neither is
"genre" in PAOLO MOJO's dictionary. In this day and age of
identifying dance music to ridiculously specified sub-genres
(electrotechydiscopunk or psyraggadrum'ndbreaks come to mind) we are
extremely proud to bring you the San Francisco debut of this UK
DJ/Producer who doesn't have a clue what the word is. PAOLO MOJO
said himself he doesn't understand "this 'genre' bollocks." To him,
music is about selecting the "best bits of a wide range of sounds
and put[ting] them together in a way that just makes sense to
people." Isn't it apropos that his latest CD Release (with Cass of
Cass and Slide) is called "Heretic?"

So join us for an evening of blasphemously good music and dance to
one of the best emerging DJ/Producers today. But don't take our
word for it.

"Paolo is one of the most talented new DJs; he?s a man you?ll be
hearing a lot more from."
? John Digweed

"He is constantly pushing and finding quality house music. One of
the best new DJs for sure."
? Hernan Cattaneo

"He plays GOOD music!"
? Lee Burridge

Enough said. We'll see you on the dancefloor!

WHO: PAOLO MOJO with Hoj, Will Spencer and the Funky Cozy Crew
(Sinukus, Jonathan Beech, and Tim McCormack)

WHEN: Saturday, October 22, 2005 from 9pm to 2am

WHERE: 111 Minna Gallery

DOOR: $10.00 ::: $7.00 presales @ www.groovetickets.com
($7.00 before 10:00 p.m.)

mmmmm blotter. blotter...blotter...blotter....i love blotter.
 I got a dope ass flyer for a party once that was on blotter paper, and it
was all perferated just like the real thing. Still have it too. That's one
flyer that was too cool to throw away.
 Anyone on the list remember Al Jourgensen's side project, Acid Horse? One
of my old bosses had an Acid Horse record and still have the original
blotter paper that came with it. Lucky bastard. I found the record once, bu=
t
it didnt have the blotter paper with it so i didnt pick it up.
 Speaking of cool additions to vinyl, my friend has a cheech and chong
record that came with a giant rolling paper in it. We were gonna use it onc=
e
for a huge ass joint. Never got around to it, we couldnt break down and do
it since it was the only one we had. Then one day we pulled it out just to
look at it, and there will small pieces missing out of it, someone cut smal=
l
pieces out of it to roll up joints. Turns out it was out phat friend Phatty=
.
bastard. Luckily my friend found another copy that still had the full piece
of paper intact, so all's good now.

Ya I went to go see that show after reading about him on sfr.  It was pretty 
solid.. the guy has a great way of keeping the beats rolling in and out of 
differing styles without letting the breakbeat break-off track, or getting 
lost in transition.. I thought that was pretty sic, even though I wasn't 
into all the varios styles he played.. but he was pretty much flawless on 
the deck and nice as hell.. I went to talk to him afterword and he's all.. 
hit me up for a free cd.. so I did.. Kewl mofo fo sho!

Ranger

From: Kevin James <djkevinjames@yahoo.com>

Dam. I so wish I could have been there. That guy is off the hook. I'm not 
sure about calling him a "new" or "emerging dj though. He's been pretty big 
in the tech-house community for a few years at least.

Osby Oi Oi Jamz <osby@viberation.com> wrote:
OK.. all U last minute groovers... check this out!! Happening 2night..
sorry late w/ BSP.. but hear ya go!

PAOLO MOJO on 10/22/05 at 111 Minna
http://drive.c.topica.com/maad6OCablfrMbPMgUxeaehqpO/
Sure, "genre-fication" is not in the dictionary. But neither is
"genre" in PAOLO MOJO's dictionary. In this day and age of
identifying dance music to ridiculously specified sub-genres
(electrotechydiscopunk or psyraggadrum'ndbreaks come to mind) we are
extremely proud to bring you the San Francisco debut of this UK
DJ/Producer who doesn't have a clue what the word is. PAOLO MOJO
said himself he doesn't understand "this 'genre' bollocks." To him,
music is about selecting the "best bits of a wide range of sounds
and put[ting] them together in a way that just makes sense to
people." Isn't it apropos that his latest CD Release (with Cass of
Cass and Slide) is called "Heretic?"

So join us for an evening of blasphemously good music and dance to
one of the best emerging DJ/Producers today. But don't take our
word for it.

"Paolo is one of the most talented new DJs; he?s a man you?ll be
hearing a lot more from."
? John Digweed

"He is constantly pushing and finding quality house music. One of
the best new DJs for sure."
? Hernan Cattaneo

"He plays GOOD music!"
? Lee Burridge

Enough said. We'll see you on the dancefloor!

WHO: PAOLO MOJO with Hoj, Will Spencer and the Funky Cozy Crew
(Sinukus, Jonathan Beech, and Tim McCormack)

WHEN: Saturday, October 22, 2005 from 9pm to 2am

WHERE: 111 Minna Gallery

DOOR: $10.00 ::: $7.00 presales @ www.groovetickets.com
($7.00 before 10:00 p.m.)



--
Take Care <3
Peace=->Jus' Me =-> O§bY {8O)

DIE WARZAU'S LATEST BLOG ON MYSPACE



Monday, October 24, 2005


The Loudest word in the world


"No"
---Rosa Parks.


In 1955, in Montgomery, Alabama, you didn't say no. You went to the 
back of the bus and you did what was expected of you. Without 
violence, without undue drama or pathos, disrespect or anger, Rosa 
Parks said no. And because she risked everything, 50,000 people put 
their lives on hold and, in her name, walked rather than ride the 
bus. They stood up against an injustice they had been tutored in 
their entire lives and forced themselves to ignore their own safety 
and fight back. Her sacrifice, and a lifetime of working towards 
justice, led to the rise of the Reverend Doctor Martin Luther King 
and his message of peaceful civil dissent. She changed the world with 
a single word, backed up by a lifetime's worth of conviction.

Rosa Parks' family told the press this evening that she passed away. 
No more information was available. She spoke in the voice of dissent- 
the voice of the spirit of this country. She spoke with the authority 
of Boston Tea Party-birthed decades of dissent and refusal to accept 
injustice. We have no way to judge what America would have looked 
like without her.

Ironically, her death is only days shy of Rosa Parks Nationwide Day 
of Absence Against Poverty Racism and War proposed for December 1st. 
Larry Holmes, an organizer with the Nationwide Day of Absence, said,

  "The government's response to the Katrina Hurricane disaster, along 
with the war in Iraq and the growing numbers of people without 
healthcare, employment and educational opportunities, and housing are 
a poignant reminder that the movement to end poverty racism and war 
is as urgent now as it was 50 years ago, We have an opportunity to 
turn one of the most important civil rights anniversaries into a 
powerful reaffirmation of our commitment to fight for racial 
equality, social justice and peace, the lofty goals that Dr. King 
devoted his short brilliant life to and ultimately sacrificed it for."

In New York City, the day will be marked with a march and rally on 
Broadway and Wall St. where civil rights leaders, including members 
of the King family and veterans of the Montgomery boycott will speak.

The Day of Absence is our chance to say "no", the way she did. It is 
our chance to stand up and follow her example to speak to the 
injustice we see around us. It is our chance to say that Healthcare, 
Housing, and Education are our human priorities as Americans-- Not 
War and Occupation, domination and economic colonialism. The civil 
rights movement in this country is not dead. It still needs each and 
every one of us as powerfully as it needed Ms. Parks. It still needs 
her word, the one she made famous, the one she used with such grace 
and skill, humility and bravery.

The loudest word in the world.

The Rosa Parks Anniversary Nationwide Day of Absence Against Poverty 
Racism & War Coalition
39 W. 14TH St.,
Suite 206 NY NY 10011
PH 212 633-6646
FAX 212 633-2889
http://www.troopsoutnow.org





MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo

Tribenet: 
<http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm



"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

--=====================_9377250==.ALT--

>
>You know what else would kick ass for a Halloween party? Combine VJing
>with a haunted house. There's a magazine called Make which contains a
>nice tutorial for this. It revolves around setting up a relay control
>board that can be connected to any computer's parallel port and
>thereby used to programatically control virtually any electrical
>equipment. You set up a nice scary tunnel, a bunch of crazy fucking
>visuals, and a range of laptop-controlled electrical sources for
>additional sensory stimuli (speakers, space heaters, fans, lights, fog
>machines, carefully secured chainsaws, industrial machinery, etc.).
>The laptop control could be pre-programmed, but a realtime control
>interface that a VJ could use in connection with the visuals and/or
>which a DJ could use in connection with the music would be
>significantly more effective. I mean seriously, fuck an Ecler, fuck a
>Rane, make your own mixer and put a button on it that says "chainsaw
>#4." That's how you throw a party.
>
>
>--
>Giles Soundwave = Giles Goat Boy
>http://www.gilesgoatboy.org/
>
>
>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr: AIM my robot!

Actually I've already done that. The most important component of Weird
Science weird was a hot brunette with super-powers. To acquire that
component, just use the super-powered bitch magnet, and tweak a few
lines of code so that the super-powered female you obtain is only a
bitch to other people, but nice to you, which, if you remember, is
pretty much how it worked in "Weird Science." That's left as an
exercise for the reader. The GoogleBot system is really a whole nother
ball of wax. The GilesGoogleBot, if it is completed successfully, will
be followed by other GoogleBots. In fact if a suitable corpus of text
exists and is visible to Google, and AndyW is willing to grant his
permission, you can expect to see an AndyWGoogleBot sometime this year
or next. Should that occur, it will certainly be pretty weird.
However, I have to admit, unless you perceive AndyW very differently
than I do, it won't actually be particularly Weird Science weird.
It'll definitely fall at the Real Genius end of the spectrum.

Subject: [sfraves] World Class Talent Comes to San Jose Tomorrow Night!

Karma Wednesdays and The Blue Monkey Lounge are proud
to present, 
Mr. David Alvarado
This is your only chance to catch one of the most
influential artists to come to San Jose in a long
time. With over 50 releases and remixes under his
belt, as well as his tracks making it on to Dj mixes
and compilations from such respected artists as John
Digweed, Terry Lee Brown Jr., Danny Howells, Jon
Marsh, John Selway, Carl Cox, Terry Farley, Pete
Heller, Josh Wink and Hipp-e to name a few. If you are
any kind of music fan, you owe it to yourself to come
down tomorrow night and catch this exclusive
appearance. That’s right! He’s not stopping in the
city, it’s San Jose, and then he’s out…

Oh and here’s the clincher…. ….It’s FREE! No cover, no
door charge, no hidden fees.
So you really have no excuse to miss this one……The
Blue Monkey Lounge is located at 1 E. San Fernando St.
in Downtown San Jose and features some of the tastiest
Tacos on the planet. See you tomorrow night!

David Alvarado’s Bio:
American underground music possesses a spirituality
and depth that can only come out of the cultural and
social melting pot that is unique to this country. As
someone who has spent more than a decade interpreting
his life experiences into music, David Alvarado has
mastered the art of creating music that truly touches
peoples souls, not only here in the U.S., but around
the world. He uses every sound, every image that comes
in to his life as his inspiration to make music that
evokes the spirit of an underground culture of music
that has existed for the last century. 
While growing up in Los Angeles David forged an
appreciation for music that was quickly being changed
by technology. His early experimentation lead him to
produce the "Las Americas Project", a single that
captured the attention of Plus8 records Richie Hawtin
and John Acquaviva, who at the time were in the
process of developing a new house imprint by the name
of Definitive Records. Through this relationship David
was introduced to other up in coming artist's and
labels such as the Toronto based Stickman Records and
Philadelphia DJ Josh Wink. His experience and exposure
to the growing house music community led him to begin
his own imprint, Bomb Records, which further
contributed to helping David expand his audience and
develop his signature sound as an artist. Bomb Records
not only was the vehicle by which David increased his
global audience, but also featured then up and coming
artists Kenneth Grahm, Eddie Amador, and Derrick
Carter.
The foresight that David exhibited with his own
production and the selections for his label quickly
sparked international interest and created a tour
schedule that grew increasingly demanding. Despite his
hectic travels David has remained focused in the
studio and completed an impressive body of work for
his own label, and for highly respected labels
including Ovum, Ultra, Strictly Rhythm, Yoshi Toshi,
Plastic City, and Peace Frog. In addition to his work
as an artist he has created a catalog of highly
acclaimed mix CDs for Chicago's Guidance Records,
Madrid's Deep Sessions Vol. 2 and United DJs of
America Vol. 15. All of which are now considered
classics in there own right.
This amazing producer whose tracks have been described
as having the longest shelf life of any releases a
record shop could carry is still hard at work
capturing the hearts and souls of a new generation of
electronic music fans. He has also developed a new
record label Sunchildren which brings an amazingly
beautiful, sexier twist to the already established
West Coast house sound. David asserts that the label
will incorporate eclectic Latin, Brazilian, and
African elements to bring a much welcomed warmth &
sensuality to the genre. If this new angle proves to
be as influential as his previous projects it will no
doubt keep West Coast House and David Alvarado right
where they belong, in the center of the world house
arena.



The Tracks 
http://www.7161.com/~retroactivefunk
http://www.myspace.com/laptopmusic
The Mixes
http://www.waxdj.com/djs/780/
About Me:
http://www.myspace.com/gabrielblack
http://www.myspace.com/techhouse
The Corrado
http://www.cardomain.com/ride/2146882

Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] nrr: alternatives to sky-watching

1. Do something.
2. Do something else.
3. Continue doing things until satisfied.

It just occured to me, I'm sure most people have enough common sense
to realize this, but just in case, "watch the skies" is not an
assignment to be pursued until presented with further instructions;
you're supposed to just look up, take a quick gander, and then do
something. And stuff. On the offchance that anybody reads this stuff
and then spends hours watching the planet Jupiter through a telescope
as it moves into Scorpio, somehow expecting that to solve your
problems, well, that's not what I'm saying.

--
Giles Soundwave =3D Giles Goat Boy
http://www.gilesgoatboy.org/

"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] David Alvarado in SJ 2 night.... 4 Free?

Karma Wednesdays and The Blue Monkey Lounge are proud
to present, 
Mr. David Alvarado
This is your only chance to catch one of the most
influential artists to come to San Jose in a long
time. With over 50 releases and remixes under his
belt, as well as his tracks making it on to Dj mixes
and compilations from such respected artists as John
Digweed, Terry Lee Brown Jr., Danny Howells, Jon
Marsh, John Selway, Carl Cox, Terry Farley, Pete
Heller, Josh Wink and Hipp-e to name a few. If you are
any kind of music fan, you owe it to yourself to come
down tomorrow night and catch this exclusive
appearance. That’s right! He’s not stopping in the
city, it’s San Jose, and then he’s out…

Oh and here’s the clincher…. ….It’s FREE! No cover, no
door charge, no hidden fees.
So you really have no excuse to miss this one……The
Blue Monkey Lounge is located at 1 E. San Fernando St.
in Downtown San Jose and features some of the tastiest
Tacos on the planet. See you tomorrow night!


David Alvarado’s Bio:
American underground music possesses a spirituality
and depth that can only come out of the cultural and
social melting pot that is unique to this country. As
someone who has spent more than a decade interpreting
his life experiences into music, David Alvarado has
mastered the art of creating music that truly touches
peoples souls, not only here in the U.S., but around
the world. He uses every sound, every image that comes
in to his life as his inspiration to make music that
evokes the spirit of an underground culture of music
that has existed for the last century. 
While growing up in Los Angeles David forged an
appreciation for music that was quickly being changed
by technology. His early experimentation lead him to
produce the "Las Americas Project", a single that
captured the attention of Plus8 records Richie Hawtin
and John Acquaviva, who at the time were in the
process of developing a new house imprint by the name
of Definitive Records. Through this relationship David
was introduced to other up in coming artist's and
labels such as the Toronto based Stickman Records and
Philadelphia DJ Josh Wink. His experience and exposure
to the growing house music community led him to begin
his own imprint, Bomb Records, which further
contributed to helping David expand his audience and
develop his signature sound as an artist. Bomb Records
not only was the vehicle by which David increased his
global audience, but also featured then up and coming
artists Kenneth Grahm, Eddie Amador, and Derrick
Carter.
The foresight that David exhibited with his own
production and the selections for his label quickly
sparked international interest and created a tour
schedule that grew increasingly demanding. Despite his
hectic travels David has remained focused in the
studio and completed an impressive body of work for
his own label, and for highly respected labels
including Ovum, Ultra, Strictly Rhythm, Yoshi Toshi,
Plastic City, and Peace Frog. In addition to his work
as an artist he has created a catalog of highly
acclaimed mix CDs for Chicago's Guidance Records,
Madrid's Deep Sessions Vol. 2 and United DJs of
America Vol. 15. All of which are now considered
classics in there own right.
This amazing producer whose tracks have been described
as having the longest shelf life of any releases a
record shop could carry is still hard at work
capturing the hearts and souls of a new generation of
electronic music fans. He has also developed a new
record label Sunchildren which brings an amazingly
beautiful, sexier twist to the already established
West Coast house sound. David asserts that the label
will incorporate eclectic Latin, Brazilian, and
African elements to bring a much welcomed warmth &
sensuality to the genre. If this new angle proves to
be as influential as his previous projects it will no
doubt keep West Coast House and David Alvarado right
where they belong, in the center of the world house
arena.

Yeah totally. I'm a fast driver. Not really a speeder...(speeders are peopl=
e
who fly and weave through traffic) i just drive fast. 80-90 is confortable
cruising speed for me, slower and i feel weird. Faster is fine, just not
really prudent most of the time. If you're gonna drive slow, please at leas=
t
be aware. If you're in the fast lane and people are passing you, get the
hell over. If you look in your rear view mirror and you see me way behind
you and when you look back in your mirror and you see me right on your ass,
get the hell outta the way.
 Can't remember where i heard it. i think it was a history or discovery
channel show about the Auto Bahn. But basically it said that the Germans
thought the americans were stupid because we are forced to drive a certain
speed limit but we're allowed to go from lane to lane. Where as on the Auto
Bahn you can drive as fast as you want, but you have to stay in the left
lane. The right lane is for passing only and as soon as you've passed
someone you have to get back into the left lane. You can get ticketed for
driving in the right hand lane and your not passing someone.
 I think they should enforce that rule here. That way everyone will line up
all nice and perfectly. There will always be a lane for you to pass in
instead of getting over to pass someone only to find the retards in that
lane are slowing down and then your stuck between 2 lanes of idiots driving
slow.

--
Chester Copperpot

"Goonies never say die!"
"Meth Monsters are my Anti-Drug"
"I feel like I'm taking crazy pills"

Subject: [sfraves] nrr: the robot is dead. long live the robot.

(this has nothing to do with raves, but wtf.)

GilesGoogleBot is dead. if you talked to him during his brief life,
thank you very very much. the new robot's name is SkippyTalkBot. you
can find him on AIM. if you want to talk to him, please do, and ping
me (dreamstooloud) if he does anything weird.

so far I've had one terrific conversation with him:

[17:12] dreamstooloud: yo
[17:12] SkippyTalkBot: Joe.
[17:12] dreamstooloud: monkey
[17:12] SkippyTalkBot: Intelligent satire for the unwashed masses.
[17:12] dreamstooloud: happy penguins
[17:12] SkippyTalkBot: Madagascar.
[17:13] dreamstooloud: what time is love?
[17:13] SkippyTalkBot: Wonder.
[17:13] dreamstooloud: all right baby, that shit made sense to me. perfect.
[17:13] SkippyTalkBot: I left the house.

I really feel like we bonded.

You can pass on the left on the Autobahn - I dunno who said otherwise. The 
thing w/ German drivers is, they flick their lights on and off WAY behind 
you to let you know "I'm a comin' - get out the damn way!". If you DON'T - 
they get RIGHT UP ON YOUR ASS at high speeds, and will flick their lights 
and beep their horns at you till you get out of the way. German drivers 
don't fuck around - and I praise them for it.

In fact, when I drive, I drive like I'm on the autobahn, and it tends to 
work just fine. lol

I've been reading Car & Driver and Road & Track for ever since I was a
kid and they always pointed out that speed has nothing to do with the
amount of accidents. the number one thing that causes accidents is
people not paying attention.

Also, I remember in my high school drivers Ed class, after watching
"red asphault" on projector was the grey haired, tenured teacher
saying this quote: "All accidents can be avoided by just paying
attention".

We tried to challenge him on this, but he always had a perfect wise,
logical, response.

On Wed, 26 Oct 2005, Gabriel B wrote:

> Date: Wed, 26 Oct 2005 12:06:26 -0700 (PDT)
> From: Gabriel B <retroactivefunk@yahoo.com>
> To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
> Subject: [sfraves] David Alvarado in SJ 2 night.... 4 Free?
> 
> Karma Wednesdays and The Blue Monkey Lounge are proud
> to present,
> Mr. David Alvarado
> This is your only chance to catch one of the most
> influential artists to come to San Jose in a long
> time. With over 50 releases and remixes under his
> belt, as well as his tracks making it on to Dj mixes
> and compilations from such respected artists as John
> Digweed, Terry Lee Brown Jr., Danny Howells, Jon
> Marsh, John Selway, Carl Cox, Terry Farley, Pete
> Heller, Josh Wink and Hipp-e to name a few. If you are
> any kind of music fan, you owe it to yourself to come
> down tomorrow night and catch this exclusive
> appearance. That’s right! He’s not stopping in the
> city, it’s San Jose, and then he’s out…
>
> Oh and here’s the clincher…. ….It’s FREE! No cover, no
> door charge, no hidden fees.
> So you really have no excuse to miss this one……The
> Blue Monkey Lounge is located at 1 E. San Fernando St.
> in Downtown San Jose and features some of the tastiest
> Tacos on the planet. See you tomorrow night!
>
>
> David Alvarado’s Bio:
> American underground music possesses a spirituality
> and depth that can only come out of the cultural and
> social melting pot that is unique to this country. As
> someone who has spent more than a decade interpreting
> his life experiences into music, David Alvarado has
> mastered the art of creating music that truly touches
> peoples souls, not only here in the U.S., but around
> the world. He uses every sound, every image that comes
> in to his life as his inspiration to make music that
> evokes the spirit of an underground culture of music
> that has existed for the last century.
> While growing up in Los Angeles David forged an
> appreciation for music that was quickly being changed
> by technology. His early experimentation lead him to
> produce the "Las Americas Project", a single that
> captured the attention of Plus8 records Richie Hawtin
> and John Acquaviva, who at the time were in the
> process of developing a new house imprint by the name
> of Definitive Records. Through this relationship David
> was introduced to other up in coming artist's and
> labels such as the Toronto based Stickman Records and
> Philadelphia DJ Josh Wink. His experience and exposure
> to the growing house music community led him to begin
> his own imprint, Bomb Records, which further
> contributed to helping David expand his audience and
> develop his signature sound as an artist. Bomb Records
> not only was the vehicle by which David increased his
> global audience, but also featured then up and coming
> artists Kenneth Grahm, Eddie Amador, and Derrick
> Carter.
> The foresight that David exhibited with his own
> production and the selections for his label quickly
> sparked international interest and created a tour
> schedule that grew increasingly demanding. Despite his
> hectic travels David has remained focused in the
> studio and completed an impressive body of work for
> his own label, and for highly respected labels
> including Ovum, Ultra, Strictly Rhythm, Yoshi Toshi,
> Plastic City, and Peace Frog. In addition to his work
> as an artist he has created a catalog of highly
> acclaimed mix CDs for Chicago's Guidance Records,
> Madrid's Deep Sessions Vol. 2 and United DJs of
> America Vol. 15. All of which are now considered
> classics in there own right.
> This amazing producer whose tracks have been described
> as having the longest shelf life of any releases a
> record shop could carry is still hard at work
> capturing the hearts and souls of a new generation of
> electronic music fans. He has also developed a new
> record label Sunchildren which brings an amazingly
> beautiful, sexier twist to the already established
> West Coast house sound. David asserts that the label
> will incorporate eclectic Latin, Brazilian, and
> African elements to bring a much welcomed warmth &
> sensuality to the genre. If this new angle proves to
> be as influential as his previous projects it will no
> doubt keep West Coast House and David Alvarado right
> where they belong, in the center of the world house
> arena.
>
>

Subject: [sfraves] My 1st Jungle weeklie  here in UK

OK.. so after a day of like well.. I kinda nooo.. actually all we did was
like run errands & like well.. i wanted 2 go 2 a music shop 'cause like i
figure the imports that I always see there in the music shops home, I
could get here & they'd be here.. ok, i confess, i was looking for *NSYNC
albums... no luck :(  Although i ende dup getting 3 CDs.. LoL

So we chill for a bit.. then Carol finds this new Jungle weeklie close by
her pad.. then we go! The weeklie is called The Style Of The Streets...
it's hip hop, jungle, old skool... I guess we missed the 1st DJ spin
Hardcore 'cause this dude told me it was hardocre earlier (gggggr :(  )...
so they were spinning jungle.. oooooooooh my goooosh.. Hello 2Day.. so the
1st hour we were there... I guess they didn't do sound check or whatever
the fuck 'cause this DJ was on & he was traaaain wreeeecking like crazy...
his levels were always fucked, the sound system was kinda shot 2 a degree,
ummm... yeah.. it wqas bad... whenever the DJ dude tried 2 mixin a new
song, he was off like by a second, ya know when that happens & like it
kinda adds this reverbish sound 2 the beat?  Oh yeah.. the DJ who spun
hardcore earlier that night was DJ Uproar if i for to mention...

So after a loooong while, the DJ who spun hardcore earlier went on &
tagged w/ the DJ who was like mondo wrecking... he sorted the mixer, got
levels right... hmm.. i wonder if there was a monitor back behond the
booth?  Anywaze, the mixing did get batter, but i dunno...

So we were still like ther & i was just dancing... oh oh oh.. so the crowd
was like this yooungish crowd & hmmm... i doubt any of them were
junglists.. there was this like Black Leather snobby girl fem Barbie Doll
dress squad there just like strikin' these mondo poses on the dance floor
2 show of their asses 2 the beat.. no really.. they were... anywaze, Queen
Ass Crack of their tribe was this Girl, see they all wore like balck tops
& jean btms.. the leader of their crew (LoL.. I giuess) was wear a leather
black vest top thingie, 2 short IMO, & this short ass jean skirt w/ an
oversized belt.. Hello 2Day.. so yeah.. when she was dancing, moving,
bending over.. her ass crack kinda mooned people, everyone.. oooooh.. so
sad

Anywaze, Queen Ass Crack (w/ no g string even) i dunno man.. OK.. & I'm so
not lying about this.. but she started getting all up on me.. literally..
she kept touching while she swayed 2 the beat, she moved her face
heeeeeeella close 2 mine, I swear i got drunk smelling her breath, Hello
2day.. she even like backed into my croch area w/ her booty & tried 2 make
me freak her... I mean.. by them, the mixing was somewhat better & I was
feelin' the Groove & i just wanted 2 dance by myslef.. but oooh my
goodness, oh my gosh man... this girl wouldnot give up seducing me i guess
& it so was not working... I even started kick stepping 2 get her away
from me.. she tried kick stepping also but almost like fell off her nigh
heel leather boots... but she did reel in this skinny white boy who i
guiess got disgusted w/ her after like a long time.. he fuckin pushed the
corner of her sholder & waked away.. LoL.. this really happend man.. I
would soooo  not make that up!

Ummm.. there wre these 3 MCs who passed the Mic off like alot... it was
kinda lame 'cause they like would MC over each other, there was this 1
Groovy MC outta the bunch of them... MC Brownie.. CooL guy! :)  We chatted
alot actually...

I dunno.. I was getting pissed @ the DJs and didn't  really feel it
anymore, so we left after spending another hour there.. uugghh.. so sad!

The crowd was small.. like seriously.. 12 people if not like 2 or 3 more
than that... yeah.. it was what it was... hmmm.. Hopefully the events i go
2 this weekend will make up 4 this big mondo fuckin ooops night!

Well.. that's it 4 now... I think i'm either goin' ice skating or bowling
2morrow...

It was it fuckin' was 2night!  Hmmm.. i hope i kick it w/ that Brownie
Dude again.. he was really CooL!

Subject: [sfraves] THUMP'O'WEEN II  -  M3, DJ Dragonfly, Logic Bomb, DJ Anti, Penta + more...Only 3

So we’ve been doing Trance events for 6+ years now and I can’t say that I’ve 
been more pleased with a line-up in the main room as I am with what we’ve 
got coming up on Friday for Thump’O’Ween II.  As many of you will recall 
from last years Thump’O’Ween, the energy and costumes and décor were 
supremely sublime and we’re looking forward to another rocker this year too.

And don’t me wrong – Hallucinogen, Penta, Sphongle were amazing, but the 
direction and journey of the main room was a bit all over the place.  This 
year, come early and stay late, and the journey we’ll be taken on cannot be 
beat in the world of trance, imho.

10-11:30 – dob (eggbeats) <--- chunk’n’funk’n it out to get things started – 
one of the few DJs that really understands how to start a room and set the 
tone.  Nice to have you back at (((thump))) Bry.  ;)


11:30-2 – DJ Anti (spiral trax) <----- We are so excited to have Anti 
back!!!  He’s been fighting the good fight all over the world representing 
the harder edge hypnotic psy-progressive sound to some of the giants of the 
house and progressive world.  Anti’s previous sets at our past (((thump))) 
events have been legendary – truly – and his set is sure to be slamming, 
deep, bouncy and fun.  Sooooooo stoked for this.


2-3:30 – LOGIC BOMB!!!  (tip world, Sweden)  <----  What can I say?  It has 
been over 3 years since Logic Bomb have played SF – an appendicitis 
prevented them from being at our Solstice outdoor in 2003 – and SF has been 
waiting and we are salivating for this set.  As many have said to me since 
we announced this, “Logic Bomb is…the bomb!”  Pumping bass with complex 
Goa-esque melodies – look out beloooooooow.


3:30-?  -- PENTA (auraquake – Russia – SF)  <----- Next level – open your 
mind super Nu-Full-on no holes barred reach for the sky uber-trance.  Nikita 
is back and just as he did last year, his set will drag the entire party 
into another dimension.


I’ve loved creating some great line-ups for our parties over the years and 
this one has come together as one of the best.  I’ll be planted on the sweet 
spot all night.  See u there.  :)


We’ve also got Haunted HOUSE from:  M3, TRACY, JT, TASHO


+


BREAKS from: FIDDLER, Jocelyn and guests

+

CHILLOUT from:  DJ DRAGONFLY, WATERJUICE, REDSTICKMAN and Peek

550 Barneveld, San Francisco

$20

Prizes for best, scariest, and strangest costumes.  Consolation prizes for 
worst and dumbest costumes.

http://www.thumpradio.com

>>> someone who has spent more than a decade
>> interpreting
>>> his life experiences into music, David Alvarado

>>> mastered the art of creating music that truly
>> touches
>>> peoples souls, not only here in the U.S., but
>> around
>>> the world. He uses every sound, every image that
>> comes
>>> in to his life as his inspiration to make music
>> that
>>> evokes the spirit of an underground culture of
>> music
>>> that has existed for the last century.
>>> While growing up in Los Angeles David forged an
>>> appreciation for music that was quickly being
>> changed
>>> by technology. His early experimentation lead him
>> to
>>> produce the "Las Americas Project", a single that
>>> captured the attention of Plus8 records Richie
>> Hawtin
>>> and John Acquaviva, who at the time were in the
>>> process of developing a new house imprint by the
>> name
>>> of Definitive Records. Through this relationship
>> David
>>> was introduced to other up in coming artist's and
>>> labels such as the Toronto based Stickman Records
>> and
>>> Philadelphia DJ Josh Wink. His experience and
>> exposure
>>> to the growing house music community led him to
>> begin
>>> his own imprint, Bomb Records, which further
>>> contributed to helping David expand his audience
>> and
>>> develop his signature sound as an artist. Bomb
>> Records
>>> not only was the vehicle by which David increased
>> his
>>> global audience, but also featured then up and
>> coming
>>> artists Kenneth Grahm, Eddie Amador, and Derrick
>>> Carter.
>>> The foresight that David exhibited with his own
>>> production and the selections for his label
>> quickly
>>> sparked international interest and created a tour
>>> schedule that grew increasingly demanding. Despite
>> his
>>> hectic travels David has remained focused in the
>>> studio and completed an impressive body of work
>> for
>>> his own label, and for highly respected labels
>>> including Ovum, Ultra, Strictly Rhythm, Yoshi
>> Toshi,
>>> Plastic City, and Peace Frog. In addition to his
>> work
>>> as an artist he has created a catalog of highly
>>> acclaimed mix CDs for Chicago's Guidance Records,
>>> Madrid's Deep Sessions Vol. 2 and United DJs of
>>> America Vol. 15. All of which are now considered
>>> classics in there own right.
>>> This amazing producer whose tracks have been
>> described
>>> as having the longest shelf life of any releases a
>>> record shop could carry is still hard at work
>>> capturing the hearts and souls of a new generation
>> of
>>> electronic music fans. He has also developed a new
>>> record label Sunchildren which brings an amazingly
>>> beautiful, sexier twist to the already established
>>> West Coast house sound. David asserts that the
>> label
>>> will incorporate eclectic Latin, Brazilian, and
>>> African elements to bring a much welcomed warmth &
>>> sensuality to the genre. If this new angle proves
>> to
>>> be as influential as his previous projects it will
>> no
>>> doubt keep West Coast House and David Alvarado
>> right

>> house

IRS Newswire


IR-2005-124

October 25, 2005
IRS Seeks Applications for TE/GE Advisory Committee
=A0
WASHINGTON - The Internal Revenue Service is seeking applications for =
vacancies on the Advisory Committee on Tax Exempt and Government =
Entities (ACT). The committee provides a venue for public input into =
critical tax administration areas.=20
Vacancies exist in the following customer segments:
* Employee Plans - two vacancies,=20
* Exempt Organizations - two vacancies,=20
* Federal, State and Local Governments - one vacancy,=20
* Tax Exempt Bonds - one vacancy, and=20
* Indian Tribal Governments - two vacancies..=20
The ACT is an organized public forum for the IRS and representatives who =
deal with employee plans, exempt organizations, tax-exempt bonds, and =
federal, state, local and Indian tribal governments. The ACT allows IRS =
to receive regular input on administrative policy and procedures of the =
Tax Exempt and Government Entities Division.
Members are appointed by the secretary of the Treasury and serve =
two-year terms, beginning in May 2006. Applications can be made by =
letter or by completing an application form, available on the IRS Web =
site. In either case, applications should reflect the proposed member's =
qualifications. A notice published in the Federal Register dated October =
25, 2005, contains more details about the ACT and the application =
process.
Applications will be accepted through November 25, 2005.

Applications should be sent to Steven Pyrek, TE/GE Communications and =
Liaison Director, Internal Revenue Service, 1111 Constitution Ave. NW - =
SE:T:CL Penn Bldg, Washington, D.C. 20224, or by fax to 202-283-9956 =
(not a toll-free number).

Subject: [sfraves] SRR: Speaker repair advice?

so i bought some speakers off Craigslist recently.  in the past, i've
had awesome luck and have two Cerwin Vega subs and two Yamaha tops.

got home it appears that one speaker is broken.

sound coming out is very muffled and low, no matter how much juice i
pump through it.

other speaker is fine.

any suggestions as to where to take this bad boy?  any "do it
yourself" tips to diagnose the problem?

Scott Henry & more.

Subject: [sfraves] OUTRAGE returns: a Jungle Club in Essex I just came from

OK.. so the drive from Rochester to Essex is like looooooong.. think SF to
Sac distance... the place they have OUTRAGE: returns is this pub called
Molly Malone's & it wqs by this train station... so we get outta the car,
there's this couple fist fighting @ the train station... LoL.. Helllo
2Day... oh yeah... we lso got lost on this country road.. oh my gosh man..
i gotta tell y'all, the buildings & everything.. the old skool arcutecture
is just Awesome...

Anywze, got 2 the pub, then like well.. they were like hella charging us "
the door, but we were on GL 'cause my Homie Balistik did the sound... so
we get in... OK.. So Dope!  Ummm.. like it was Awesome.. OK.. strait
away.. i felt the vibe.. it was reeeeeally thick!  Every1 there was hella
fuckin' into the music.. the whole place was jumpin' w/ this Awesome
fuckin' energy.. Loved it!

The 1st DJ who we saw when we got in was spinning this hard dubby shit..
Loved it!!  Balistik bought me & Carol a drink & we had this yelling
conversation.. LoL.. Actaully it was Dope... 'cause Balistik & I have
known each other like online homies 4 like the past 2 years i guess... So
yeah.. LoL.. it was kinda surreal meating him & we had hella good chats
thoughout the night...

The 2nd DJ.. DJ Unix.. played some wicked shit.. he mixed w/ a deck &
CDJ.. so i'm assuming he played alota OG produced shit... OH My Gosh man..
danced hella hard 2 his set!  Yum!  Again.. all hard dubby stuff & some
liquid too!

The 3rd DJ was some1 I met online like a few nights ago when her &
Balistik were tagging on dnbradio.com.. her name#s NETAFEX.. oh ,y gosh..
so Sweet & when she spun... ooh man... her style is like Seraphim.. all
hard, evil shit dubby stuff.. it was Dope!!

Yeah man.. there was apoint when i ws dancing & this Dude who looked
exactly like Mobber was like arguing w/ another dude 7 he was ready 2 box
& hella drunk.. anywaze.. the only way that the fight didn't happen was
'cause his girlfriend, or maybe girl he  met @ the bar, kept kssing him &
holding his head... it was to far from that happening when they started
goin' so hardcore @ it... & I saw hands & hips moving where they shouldn't
be moving in a public place...

OH yeah.. since i still got a stash of SFLNC @Dancing's Not A Crime@
stickers... I gave some out ther & the peopel really liked them!!! LoL...
ummm.. NETAFEX put 1 on her Record Case like right away!!

Man.. OK... this is the start of a Really Fuckin' Awesome Weekend!  Good
Shit man!

Hope y'all doing Groovy " home!!  Whoever goes 2 OW 2morrow night... grab
hella floor 4 me & tear it up!!!  YAY!!!

Friday, October 28, 2005 ** Bumpin Pumkin #1 **

Just when you thought is was safe...From the creators of ETD POPSICLE, ETD 
LOVE and The Love Parade AFTER PARTY, SKILLS screams back for another 
spook-tacular-frightfully fun evening of things that go bump in the night.

SKILLS presents ********BUMPKIN PUMKIN 1 & 2********* 8 Year Anniversary!

FRIDAY, OCTOBER 28th and SATURDAY, OCTOBER 29th 2005 Celebrating the 
International CD Album Release by MARS titled ALIENAIDED on Frequency 8 
Records


9PM-4AM

Friday, October 28th

KYAU VS ALBERT - KyauvsAlbert.de//Euphonic Records - Germany PULSER - 
djPulser.com//A State of Trance - United Kingdom ROBERT NICKSON - 
RobertNickson.nl//A State of Trance - Holland DEEP VOICES - 
DeepVoicesMusic.com//Adjusted//NOYS - Germany/SF MARS - Frequency8.com - 
SF WEIRD PSYANTS - SKILLS Recordings - SF ANGEL & ROHAN - SKILLS DJ 
Workshop - SF




BUMPKIN PUMKIN 1 & 2 are both 100% fully permitted & secured, guaranteeing 
ghostly frights on this Halloween night. Located at TERRA SF 511 Harrison 
Street @ 1st - San Francisco, CA 94105


~U7 hours of monsters, mayhem and madness that, once again, must be seen 
to be believed. ~UHosted by Team Tronic and the Sexy SKILLS Sirens ~UAll 
Responsible gravers 18 and over are velcome. ~ULimited 1000 person 
capacity for each night ~UOUT DOOR VENDOR VILLAGE (Under cover of 
darkness) - Where ghosts whisper, spiders dance and witches laughter can 
be heard. ~U FULL FOOD CONCESSONS. *Vegetarian friendly. ~UFull bar for 
the 21 and up ~UDiscover this unique experience - Dress up in scary and 
fun-filled costumes...if you dare! ~UFast & Friendly Security. ~ULots of 
fun give-a-ways ~UFor up-to-date info log onto WWW.SKILLSDJ.COM


Presale tickets go on sale October 1st for both events. (Each event sold 
separately. One ticket per event.) Tickets will start at $25 
(un-boo-lievable). When those run out tickets will be $30, and finally 
$40.

EACH NIGHT SOLD SEPARATELEY.

Experince the height of fright: Purchase VIM (Verry Important Monster) 
presale tickets for only $60. A terror-ific deal! VIM includes line 
privledge. Ins and outs. Access to VIP/Artists area. Back stage all 
access. Lots of treats & goodies. Full Food and beverage garden.s

TRICK OR TREAT! Go for the treat and avoid being tricked by purchasing a 
fake ticket. Only buy from authorized presale ticket outlets or buy 
onlline @ groovetickets.com.

AUTHORIZED PRESALE TICKET OUTLETS:

ONLINE :: GrooveTickets.com PHONE // 877.714.1662

BERKELEY :: Skills DJ Workshop 2566A Telegraph Ave. // 510.704.9876

SAN FRANCISCO :: Anubis Warpus 1525 Haight St. // 415.431.2218

SAN JOSE :: Solid Grooves 2271 THE ALAMEDA // 408.248.6399

SAN BRUNO :: Ultra Soundz 482 San Mateo Ave. // 650.871.4170

SACRAMENTO :: Channelz 2371 Arden Way // 916.641.8808

CONCORD :: Generation Rock 820 Mt. Diablo St. // 925.682.9042



Once again, please continue to respect the venue so that others may dance 
there in the future. Drink lots of water, tell a friend! If you have it, 
bring extra cash. An eclectic assortment of vendors will be selling a wide 
variety of fun stuff.


Fiendishly Fun Facts: YES! You will be safe because NO DRUGS or weapons of 
any kind will be allowed. A no tolerance policy will be in effect! YES! 
Concession stands will be available inside the event so you won't have to 
bring outside food or beverage. YES! We will be able to use this venue 
again because there will be no pens or markers allowed. Respect the venue! 
YES! You will be allowed to bring in both cameras and video cameras so 
that you won't forget a Super Duper Moment! YES! There will be a large 
outdoor area so that you don't have to smoke inside the event. YES! You 
will win lots of fang-tastic stuff if you dress up in costume.

LIGHTING BY LUMATECH LASERS BY UV99 SOUND BY JK

Stay Connected 510.869.4601 415.437.4460 WWW.SKILLSDJ.COM

BUMPKIN PUMKIN 1 & 2 are both drug free events. Let the music take you 
higher.

Interested in joining the promotion team? Email us at 
promo@skillsdjworkshop.com Want to set up a booth and vend? Email us at 
vend@skillsdjworkshop.com


http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf/calendar2/events/view?identifier=2279 
San Francisco California, USA

San Francisco - downtown California, USA

Wednesday, November 2, 2005 ** Free Scratch and Akai MPC Beat Dropping 
Session II **

Norcal DJ and Music Production Academy & B-Side Records & Distortion 2 
Static present: Free Scratch and Akai MPC Beat Dropping Session II 
Wednesday November 2nd 7:30-9:30pm Hosted by Yun Lee What is the Akai MPC? 
Invented by Roger Linn of LinnDrum fame, the Akai MPC is arguably the most 
powerful piece of beat making hardware on the market.  The MPC has been a 
favorite amongst many of today~Rs top producers including Dr. Dre, Pete 
Rock, The RZA, LTJ Bukem, Madlib (Stones Throw), and many other artists 
spanning from every style and genre.  The MPC has become a standard piece 
of equipment in all categories of electronic music.  It is one of the only 
machines that combine a sampler, drum machine, and sequencer into one 
powerful package.  Scratch session info: Got skills? Come to showcase, 
learn, or just listen. Free scratch session held from 8 to 9:30 at the 
LAB. Original music will be provided by the MPC session. Format is listed 
below. · Total Time: 1.5 hours · Switch every 8 bars · Setups provided (2 
turntables and a mixer) · Bring: Your own vinyl, needles and headphones 
MPC Session info: Got beats? Come to showcase, learn, or just listen. Free 
MPC session will be held from 8-9:30 at the LAB. Scratch artists will 
perform over your beats so bring tracks in tempos of 90BPM, 100BPM, and 
110BPM so we can play continuously. You can bring pre-made sequences and 
songs or just jam live. · Total Time: 1.5 hours · Switch every 64 bars · 
Speakers, cables and PA provided · Bring: MPC, headphones, original music 
Only at norcalDJMPA 600 Townsend Street Suite 190W San Francisco, 
California 94103 Call 415.255.8789 for details or to be let in the 
building after 8:00pm



http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf/calendar2/events/view?identifier=2324

  On Sat Nov 5, at Spin THIS! - Dark forces will be uniting! Mistress of

http://www.regenerator.net/

your freaky best to raise your chances of winning!

We will be celebrating the close of Samhain and honoring the Day of the 
Dead.  There will be an enchanted ritual by Coven Fire Troupe and an alter 
dedicated to our ancestors.  Please feel free to bring your own offerings! 
Expect treats and decor a bit on the spookier side.  Mwahaha!

sideshow performers and vjs to delight your visual senses!

-------------------------------------------------
  Administrative Notes 
-------------------------------------------------

THE SFRaves.org Calendar is sent via email every week.

To subscribe to the list, send a message to:
sfraves-calendar-subscribe@hyperreal.org

To remove your address from the list, send a message to:
sfraves-calendar-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org

Send mail to the following for info and FAQ for this list:
sfraves-calendar-info@hyperreal.org or sfraves-calendar-faq@hyperreal.org

If you have events to add to the SFRaves calendar, please publish them by
Friday @ Noon to be included in the SFR Calendar Weekly Edition Mailing.

SFRaves is a not for profit entity serving the Bay Area & all forms of
electronic music for 13 years.

Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

I'm sorry, but as someone who has lived with both parents and step parents being major alcoholics and drug addicts I have to respond to your condescending tone. It is because of AA and NA that my step father is sober today and that I am able to have a wonderful positive relationship with him. AA does not profess to "cure" you. It does however encourage you to discuss your reasons and problems in addiction and to face your own bullshit. There really isn't anyone in there that thinks they have the answer...they all are addicts and trying to help eachother. It's admitting that you are human and can have a substance dependency. Addiction is not a matter of you not having enough will power and there are plenty of atheists in the program. It doesn't work for everyone and there are breakthrough drugs coming around to help addiction but those are years into the future. My friend recently went into AA and he said it was more of a spiritual awakening than he had ever experienced in his life
 quite the opposite of "giving up his spiritual quest." I don't know if you've ever been on the verge of total addiction and losing everything important to you but I think at that point you might consider surrendering to a higher power. AA does not work for everyone but I would encourage anyone who is battling addiction to at least try it and if that doesn't work seek other help. Whatever works for you!

Sean G <rationalhatter@gmail.com> wrote:Lots of luck with this.
A close friend of mine is in NA atm (as per the terms of his parole
agreement...) and it scares the shit out of me. I really hope he'll take the
next step and not use AA as his new dependency. :/ People don't seem to
realize that change and improvement come from within, not from any number of
substances or support groups. The whole 'surrender to a higher power' thing
seems counterintuitive to all genuine efforts at self-improvement.

Kind of like giving up your spiritual quest and just becoming a seventh day
adventist because 'it works'.

im not talking down here - just some things to mull over. I'm sure AA can be
a really helpful tool... as long as you use it as a tool, not perceive it as
a cure.

Sean
