Subject: Re: [sfraves] AA meetings?

-----Original Message-----

There are secular alternatives to AA.  One that I've heard good 
things about is LifeRing.  There are many meeting opportunities 
available in the Bay Area:  http://www.unhooked.com/meetings/meetings.html#1


AA doesn't support any creed/religion/belief system over others.  it's *already* secular.

"surrendering to god or a higher power" is only part of it.  the rest of the sentence is "god - as you understand and relate to him/her/it"

My "god" is Truth.  Truth is what IS.  the Tao.  The Universe.  No old grey dude in the sky sitting on a throne. I look around me and see things as they ARE, and realize that when i'm not living in that reality-tunnel (part of which is: i should never ever drink alcohol), i am not living according to the Tao, or god's wishes, or however you want to think of it.  i lose every time.  we all know that fighting the Universe is a losing proposition, but there's some irrational draw that intoxicants can have over you.

which brings me to a point you brought up, Sean.  surrendering is really the only key to winning.  it took me a long time to figure this one out, because i consider myself a pretty bright guy who can usually solve problems with little to no trouble.  this makes me a GREAT architect and designer, but a terrible drunk. :-)

the reason why is this: THERE IS NO RATIONAL EXPLANATION FOR AN ADDICTION.  you try and try to think your way around it, trying to outsmart it or change up your habits or where you hang out, or who you hang out with, but it's impossible, because your addiction isn't playing by the rules of thought and rational behavior.  i thought that surrendering meant that i was giving up, and i wasn't capable of solving this problem on my own.  it was a pretty huge blow to my (quite substantial) ego to find out that, yeah, i CAN'T do it on my own.  kind of a mind fuck, really.

so without the 12 steps, which are really a personal method to recovering from an addiction, the best way i can summarize my path to sobriety is:

- First, acknowlege the Reality I live in. (this includes my body's constitution which makes me a psychotic with alcohol.)
- Figure out what i'm supposed to be doing. This can be any scale - from major life plans right down to being constantly aware of how my actions affect others.
- Once i've figured out what i'm supposed to be doing, GET TO WORK. make it happen.

i find that if i stay on my Right Path - the one that the Tao / Universe has in store for me - i am a much stronger person, and alcohol is no longer able to creep in and take me down.  This has a great side-benefit of constant self-improvement and learning and growing. Stay on the Path, philip. :-)

it's been a very enlightening trip thus far, and i'm still learning, but the real learning comes in teaching someone else. so, to that end, i would feel honored and blessed to talk more with anyone who might have any questions.... so please shoot me an email or call me at 415.255.9776 if you wanna chat.

philip

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I think it is simple...AA, NA, kwanza, kaballah, buddhism....
It is a belief system, different ways of life work for different people.  I 
am here to find out if aa or na works for me.  I was sober 3& 1/2 months and 
relapsed and this is where I stand now....Does drinking 24/7 provide my life 
with ANY good whatsoever?  Does the occasional line cause me to be in a 
space of certainty, so I can create the rest of my life making wise 
decisions?
Nope, and it took me over 11 years to figure this out, for me, myself.  
These are my issues, my choices.  Other people have shared similar thoughts/ 
feelings because they were involved with it as a child, now or maybe it has 
not happenned.  BUT Alcoholism is a serious thing, I am affected, I hate 
saying that i am an addict, so sometimes I don't when I go to a meeting.  I 
think anybody who has any nerve or God given right to judge anyone on this 
list needs to attend a few meetings first, or meet a loved one whom you know 
WILL die because of poor decision making, turned habit, turned "disease"
Trust me, I am the ultimate "overanalyzer" and I have thought these things 
over and over again....
I am not perfect, nor is anyone else, God did not intend that to be the case 
for anyone, especially Richard simmons.
I brought this topic up because I am in need of education, something new to 
teach me so I can move forward and bring some peace into my life.  Does 
anyone want to argue with that?  I am sure there will be one person at 
least.  I also brought this up because it is very relevant in the culture in 
which we live.  Alcohol is everywhere. People abuse it all the time, this 
goes for so many things...addiction is a mutherfucker.
I am not telling you to think this way or that.  I would love it if people 
were a bit more open to the fact that there are lots of people out there who 
live differently...and have different problems.  Why judge them when you can 
help just by being open to new conversation or by offering new 
ideas.......which brings me back to my origonal question...
"Does anyone know of any good AA meetings in SF?"
grr.
Danny

>From: Amber Leahey <princess_leahey@yahoo.com>

>I'm sorry, but as someone who has lived with both parents and step parents 
>being major alcoholics and drug addicts I have to respond to your 
>condescending tone. It is because of AA and NA that my step father is sober 
>today and that I am able to have a wonderful positive relationship with 
>him. AA does not profess to "cure" you. It does however encourage you to 
>discuss your reasons and problems in addiction and to face your own 
>bullshit. There really isn't anyone in there that thinks they have the 
>answer...they all are addicts and trying to help eachother. It's admitting 
>that you are human and can have a substance dependency. Addiction is not a 
>matter of you not having enough will power and there are plenty of atheists 
>in the program. It doesn't work for everyone and there are breakthrough 
>drugs coming around to help addiction but those are years into the future. 
>My friend recently went into AA and he said it was more of a spiritual 
>awakening than he had ever experienced in his life
>  quite the opposite of "giving up his spiritual quest." I don't know if 
>you've ever been on the verge of total addiction and losing everything 
>important to you but I think at that point you might consider surrendering 
>to a higher power. AA does not work for everyone but I would encourage 
>anyone who is battling addiction to at least try it and if that doesn't 
>work seek other help. Whatever works for you!
>

sickness. The beats were throbbing and funky, the vibe was hypnotic, they 
really took the crowd on a journey. On top of that, they're suuuuper nice 
folks, and were a pleasure to get to hang out with. Thanks again to OW crew 
for letting me pick up Ben & Jack before the gig - I had a great time 
conversating with them.

DJ Zeph - in both his solo set and the work he did w/ Azeem, he blew my 
mind. On par with someone like Z-Trip or A-Skillz, this guy has immense 
talent and is sure to go far. I got to kick it him a bit after his solo set, 
and he's a really nice guy on top of all that talent.

Azeem - this guy NEVER ceases to amaze me with how talented he is. His flows 
are impeccable, his rhymes are tight and intelligent. I for one am thankful 
I keep getting to see him in such an intimate setting as OW is. Some day 
this guy is gonna blow up and become huge, and I for one am all for it.

Fingermonsters - what can I say about our local SFRavers? AMAZING!! I was 
seriously impressed with the bangin' beats these 3 fuckers unleashed 
Saturday night. They looked like they were really having fun with the set 
too, and it came across in the tunes. As far as I'm concerned, they can play 
at every party I go to for the next few years, and I'll be a happy camper!

Forest Green & Mochipet - well hot damn. Techno & Electro served up on a 
silver platter, thick and chunky the way it should be. I 
reaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaly dug their set.

Praxis & DJ Yap - even though they played in different rooms at diff. times, 
I'm listing em together, cuz they both played booming sets, and I didn't 
catch either one's full set. Nevertheless, I am always impressed by them, 
and Saturday night was no exception. BOH!

I'm not sure who all caught myself and Bam's set - but I feel like we warmed 
things up proper. People kept coming up to me all night long saying how much 
fun they had during our set, so we musta been doing something right. Thanks 
to OW for letting us do our thing!!!

Also - big ups to Terry & Kevin from Viberation - the visuals were sick as 
usual!

(and it was great to see you again Ryan!!!! Welcome back!)

The rest of the night is a bit of a blur. I was running around connecting w/ 
people I know, meeting new folks, and being a Meat Beat Manifesto fanboy 
every chance I got. I actually hung out with them for quite some time, and 
had quite a few fun conversations with them all. Great bunch of folks. I 
still can't believe I got to see them in my friend's living room. Hehe.

Otherworld - how do you guys keep outdoing yourselves???? Saturday was 
seriously insane, and I thank all you of sincerely for your intense efforts. 
The party was 110% perfect. I couldn't have asked for a more fun Halloween, 
and all myfriends that came in from out of town had a blast!!!

Still afterglowing...
Marc(O)

Subject: [sfraves] AA

What a pleasant surprise to hear an alcoholism topic on a raves list.  
I drank heavily for 30 years and then stopped cold when my father died. 
  Apparently there was a connection.   88*D

I like going to AA meetings, because it's fun to be around people who 
are grappling with life in a positive way and often making substantial 
progress with their issues.  I am an alcoholic, and now I have no 
trouble saying I am an alcoholic.  My hardest issue around that was 
that I used to believe that I hadn't bottomed out badly enough to be 
worthy of the name "alcoholic."  I go play cards sometimes at an AA 
watering hole, the Castro Country Club, near 18th and Hartford.  It's 
my favorite place in the Castro to sit on a stoop and watch hot numbers 
walk by.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP Halo this wednesday @ the Blue MOnkey - for free!

This November is going to be hot! Hot in November you
say? 
Karma at The Blue Monkey is heating things up, just
look at the flier!

http://www.mjgamez.com/karma/images/NovFront_web.jpg
http://www.mjgamez.com/karma/images/NovBack_web.jpg

This Wednesday! Halo Varga! FOR FREE!!!
Happy Hour from 9pm to 11pm features HYPNOTIQ DRINK
SPECIALS & $5 LONG ISLANDS!
Karma Wednesdays and The Blue Monkey Lounge are proud
to present, HALO!

Oh and here's the clincher.. ..It's FREE! No cover, no
door charge, no hidden fees.
So you really have no excuse to miss this one..The
Blue Monkey Lounge is located at 1 E. San Fernando St.
in Downtown San Jose and features some of the tastiest
Tacos on the planet. See you on the dancefloor!
BIOGRAPHY

When you step inside the funky, soul-flavored house
built by Brian Varga (aka Halo), get ready to be
moved. This Chicago bred, House-fed DJ has been
wreckin decks everywhere from Japan to Korea, Brazil,
Australia, Israel, Africa, Turkey, and back to North
America, currently capturing the scene in Southern
California. He’s been groovin London’s Fabric now for
four years as a bi-monthly resident, and he’s no
stranger to gracing stages with the most infamous
faces in electronic culture. Now, with a successful
solo production career, a new album and a national
tour in the making, Halo’s house has the whole block
rockin. 

Inspiration was always close to home for Halo; born in
Chicago of 1974, he was introduced to house music in
the city most notorious for constructing it. He
recalls attending underground loft parties and
witnessing such visionaries as Gene Hunt,Larry
Heard,Diz, DJ Frique, Glenn Underground, Frankie
Knuckles, Boo Williams and countless others who
enticed his developing passion for Djing. Taking to
the decks at a mere 13 years of age, Halo was quick to
create alliances with hometown DJ’s and rapidly began
releasing solo and joint projects on Chicago’s Moody
Recordings.   

As the Midwestern dance scene grew stale, Halo craved
to move somewhere that had a fresh, untapped scene.
Halo fell in love with San Diego and relocated,
bringing his chicago roots out west with former friend
Hipp-e under the group name H-Foundation. Anxious to
do more than just spin records, Halo launched his own
Bluem Recordings in 2001, which celebrates almost
twenty releases from such legendary producers as DJ
Deep, Frank Rogers, Fresh & Low, Andre Harris, Jay-J,
Souldoubt and Charles Webster.   

Halo also recorded for a number of premium house
labels including Large, Seasons, Nordic Trax, NRK, Om
and Yoshitoshi and has remixed tracks by Afromystik,
Sumo, Heather, Nigel Hayes, Morgan Page and many more.
Selections from his discography appear on such high
profile compilations as Mark Farina’s Connect, Ben
Watt and Jay Hannan’s Lazy Dog Volume 1, Jay-J’s and
Miguel Migs’ In the House and Kaskade’s Soundtrack to
the Soul. Motivated by the success stories behind
Masters at Work, Blaze, Kerri Chandler and DJ Deep,
Halo is focused on continuous producing and the
building of powerful relationships for future
projects.   

Behind the decks, Halo remains among the most
respected in the industry and continues to assert that
Djing is his first passion. His productions, which
reside in the record boxes of the world’s top
tastemakers, are equally valued. He’s traveled around
the world spreading his deep, melodic vibes, and he’s
played alongside some of the best: Louie Vega, Mark
Farina, and Marques Wyatt, to name a few. His next-up
projects include collaborations with Marlon D., Alix
Alvarez, Mr. V and more studio work for his City Deep
Music label. Bottom line: Halo’s house is definitely
where the heart is. 

For more on Halo, visit www.bluemrecordings.com or
www.siestamusic.com
KARMA is held every Wednesday night and features
Downtempo, Deep Dub, SF House and Chicago House.

With your weekly residants

Mike Slim (Karma/BlueMonkey)
Gabriel Black (Karma/Sierra Recordings)

The Blue Monkey is located at 1 E San Fernando Street,
SJ
21+ and over
9PM to CLOSE.</center>

I agree. This party rocked. It was so nice seeing everyone again, it's been
a long time since i've been out in force. The music was awesome. It was so
fucking rad to see meat beat up close like that. They never cease to amaze
me, nor does Otherworld. You totally out did yourselves this year.
 The only drawback to that night was the fact that my car got broken into
Stereo and Ipod were stolen. It was just a matter of time i suppose, with
all the times i've parked out there for parties (attending and doing sound)
it was bound to happen sooner or later. Kinda ruined my night from that
point on and ended up leaving a little earlier than i would have liked just
because i couldn't seem to cheer back up after that.
 All in all though it was an amazing night, i wish every night could be as
magical as that.
 Major Props to Otherworld, Meat Beat, Bam, Marco, Praxis, Terry, Kevin and
everyone else involved in bringing it all together.
 --
Chester Copperpot

"Goonies never say die!"
"Meth Monsters are my Anti-Drug"
"I feel like I'm taking crazy pills"

 On 10/31/05, Van Mundegaarde <electrofunk138@hotmail.com> wrote:
>
> Well goooooooooooood-damn!
>
> Saturday night has to go down as one of the most fun nights I have ever
> had.
> The vibe was amazing, the talent was off the hook, and the party was epic=
.
>
> Let's start off with the highlight - Meat Beat Manifesto. Fucking AMAZING
> show. Talk about total auditory and visual immersion. Some of the things
> they did simply blew my mind - especially all the video scratching, pure
> sickness. The beats were throbbing and funky, the vibe was hypnotic, they
> really took the crowd on a journey. On top of that, they're suuuuper nice
> folks, and were a pleasure to get to hang out with. Thanks again to OW
> crew
> for letting me pick up Ben & Jack before the gig - I had a great time
> conversating with them.
>
> DJ Zeph - in both his solo set and the work he did w/ Azeem, he blew my
> mind. On par with someone like Z-Trip or A-Skillz, this guy has immense
> talent and is sure to go far. I got to kick it him a bit after his solo
> set,
> and he's a really nice guy on top of all that talent.
>
> Azeem - this guy NEVER ceases to amaze me with how talented he is. His
> flows
> are impeccable, his rhymes are tight and intelligent. I for one am
> thankful
> I keep getting to see him in such an intimate setting as OW is. Some day
> this guy is gonna blow up and become huge, and I for one am all for it.
>
> Fingermonsters - what can I say about our local SFRavers? AMAZING!! I was
> seriously impressed with the bangin' beats these 3 fuckers unleashed
> Saturday night. They looked like they were really having fun with the set
> too, and it came across in the tunes. As far as I'm concerned, they can
> play
> at every party I go to for the next few years, and I'll be a happy camper=
!
>
> Forest Green & Mochipet - well hot damn. Techno & Electro served up on a
> silver platter, thick and chunky the way it should be. I
> reaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaly dug their set.
>
> Praxis & DJ Yap - even though they played in different rooms at diff.
> times,
> I'm listing em together, cuz they both played booming sets, and I didn't
> catch either one's full set. Nevertheless, I am always impressed by them,
> and Saturday night was no exception. BOH!
>
> I'm not sure who all caught myself and Bam's set - but I feel like we
> warmed
> things up proper. People kept coming up to me all night long saying how
> much
> fun they had during our set, so we musta been doing something right.
> Thanks
> to OW for letting us do our thing!!!
>
> Also - big ups to Terry & Kevin from Viberation - the visuals were sick a=
s
> usual!
>
> (and it was great to see you again Ryan!!!! Welcome back!)
>
> The rest of the night is a bit of a blur. I was running around connecting
> w/
> people I know, meeting new folks, and being a Meat Beat Manifesto fanboy
> every chance I got. I actually hung out with them for quite some time, an=
d
> had quite a few fun conversations with them all. Great bunch of folks. I
> still can't believe I got to see them in my friend's living room. Hehe.
>
> Otherworld - how do you guys keep outdoing yourselves???? Saturday was
> seriously insane, and I thank all you of sincerely for your intense
> efforts.

> Halloween,

On Oct 31, 2005, at 10:24 AM, sideshow wrote:

> I couldn't possibly disagree any more. I'm glad everyone else had fun
> though. I'm not quite sure how they seem to attract so many people  
> that do
> not believe in bathing. This was my first and last other world  
> event. I only
> stayed four about 15 min and would of asked for my cash back, but  
> that is
> just bad form.


i'm wondering a couple things:

   - exactly WHICH 15 minutes were you there for?  really, if you  
were only there that long, you didn't give it a chance, now did you?

   - could your post be a set-up / red herring for future events that  
might conflict with DTS/HCFTP parties?  just a thought that crossed  
my mind.

   - what makes a good party for you?

i've been to a couple DTS/HCFTP parties that had a lack of  
functioning bathrooms (and TP), pushy "security", and draconian door  
policies, not to mention a lack of AIR and WATER *, and you know  
what?  i stayed for the duration of the event to suss it out.. and to  
help.  i tried to help out by un-clogging sinks, re-stocking TP, and  
opening windows and re-directing fans to improve the air flow in the  
space.  and i did all this without posting nasty emails about your  
events, though the urge to do so was tempting.

i would recommend that the next time you're at an event where  
something isn't going right, or could be better, step up and do  
something about it.  complaining doesn't count.   i wish i could  
offer a solution to the un-washed raver issue, but i'm coming up  
short there. :-)

the people involved in throwing this Halloween event put an insane  
amount of work into it, and that production level is rarely matched  
in the underground scene.  how many sound crews will fly the speaker  
cabinets just for increased sound quality?  free food and water?  
THREE shuttle vans (so that nobody had to wait outside in the cold  
for more than a minute or so) to take you to and from a safe place to  
park your car?  SIX FUCKING ROOMS of music for $15?  i mean, if you  
didn't notice these "details" about the party, you really should pay  
better attention next time.  and again, i'd really like to know what  
your idea of a good party is.

-philip-


* for those who might not know - AIR and WATER are basic survival  
needs for mammalian life forms. this includes ravers, no matter how  
stinky they may be.

It just wasn't my type of event. I would hardly call what I wrote to be
considered nasty. The only mean thing I said was in reference to the smell
in the place. It was obvious there was a serious lack of deodorant being
used in that place. The crew is not in control of that, I just choose not t=
o
be in a place that I feel the urge to vomit. I also don't like to leave my
car in shady neighbor hoods. My personal belongings are more important to m=
e
that a party.

Some events are not for everyone. I personally don't enjoy the type they
throw. They have a good following with people who enjoy their shows every
time they do one. Who cares what I think.

PS Please tell me what show you went to that HCFTP threw that did not have =
a
bath room? And DTS shows are normally $5 to - $10 so if you are complaining
about lack of air, bathrooms and other things I'm sorry. DTS has always
remained true to the idea of keeping the show as affordable as possible. DT=
S
is about the music not that lights and extra BS that would force us to
charge twice as much. We really do our best with what the venue gives us as
far as bath rooms. Come to think of it DTS has only done shows at the crack
house except for mad hatter. And as we all know that venue has two
bathrooms. DTS also threw a completely free day party that cost us almost
$400. So if you feel like we let you down I'm sorry. We try to do what we
can with the money we have. DTS has yet to turn a profit, and has come very
close to breaking even on every show.

--
Nick Sideshow
---------------------------
http://www.hcftp.com
HCFTP/DisturbingTheScene

My car was broken into as well, ipod, cds and sub stolen, and damaged my 
receiver. Same as Mr. Copper, the odds were against me, but it still 
sucks. Parking under a street light, in between a school and church 
doesn't mean anything in Oakland :)

The party was amazing though, good people, good feel and awesome music. 
MBM were unbelievable and one of the best acts I've seen up so close. 
The guys were  down-to-earth and just damn good at what they do. Having 
the Finger Monsters come up right after was just perfect and they laid 
down some sweet tunes.

Cheers to OW, Viberation, and all the audio teams for a perfect Halloween!

- Buzz.

I'm not blaming you guys or saying I could do anything better. I'm just
saying it wasn't my type of show. It just seemed like everyone was on acid
walking around and talking to people that weren't really there. I didn't
really like the music, I didn't know many people there. So when you add all
the things together it makes my social anxiety disorder kick in over drive.
I'm not really up for partying it tight space with no outside area these
days. Sorry for all the drama

Nick

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Thanks to OW for a SLAMMING Halloween!!

Yup!!  Thanks for a great time!

As Marco said, the MBM set was amazing.  The mixing of visuals and audio
(as well as the audio FROM the visuals with the audio of the set) was
off the hook.  (Looping a drum line, or a KEYBOARD line, from some dude
playing in a demo video or concert footage and mixing that audio in.
Damn.  Try that one at home.)

The Fingermonster set was done amazingly.

Forest Green/Mochipet, Praxis: Yum!!

And of course, free water and food definitely help to nourish the raver
body.

As for Sideshow Bob's take on things, he might want to look in to
parties in L.A., as it sounds like that scene is likely more his thing.
Or if he wants a hookup with some promoters in Vegas, he can probably
pursue that and find his kind of vibe there too.  But OW, that was
SF-style.

I started the OW evening off probably freaking Tala out a bit with the
devil/jesus bit (hesitated a bit before getting into the shuttle) and I
ended the OW evening by freaking out a few of the street people I was
talking with for 2 or 3 hours at the 12th st bart station (finally
hopped on the bart around 10.)

P.S. on the MBM era tip:  Whatever happened to Consolidated?


http://www.jcthedj.com

The Universe is Ego

--0-961523799-1130789464=:58817
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

I'm a long time lurker and sometimes poster.  I just had to throw in my .02 about this party......  
 
first off, let me start by saying this was my first otherworld party.  I've heard about their parties for a long time and wanted to check them out, but for one reason or another timing has never worked out right until saturday night.  needless to say I was excited about it and had high expectations.  
 
on the whole, otherworld delivered.  the place looked great.  loved the graveyard setup in the main room.  it was a bit confusing to navigate the hallways (in fact I think I missed one of the music areas entirely because I couldn't find it).  maybe next time some signs pointing the way to the different rooms would help.  or bigger signs if there were signs posted.  seems like I spent a lot of time jammed in narrow hallways trying to figure out where the rest of the party was.  but the crowd was great, for the most part.  could have done without the wannabe ganstas trying to grope me, but that's just oakland.  I live there -- I'm used to it.  I also wasn't aware that there wouldn't be any water sold there, so I had to leave right after I arrived to walk down to the corner store to get a bottle.  otherworld had cold water available for free, which is very cool, but they didn't have any containers with lids to put it in.  the next time I'll know to bring my own bottle.  
 
the biggest downside for me was the music itself.  it was way too down tempo in the main room for the 3-1/2 hours that I was there.  I wasn't familiar with meat beat manifesto so I wasn't sure what to expect.  I really enjoyed the audio/visual show - very impressive, but I felt like I was at a performance art show and not a rave.  I wanted to dance, and the music wasn't consistent enough for me.  it was very interesting and I enjoyed it, don't get me wrong.  but....  for someone who is geared up to dance hard the down-tempo stops and starts were frustrating.  my friends (my ride) grew really bored during meat beat's set so we ended up leaving towards the end of it.  that was a bummer for me - I missed forest green's set which is what I really came to see.  I did countless loops around the place (though the other three rooms that I was able to find) looking for my groove.  it was nowhere to be found.  
 
so I guess what I'm trying to say is that I can understand why some people would not have a good time at this party.  don't be too hard on them.  otherworld did a great job....  it all just boils down to a matter of personal taste.  this party fit with some people's, didn't fit with others.  it's as simple as that.  you can't really trash someone for not liking the same kind of music you do - we're all entitled to our preferences.  there were lots of great things about this party, and I had a good time overall.  the music just wasn't hittin' it for me.  I enjoyed and appreciated the technicality of it, but I couldn't do what I came to do -- dance my ass off.

cheers, 
susan

"J.C." <dougm@kzsu.stanford.edu> wrote:
Yup!! Thanks for a great time!

As Marco said, the MBM set was amazing. The mixing of visuals and audio
(as well as the audio FROM the visuals with the audio of the set) was
off the hook. (Looping a drum line, or a KEYBOARD line, from some dude
playing in a demo video or concert footage and mixing that audio in.
Damn. Try that one at home.)

The Fingermonster set was done amazingly.

Forest Green/Mochipet, Praxis: Yum!!

And of course, free water and food definitely help to nourish the raver
body.

As for Sideshow Bob's take on things, he might want to look in to
parties in L.A., as it sounds like that scene is likely more his thing.
Or if he wants a hookup with some promoters in Vegas, he can probably
pursue that and find his kind of vibe there too. But OW, that was
SF-style.

I started the OW evening off probably freaking Tala out a bit with the
devil/jesus bit (hesitated a bit before getting into the shuttle) and I
ended the OW evening by freaking out a few of the street people I was
talking with for 2 or 3 hours at the 12th st bart station (finally
hopped on the bart around 10.)

P.S. on the MBM era tip: Whatever happened to Consolidated?

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Thanks to OW for a SLAMMING Halloween!!

Yea, I guess if you were looking for an all out pounding set to bug on, Meat 
Beat wouldn't have been your thing. I for one kind of liked the 
rollercoaster ride they took us all on. Sometimes my little legs just can't 
hack dancing for 2 or 3 hourds solid, so the little breaks and ambient 
pieces were a welcome thing.

Glad to hear that despite the fact that you couldn't find your groove you 
still had a good time, and you appreciated the work that had been put into 
the event. That says a lot about you...willing to find the good in a 
situation you might not have been totally pleased with.

I guess I'm always so impressed with Otherworld events, cuz they really go 
all out, and bring a variety of sounds/vibes together that you just don't 
ordinarily see at a party. You get a chance to be exposed to more than just 
the basic house, trance, techno, breaks, D&B formula.

And whether or not you liked Meat Beat Manifesto - you witnessed a slice of 
electronic music history happening in someone's living space. Simply 
amazing.

> situation you might not have been totally pleased with.
>
> I guess I'm always so impressed with Otherworld events, cuz they really g=
o
> all out, and bring a variety of sounds/vibes together that you just don't
> ordinarily see at a party. You get a chance to be exposed to more than
> just
> the basic house, trance, techno, breaks, D&B formula.
>
> And whether or not you liked Meat Beat Manifesto - you witnessed a slice
> of
> electronic music history happening in someone's living space. Simply
> amazing.
>
>
> >From: Susan Williams <susanmwill@yahoo.com>
> >To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
> >Subject: Re: [sfraves] Thanks to OW for a SLAMMING Halloween!!
> >Date: Mon, 31 Oct 2005 12:11:04 -0800 (PST)
> >
> >I'm a long time lurker and sometimes poster. I just had to throw in my
> .02
> >about this party......
> >
> >first off, let me start by saying this was my first otherworld party.
> I've
> >heard about their parties for a long time and wanted to check them out,
> but
> >for one reason or another timing has never worked out right until
> saturday
> >night. needless to say I was excited about it and had high expectations.
> >
> >on the whole, otherworld delivered. the place looked great. loved the
> >graveyard setup in the main room. it was a bit confusing to navigate the
> >hallways (in fact I think I missed one of the music areas entirely
> because
> >I couldn't find it). maybe next time some signs pointing the way to the
> >different rooms would help. or bigger signs if there were signs posted.
> >seems like I spent a lot of time jammed in narrow hallways trying to
> figure
> >out where the rest of the party was. but the crowd was great, for the
> most
> >part. could have done without the wannabe ganstas trying to grope me, bu=
t
> >that's just oakland. I live there -- I'm used to it. I also wasn't aware
> >that there wouldn't be any water sold there, so I had to leave right
> after
> >I arrived to walk down to the corner store to get a bottle. otherworld
> had
> >cold water available for free, which is very cool, but they didn't have
> any
> >containers with lids to put it in. the next time I'll know to bring my
> own
> >bottle.
> >
> >the biggest downside for me was the music itself. it was way too down
> >tempo in the main room for the 3-1/2 hours that I was there. I wasn't
> >familiar with meat beat manifesto so I wasn't sure what to expect. I
> >really enjoyed the audio/visual show - very impressive, but I felt like =
I
> >was at a performance art show and not a rave. I wanted to dance, and the
> >music wasn't consistent enough for me. it was very interesting and I
> >enjoyed it, don't get me wrong. but.... for someone who is geared up to
> >dance hard the down-tempo stops and starts were frustrating. my friends
> >(my ride) grew really bored during meat beat's set so we ended up leavin=
g
> >towards the end of it. that was a bummer for me - I missed forest green'=
s
> >set which is what I really came to see. I did countless loops around the
> >place (though the other three rooms that I was able to find) looking for
> my
> >groove. it was nowhere to be found.
> >
> >so I guess what I'm trying to say is that I can understand why some
> people
> >would not have a good time at this party. don't be too hard on them.
> >otherworld did a great job.... it all just boils down to a matter of
> >personal taste. this party fit with some people's, didn't fit with
> others.
> > it's as simple as that. you can't really trash someone for not liking
> >the same kind of music you do - we're all entitled to our preferences.
> >there were lots of great things about this party, and I had a good time
> >overall. the music just wasn't hittin' it for me. I enjoyed and
> >appreciated the technicality of it, but I couldn't do what I came to do
> --
> >dance my ass off.

> >cheers,

Lollerskates.
 One of the best parties of the year, despite being savage drunk. The OW
venue is awesome, the price was $15 at the fucking door, and its been an ag=
e
since I was at an event where people seemed to be genuinely super-social an=
d
friendly without being off their tits on drugs.
 No cavity searches. No fights. No shitheels. Free water. Food. Mighty
drinks for three dolla. If you were expecting a 'rave' it wasn't quite that
in the modern incarnation of the term (replete with candy kids and
lightshows, although I saw a couple of those)... but it was a great party,
great crowd, bangin music.
 MBM was kinda... ehh, tho. Not to talk shit, but... I was expecting -- if
not totally danceable -- at least some genuinely trippy crazy music. The
breaks upstairs were sick all night, however! Winnie the Pooh threw it down
hardstyle.
 kthxbye.
 PS: Don@Otherworld? Bueller? Can u hit me up private-like, if you're on
this list?
 srg

I'm sorry I came across as condescending. I think it's just the way I'm
wired. :) I am not here to discourage anyone from making positive changes i=
n
their life.
 What I was trying to convey, here, is that NA doesn't really seem to be
doing my friend any good. I can't explain why -- he isn't doing drugs, at
the moment, but I'm sure that has everything to do with him being piss
tested every two weeks, and almost nothing to do with any spiritual
revelations he has had in NA. From my conversations with him, he is growing
up and learning a lot -- but, again, this has to do with him not gobbling a
dozen tabs of ecstasy a week, not any higher power or meetings.
 At present, he is still blaming his parents for his problems, rather than
accepting responsibility for his life and his actions and his choices. He
says things like "I''ve learned to cope" and upon being pressed tells me, "=
I
cope by not dealing with it." He says he's learning something, but it seems
like all he's learned to do is feel sorry for himself.
 I visited him, once, right after one of his meetings... it's one of the
only times I can see him, in between check-ins with his parole officer. A
brief interaction -- paired with some idle reminiscing wrt previous
friendships and relationships with people in/going through AA -- gave me th=
e
impression that these people have not grown up. I don't advocate growing up=
,
mind you, but these cats had not grown up in any of the important ways. The=
y
were older, held down jobs, et cetera ... NA turned them into productive
members of society. It did not let them answer the questions they needed to
answer to mature and evolve as human beings. A quick fix, a patch on a flat
tire.-
 How can I summate here? While never having experienced this stuff first
hand, it seems like 'it works'. It works insofar as it can keep you away
from your addictions and give you something new to obsess over. It cannot
take you to the 'next step' in which you move beyond the need to have
something external to yourself to feel good.
 I don't know what that step is. I'm sure by the time my alcoholism totally
consumes me i'll be ready to try just about anything. Hopefully I'll have
more insights by then.
 sean

 On 10/30/05, Amber Leahey <princess_leahey@yahoo.com> wrote:
>
> I'm sorry, but as someone who has lived with both parents and step parent=
s
> being major alcoholics and drug addicts I have to respond to your
> condescending tone. It is because of AA and NA that my step father is sob=
er
> today and that I am able to have a wonderful positive relationship with h=
im.
> AA does not profess to "cure" you. It does however encourage you to discu=
ss
> your reasons and problems in addiction and to face your own bullshit. The=
re
> really isn't anyone in there that thinks they have the answer...they all =
are
> addicts and trying to help eachother. It's admitting that you are human a=
nd
> can have a substance dependency. Addiction is not a matter of you not hav=
ing
> enough will power and there are plenty of atheists in the program. It
> doesn't work for everyone and there are breakthrough drugs coming around =
to
> help addiction but those are years into the future. My friend recently we=
nt
> into AA and he said it was more of a spiritual awakening than he had ever
> experienced in his life
> quite the opposite of "giving up his spiritual quest." I don't know if
> you've ever been on the verge of total addiction and losing everything
> important to you but I think at that point you might consider surrenderin=
g
> to a higher power. AA does not work for everyone but I would encourage
> anyone who is battling addiction to at least try it and if that doesn't w=
ork
> seek other help. Whatever works for you!

Subject: Re: [sfraves] AA meetings?

Well, I can see how you'd have the impression of N/A & A/A that you do. I 
myself was forced to go when I got arrested for posession of paraphenalia 
back in VA a couple of years ago, and I thought that it was a complete waste 
of time.

Now - before I go offending anyone with my OPINION of these services, let me 
preface this by saying, I know that it DOES help people. And when you're 
dealing with addictions, sometimes a method like this is necessary to deal 
with the situation.

That being said, I tend to think that nine times out of ten it does nothing 
but give people a new addiction. I have seen so many people that have gone 
through these things either become "12 Step Junkies" or all of a sudden 
"find religion". I wish these programs would focus less on the "god will 
give you strength" approach, and more on the "find strength within yourself" 
approach. It's almost as if they say to you "All your problems will 
magically go away if you surrender to god's will and come to these 
meetings". And I dunno - when I quit smoking, I quit cold turkey. I gave 
away a full pack of smokes. I have known other folks with bad meth habits 
that just STOPPED. No meetings, no self help books, no bibles, no Jesus. I 
fully believe that change ocmes from within. You have to WANT to stop what 
you're doing. Until that happens - you can go to meetings till the cows come 
home, and you'll still be left with your addiction.

I also went to some of the "non religious" meetings after I got sick of 
having to pray and talk about god every time I went to a meeting, and while 
the religious aspect was lessened, it still wasn't fully absent. Go figure 
when 90% of these things are held at churchs, lol.

I honestly think that a better approach would be for people with addictions 
to get real counseling from a phychiatrist or an addiction specialist of 
some kind. Someone whose approach isn't 1st to try and convert you or make 
you feel like some helpless little puppet of "god".

But if people would rather OD on Jesus than on booze or illicit substances, 
I guess that's up to them...

>doing my friend any good. I can't explain why -- he isn't doing drugs, at
>the moment, but I'm sure that has everything to do with him being piss
>tested every two weeks, and almost nothing to do with any spiritual
>revelations he has had in NA. From my conversations with him, he is growing
>up and learning a lot -- but, again, this has to do with him not gobbling a
>dozen tabs of ecstasy a week, not any higher power or meetings.
>  At present, he is still blaming his parents for his problems, rather than
>accepting responsibility for his life and his actions and his choices. He
>says things like "I''ve learned to cope" and upon being pressed tells me, 
>"I
>cope by not dealing with it." He says he's learning something, but it seems
>like all he's learned to do is feel sorry for himself.
>  I visited him, once, right after one of his meetings... it's one of the
>only times I can see him, in between check-ins with his parole officer. A
>brief interaction -- paired with some idle reminiscing wrt previous
>friendships and relationships with people in/going through AA -- gave me 
>the
>impression that these people have not grown up. I don't advocate growing 
>up,
>mind you, but these cats had not grown up in any of the important ways. 
>They
>were older, held down jobs, et cetera ... NA turned them into productive
>members of society. It did not let them answer the questions they needed to
>answer to mature and evolve as human beings. A quick fix, a patch on a flat
>tire.-
>  How can I summate here? While never having experienced this stuff first
>hand, it seems like 'it works'. It works insofar as it can keep you away
>from your addictions and give you something new to obsess over. It cannot
>take you to the 'next step' in which you move beyond the need to have
>something external to yourself to feel good.
>  I don't know what that step is. I'm sure by the time my alcoholism 
>totally
>consumes me i'll be ready to try just about anything. Hopefully I'll have
>more insights by then.

would have suggested that while MBM was playing that one of the other,
larger rooms be playing something in the 120-140 BPM range, perhaps
something with a 4-4 structure, that people (no matter what they are
on and no matter what music they are into) can dance to.

too god damn hot to dance in.  :(

"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path 
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and 
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, 
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and 
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can 
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and 
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond 
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative 
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of 
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will 
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

yeah, I totally missed the whole upstairs section.  :o(  it was my first time at the otherworld warehouse and I didn't even know about the upstairs.  I only found 4 rooms - one near the door, the two that were next to each other (one of those had MBM), and the back area that had a PA system for a live band.  I made a few loops looking for other areas, but gave up after a while and just stayed in the room where MBM was.  

and yeah, I thought it was downtempo music in that room while I was there.  I'm not saying it was bad -- it was just a bit slower than what I was looking for.  as soon as I would kind of get in to a beat it would drop out or stop.  I found it a little frustrating, so eventually I stopped trying to dance and just enjoyed the show.  

overall I thought the party was really fun.  it was great to see so many people in the spirit and dressed up.  the people made it for me - they were great (excluding that moderately scary group of guys who tried to grab me every time I went into the hallway - poo on all of you.  reaching out and grabbing is not the way to pick up a girl.)  my problems with the music really don't reflect poorly on otherworld or anything, it just has to do with my preferences.  and I did enjoy what I heard even if I couldn't figure out how to dance to it.

Bam <invibe@gmail.com> wrote:
downtempo in that much of what MBM was playing was in the 80-110 BPM range.

not your typical 120-140 breakbeat, house, 4-4 range.

which I can see some EDM dancing lovers not being too keen on. i
would have suggested that while MBM was playing that one of the other,
larger rooms be playing something in the 120-140 BPM range, perhaps
something with a 4-4 structure, that people (no matter what they are
on and no matter what music they are into) can dance to.

i personally had no complaints! other than my Pooh bear costume being
too god damn hot to dance in. :(

-b

On 10/31/05, Sean Casey wrote:

Yeah, these guys tried their damnedest to remove my deck but couldn't. 
So they took the remote control instead. The ipod was a friends, and it 
was in the glovebox, but the car was clean and nothing was visible. They 
even went through the sunglass holder, and tried pulling back some of 
the carpet to get to the deck from the back. Talk about time on your hands.

They also took about 8 pairs of my friends shoes that were in the trunk. 
Excitement. I was amused they looked at my amp, left it and took the sub.

But then again, if you're in that neighborhood, it is pretty obvious by 
the amount of people what is going on. The guy working at the liquor 
store asked me if the party was getting packed.

my thoughts to otherworlds halloween bash!!!
 
i thought i wasn't gonna have fun cuz my date for the night cancelled on me...
so i kinda was hesistant in going by myself and i was hella bummed out...even thou i was gonna meet delia and her hot date there...thou still, going stag to a shindig isn't my style...
 
anywho...i still went and all i have to say is YUMMMMEEEEEE!!!!!!!
 
my goddess!!! this event was absolutely the yumeeeeeeeeest with extra fudge on top and cherries!!!!! i havent had so much fun since pandomoneum...
i give great props to everyone at ow...
 
i parked my car at the parking place and rode the shuttle, really nice driver...he waited for me to park my car and didnt leave me there all by my lonesome...i was really impressed with ow's shuttle service...
 
as to ow, each room was hot!!! 
 
i loved marco and bam's tag team set...it kicked assssss!!!! sweeet!!!!got me dancing lots...
 
the dnb room was smokin hot as well...danced and danced and danced...
 
the techno room, god dam..this dj, i didnt get her name but she was playing hard techo..and it was fucken delicious...it brought back hardcore raver memories..i got chills running up my spine just listening to her set...
 
forest was off the hook...
 
i caught other dj's sets as well..thou i can't remember their names..anywho...it was all good vibes and flavor in the air...
 
lots of people,saw chel-c,sean, matt & jessie..catharisis was also there..pacific sound crew was there..my friend kreshno from the dnb scene was there..delia and her hot date..woohoo..go delia...
 
hey phillip was that you i tripped with my foot, hehehe...
 
so over all i i had a blast..i danced and i drank till they ran outta vodka..boohoo..then i drank whisky,hehehe...makes me still wonder how the heck i drove myself home.. anywho...yeah...
 
thanks ow!!! for a blissful night...
 
can't wait for your next event...
 
kudos...
~adriana
